<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iceland     09-28 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iceland,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Center-Left Government Takes Office, Devalues Krona</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new center-left government headed by
former Prime Minister Steingrimur Hermannsson took office
Wednesday, enacting an immediate price-wage freeze and devaluating
the Icelandic krona.
   The government, in a statement issued immediately after assuming
power, announced a 3 percent devaluation of the krona, a wage
freeze until mid-February and a price freeze until the end of
February in a bid to stave off Iceland's acute economic problems.
   Thorsteinn Palsson's 15-month center-right coalition government
resigned last week after failing to agree on economic policy.
   Hermannsson's nine-member Cabinet groups his centrist
Progressive Party, the Social Democratic Party and the leftist
People's Alliance. It was sworn in by President Vigdis
Finnbogadottir following negotiations among the political parties
without an election being called.
   Hermannsson said his government's top goal was to bring down the
annual rate of inflation from its present level of 25 percent to
around five percent by the middle of next year.
   The fishing industry, accounting for two-thirds of this North
Atlantic island nation's foreign exchange earnings, has been
especially hard-hit by the crisis and is reported near bankruptcy.
   The fishing industry has demanded a sharp devaluation of the
krona to cut the price of its exports, making them more
competitive. But a currency devaluation automatically pushes up the
price of imports from abroad.
   One U.S. dollar was worth 46.76 kronur immediately before
Wednesday's devaluation, the third this year.
   Hermannsson was foreign minister in Palsson's government, which
took office in June 1987.
   Under a NATO agreement, this nation of 250,000 people is the
site of a major U.S. air base at Keflavik, 25 miles southwest of
the capital Reykjavik, guarding strategic sea routes.
</TEXT>
