<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MutilationRapist-Suit 1stLd-Writethru a0777 09-28 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mutilation Rapist-Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0777,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rape Victim Drops Efforts To Collect $2.56 Million From Destitute
Attacker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 11 through end with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
Singleton telling police he does not plan to stay in Pinole, Calif.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rape victim whose attacker cut off her
arms with an ax has reluctantly given up efforts to collect a $2.56
million judgment from the man after he revealed he is nearly broke,
her lawyer said.
   And yet another community is trying to get rid of convicted
rapist Lawrence Singleton, who set off a public furor in several
northern California communities where he attempted to live after
being released from prison earlier this year.
   Mary Vincent won a $2.56 million civil judgment in a Nevada
court against Singleton earlier this year over the 1978 attack.
   However, her attorney, Mark Edwards of Tustin, a Los Angeles
suburb, said Monday that Singleton told him during a
deposition-taking in a San Francisco hotel last weekend that his
only income is a $600-per-month Social Security check.
   Singleton has only about $200 in the bank, is unemployed, is
disabled by kidney problems, owns no property, and has not sold the
movie, book or television rights to his story, Edwards said.
   ```I guess I am going to have to give up on collecting this
judgment for the time being, but in my heart I am not going to let
it go,''' Edwards quoted Ms. Vincent as saying.
   Ms. Vincent is married and lives in the Pacific Northwest. She
was 15 when Singleton picked her up while she was hitchhiking and
raped her and hacked off her forearms.
   Edwards said he was contacted informally by Singleton's
attorneys who offered to set up the deposition hearing.
   Edwards promised not to reveal information about the deposition
for at least 48 hours after it was held, to allow Singleton time to
return to his out-of-state home. He also agreed not to reveal where
Singleton is living.
   But in Pinole, 30 miles east of San Francisco, Police Chief Ted
Barnes told the city council Monday night that Singleton had been
living there for several days.
   ``He has some personal matters to take care of, and once he's
taken care of them, he says he's moving on,'' Barnes said Tuesday.
   Before police learned that Singleton did not plan to stay in the
town, Mayor Phil Green had said, ``I don't want to have this guy in
our town for 30 seconds.'' He promised Singleton would be banished
``if we have to call in the National Guard.''
   Councilman Roy Swearingen also had called for Singleton to move
on, but cautioned the community not to overreact.
   ``This man is hated by everyone,'' he said. ``I'm concerned that
there will be some kind of violent act.''
   Earlier this year, Singleton had been living in Tampa, Fla.
</TEXT>
