<HEAD>Sex Offender Ordered To Wear Sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sex offender carried her sentence out of a
courtroom: A sign reading, ``I am a child molester.''
   Julie Lynn Guptill-Gilbert, 20, will have to wear the sign when
she goes out in public, although she did not have to wear it out of
the King County Courthouse on Tuesday.
   She pleaded guilty in March to two counts of communicating with
a minor for immoral purposes in incidents involving two 4-year-old
girls when Ms. Guptill-Gilber was working at a preschool in Bothell.
   At the time, Superior Court Judge Warren Chan gave her the
choice of wearing the sign for 60 days or spending 30 days in jail.
She chose the sign.
   Ms. Guptill-Gilbert said nothing at a hearing Tuesday, when she
was given the foot-long, 4-inch wide, county-made sign.
   She will have to wear it for only 33 days because of time
already served.
   Her sentence amounts to house arrest because she plans to stay
with relatives in Monroe, said county prosecutor's spokesman Dan
Donohue.
