<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Thatcher     09-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says West Will Benefit If Perestroika Succeeds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
believes it is ``in the Western interest'' for Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev to succeed in restructuring the Soviet Union's
economy and increasing social freedoms.
   In an interview published in Wednesday's New York Times,
Thatcher said that what she likes about Gorbachev's approach ``is
the idea that enlarging the liberty and responsibility will give
you the greater economic prosperity.''
   Thatcher said that when she visited the Soviet Union last year,
``I had to decide whether I thought it was in the Western interest
that he succeed. And I think it is.''
   Of Gorbachev's efforts, she said: ``It's a great, massive
turnaround, where you have in fact been saying to people for 70
years, you don't do anything unless you've got permission, to turn
round and say, well now, look you've got to do quite a lot on your
own initiative.''
   Thatcher said Britain would support the changes in the Soviet
Union ``in every way we can without interfering.'' She cited an
increase in East-West contacts and in joint ventures between Soviet
state enterprises and British companies.
   But she also said that this uncertain period of change in the
Eastern bloc ``requires total Western unity and preparedness.''
   She said Britain would insist that the NATO alliance modernize
conventional and nuclear weapons in Western Europe.
   Thatcher said she hadn't watched the debate between presidential
candidates George Bush and Michael Dukakis.
   ``I'm not going to get involved in your election problems for
very obvious reasons,'' she said.
</TEXT>
