<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Elections Bjt   09-28 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Elections, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Elections Loom Large Over Congressional Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the 100th Congress rushes toward
adjournment, it finds itself increasingly tangled in election-year
politics and the presidential campaigns of George Bush and Michael
Dukakis.
   Even the tamest bill can find itself held hostage to political
fortune and partisan campaigning.
   Proposals that have languished for years suddenly have new life
breathed into them by lawmakers with an eye on politics, home
district polls and opponents' press releases.
   No single issue more sums up the election-year mood of Congress
than the drug bill passed last week by the House and now pending in
the Senate. As Bush and Dukakis accused each other of being soft on
drug dealers and crime, Republicans and Democrats in the House
scrambled madly, clamoring to lead the charge in a War on Drugs.
   The vote was a whopping 375-30 for a package of anti-drug
provisions that even sponsors say may be unconstitutional. ``If
this bill becomes law, Americans will be less free,'' said Rep. Don
Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the House civil rights subcommittee.
   But another Democrat, Charles Rangel of New York, expressed the
feelings of the majority. While the bill is flawed, he said, ``at
least all of us can go home'' and say ``we responded to our
constituents and the nation.''
   With all 435 House seats and 33 Senate seats up on Election Day,
going home is just what Congress wants to do, and as soon as
possible.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas says Congress could
adjourn this week if it would simply pass the pending appropriation
bills and a few other relatively noncontroversial issues.
   Dole said many of the late-blooming issues should be left to the
presidential election campaign and its winner. ``We should
determine precisely what Governor Dukakis and the vice president
have in mind on these issues,'' Dole said. ``We will have plenty of
time next year to address each of them.''
   But Republicans and Democrats alike each have a political agenda
that could keep them in Washington well into October. Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., is telling colleagues to plan
on weekend work and a mid-October escape.
   What's keeping Congress in town? In addition to some money
bills, a bipartisan overhaul of the welfare system and other
issues, at least four partisan fights are running out the
election-year clock:
   _Minimum Wage. For five days, the Senate debated a proposal to
raise the minimum wage. The minimum wage hasn't been increased
since 1981, but Democrats brought this plan to the floor in the
final weeks of the two-year-long 100th Congress. Republicans
filibustered, saying the Democrats wouldn't get action on the
minimum wage unless they allowed Senate votes on two dozen Reagan
judicial nominations languishing in committee.
   Byrd pulled the minimum wage bill down, with both sides crying
dirty politics.
   Dole complained that Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman
of the Labor and Human Resources Committee, was unleashing a flood
of liberal social legislation just before the elections.
   ``How many more bills are we going to get from Kennedy's
committee?'' Dole asked. He got his answer a few minutes later,
when the Senate turned to another Labor Committee proposal:
   _Family Leave. This bill would guarantee at least 10 weeks of
unpaid, job-protected leave to seriously ill workers and to those
with newborn, newly adopted or seriously ill children. Dukakis
supports the plan; Bush says women shouldn't have to worry about
getting their jobs back after maternity leave but hasn't yet issued
a detailed proposal.
   _Taxes. This bill makes numerous technical corrections in the
big 1986 tax overhaul and also contains several tax breaks and the
relatively minor tax increases needed to pay for them.
   Harmless?
   In another year, it could be approved quickly and quietly. But
this time, each side has election-year jitters.
   The White House said this week it will support an amendment to
the bill that would deny tax exemptions to hospitals and clinics
that routinely perform abortions, guaranteeing a partisan fight
when and if it hits the floor.
   On the other side, Byrd is afraid Republicans might accuse
Democrats of raising taxes if they pass the bill.
   ``I'm just suspicious of this White House,'' Byrd said Tuesday.
He said he can see Reagan administration officials complaining
loudly, ```There they go, raising taxes. There the Democrats go.'''
   As a result, neither Democrats nor Republicans are going
anywhere until the need to campaign at home overcomes the urge to
campaign in Washington.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Gould has been chief of The Associated Press
congressional staff since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
