<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0941EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxBill Bjt   09-28 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Bill, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Election Politics Snag Tax Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate tax bill that for two years has been
gathering everything but momentum is now hung up over fears that
President Reagan will accuse its backers of favoring higher taxes.
   In comparison with the giant 1986 tax overhaul legislation,
which shifted $125 billion in taxes from individuals to
corporations over five years, this bill is peanuts, with a
three-year price tag of $2.3 billion.
   It was launched in the summer of 1986 just to correct errors and
clear up ambiguities in the new tax law. It since has become the
vehicle for dozens of other tax provisions whose beneficiaries
include farmers, workers who receive education assistance from
their employers, and taxpayers involved in disputes with the
Internal Revenue Service.
   To pay for those benefits, the bill would raise taxes by $2.3
billion, with most of the money coming from corporations.
   The Reagan administration has expressed support for some
provisions in the bill and reservations about others. But that is
not good enough for Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, who has
implied the Senate might not even consider the measure this year
unless the administration clears up the confusion.
   ``I'm just suspicious of this White House,'' Byrd told
colleagues Tuesday. He said he fears that once Congress passes the
bill, administration officials will pick up one of President
Reagan's campaign cries of the past: ``There they go raising taxes.
There the Democrats go.''
   ``It would be well if we could get some clear, unequivocal,
indubitably plain, well-understood statement from the White
House,'' Byrd said. ``I'm just concerned the White House will stand
on the sidelines and attack Congress on the tax bill.''
   Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas was asked if the White
House will respond to Byrd's request.
   ``I think they have already responded,'' he replied. ``They
would support the Senate bill.''
   But Byrd said, ``We haven't gotten anything clear and
unambiguous from the White House.''
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who is managing the bill, said he is
convinced the White House supports it. ``They agree with the
revenue-raisers,'' he told reporters.
   The latest administration pronouncement on the bill, which came
from the White House Office of Management and Budget, added another
complication. It said the administration supports a proposed
amendment that would deny a tax exemption to any hospital or clinic
that performs abortions when the life of the mother is not
threatened.
   The OMB letter states: ``The federal government should not
subsidize abortion through an exemption in the tax code.''
   Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, Republican manager of the tax bill
and an opponent of federal restrictions on abortions, said he feels
confident that amendment can be defeated. He called the OMB
endorsement ``a throwaway to the right-to-lifers.''
   In 1986, when the tax overhaul was being written, Sens. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., and William Armstrong, R-Colo., blocked action on
that bill with a similar amendment. The obstacle was removed after
Reagan personally pleaded with the two senators, saying that while
he supported their goal, he feared the controversy could doom the
tax bill.
   Packwood, seeking to assure Byrd, said, ``The White House would
sign the Senate bill as it came out of the Senate Finance
Committee.'' But any bill that moved toward the House version would
be vetoed, he added.
   In comparison with the $2.3 billion cost of the Senate bill, the
House version would cost $7 billion over three years.
   Among dozens of provisions in the Senate bill are those to free
farmers and some other businesses from paying the federal tax on
diesel fuel used for off-road purposes; extend expiring tax
benefits for research, employer-financed education and legal aid,
and assistance for first-time home buyers; allow freelance writers
to deduct expenses before their works start making money; assure a
deduction for football fans who give to their alma mater and, in
return, are assured the privilege of buying season tickets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
