<DOCNO> AP880928-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WelfareOverhaul Bjt   09-28 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Overhaul, Bjt,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welfare Overhaul Receives Bipartisan Backing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans alike are praising a
sweeping welfare overhaul plan that would require some recipients
to work for their benefits, despite complaints from an advocacy
group that the measure would ``drop a bomb on the poor people of
America.''
   The compromise plan, approved Tuesday by House and Senate
negotiators, is billed as the most extensive welfare overhaul in 50
years. It immediately won praise from members of both parties
including President Reagan and Democratic vice presidential nominee
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   While workfare provisions aimed at welfare mothers provoked the
most dispute, the bill also aims to help welfare recipients help
themselves through a combination of training, education, support
services and stepped-up child support collections.
   House and Senate negotiators formally approved the compromise,
in the works all summer, on a 35-8 vote Tuesday evening. All nine
senators voted yes. Each chamber must approve the compromise before
it goes to the White House.
   Reagan, returning to the White House from New York, said he was
``very happy'' with the five-year, $3.34 billion measure, which
contains the workfare requirement upon which his administration had
insisted.
   The president's chief of staff, Kenneth Duberstein, said, ``Our
indications ... are that in fact it is in fact a good, strong
workfare requirement, which would meet the president's test.''
   The Reagan administration succeeded in winning a 16-hour-a-week
workfare requirement for one adult in two-parent households
receiving welfare. The provision affects only about 7 percent of
the caseload, would not kick in until recipients had undergone an
intensive two-month job search, and is not effective until 1994.
But conservatives were jubilant despite the conditions.
   ``That work requirement is indeed the nose of the camel under
the tent,'' said Rep. Hank Brown, R-Colo. ``It is the beginning of
a different approach to welfare.''
   Deeply frustrated House opponents agreed with him, but branded
the requirement unfair to recipients and burdensome to states.
   ``It does not provide education or training to make welfare
recipients employable, and does not lead to permanent jobs,'' said
Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the Education and
Labor Committee. ``It is simply a punitive approach to forcing
people off the rolls.''
   Some House members also said mothers required to participate in
the work program would not receive sufficient child care help or
safety assurances under the bill. And they said people working off
their grants in public work programs could be paid the equivalent
of the minimum wage regardless of how much those working next to
them were making.
   But in the end many heeded the warning of Rep. Tom Downey,
D-N.Y., whose subcommittee had handled the original House welfare
bill, a much more lavish proposal costing twice as much as the
compromise.
   ``It's not as far as we'd like to go but it's as far as we're
going to get,'' Downey said, urging his colleagues not to pump up
welfare recipients with false hopes of a better bill to come.
   The conference chairmen expressed satisfaction with their
product.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, called the compromise ``far from perfect'' but
added, ``I am confident ... that the families who are trapped in
the cycle of poverty would tell us to give them a chance and pass
this bill.''
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said the bill
would improve America's economic status as well as people's lives.
``You can't be internationally competitive if you have the number
of people on welfare that we have today,'' he said during a
campaign stop in Detroit.
   The National Governors Association and the American Public
Welfare Association supported the bill, but the National Welfare
Rights and Reform Union claimed it would ``drop a bomb on the poor
people of America'' by forcing mothers to work.
   The current welfare system, Aid to Families with Dependent
Children, serves 3.7 million families that include 7 million
children. The federal government pays out about $8.5 billion a year
in cash benefits under AFDC, established in 1938 as part of the
Social Security system.
   In addition to the work requirement, key elements of the new
plan include:
   _$600 million in federal money for a new Job Opportunities and
Basic Skills program in its first year, rising gradually to $1.3
billion in 1995. States would design their own JOBS programs and
contribute matching money toward them.
   _Parents with children under age 3, or age 1 at state option,
would be exempt from JOBS participation. States would have to be
serving 20 percent of eligible participants by 1995. Up to 400,000
people a year will be helped nationwide.
   _JOBS participants would receive transportation and child care
help. Welfare parents working their way off the rolls would qualify
for a year of transitional child care and Medicaid benefits. Up to
475,000 people are expected to continue working because of the
transitional help.
   _The 23 states that do not offer welfare benefits to two-parent
households would have to do so for at least six months of each year
starting in fiscal 1991. That would add 65,000 families to the
rolls.
   _States would have to step up child support collections from
non-custodial parents, including tougher paternity determination
requirements and mandatory wage withholding upon the court award of
support payments.
   _The expense of the bill would be subsidized through a variety
of tax moves including reducing the dependent care credit for
higher income people and making permanent the Internal Revenue
Service's debt collection program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
