<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FamilyLeave     09-28 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Leave,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Considering Job-Protected Medical, Parental Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has said ``yes'' to requiring plant
closing notifications and ``no'' to raising the minimum wage. Now
it is weighing whether businesses should be forced to offer
employees job-protected medical and parental leave.
   The proposed leave act would require employers to offer at least
10 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave to workers with newborn,
newly adopted or seriously ill children, or who are seriously ill
themselves. Companies with fewer than 50 workers would be exempt.
   The Reagan administration said Tuesday that employers should be
encouraged _ but not required _ to respond to family needs of this
kind, and Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., said he would propose a tax
incentive amendment reflecting that aim.
   Pending when the Senate shut down Tuesday was an amendment to
tighten laws and stiffen penalties in the areas of child
pornography and obscenity.
   The leave act sponsored by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
required at least 13 weeks of medical leave and exempted only firms
of under 20 when it first came to the floor. Dodd on Tuesday
offered the substitute to reduce the leave time and the number of
companies involved, saying he was particularly concerned about big,
impersonal businesses where bosses are not familiar with their
workers' lives.
   The revisions, approved by voice vote, mean only 5 percent of
U.S. companies would be affected and it would cost them $2.67 per
year per covered employee _ a total of about $160 million, Dodd
said.
   ``All this legislation says is that for 10 weeks every two
years, if you're confronted with a crisis, you don't lose your
job,'' Dodd said. ``I don't consider that to be an unreasonable
idea. I think it's human decency. I think it's common sense.''
   Congressional Democrats, after a protracted battle, managed to
force the administration's hand and enact a bill requiring
companies to notify workers in advance of mass layoffs or plant
shutdowns. But the same forces, trying to raise the minimum wage,
were defeated this week by a conservative-led filibuster in the
Senate.
   Many moderates and conservatives called parental leave an
important benefit but fretted about the burden it would place on
employers.
   ``I have grave concerns about the negative effects on our
economy'' that the bill could cause, said Sen. Pete Domenici,
R-N.M. ``We can feel real concern for those who want to spend time
with a seriously ill child. I have eight children myself and I'm
inclined to support some kind of compromise on this bill.''
   Cochran branded the requirement ``a very drastic departure from
current practice, and it is not really necessary in trying to deal
with the needs of a diverse and changing workforce. ... We should
all be concerned about the impact it may have on other benefits
that may be available.''
   The Reagan administration issued a policy statement Tuesday
saying the president's advisers would recommend a veto of the Dodd
bill in its present form.
   ``The administration would support a proposal for parental leave
which encourages employers and employees to agree on the leave
policy best suited to them,'' the statement said. ``The
administration would support a bill that promotes the adjustment of
work-family conflicts by providing incentives to employers to
provide leave to their employees during reasonable periods at the
birth or adoption of a child.''
</TEXT>
