<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bendectin     09-28 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bendectin,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Ruling Against Bendectin Damage Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury relied on scientifically invalid expert
testimony when it decided that the anti-nausea drug Bendectin
caused birth defects, an appeals court said in upholding a judge's
earlier decision.
   The decision by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here is the
first to validate a lower court decision setting aside a verdict in
a Bendectin case on the ground that it was not supported by valid
evidence.
   The three-judge panel said Tuesday that U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson properly ruled that the testimony of an
expert witness for the plaintiff contradicted ``nearly universal
scientific consensus.''
   In 1986, Jackson set aside the jury's award of $1.16 million to
Carita Richardson, a 10-year-old Washington girl who was born
without a right leg and with a deformed left arm and hand.
   The appellate panel concluded that the expert's opinion ``lacks
adequate basis and therefore, whether viewed alone or in
conjunction with those of other experts, did not provide the
`substantial probative evidence' that would require us to leave the
verdict as the jury rendered it.''
   The decision ``could portend a little more judicial intervention
on scientific questions,'' said Walter Olson, who heads the civil
justice reform project of the Manhattan Institute, a conservative
think tank in New York.
   In recent years, trial judges have faced a ``spiral of expert
witnesses in which each side will bring in a witness who is as
slanted toward their side as they can get away with,'' Olson said.
   ``The jury is left with the bewildering choice between experts
who appear to disagree on every possible point and make it look as
if it is in dispute in the scientific world when it's not quite as
up in the air,'' he said.
   The ruling also was hailed by Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc.,
which made the drug for nearly 20 years.
   The decision ``further emphasizes the importance of focusing on
the scientific as well as the emotional aspect of these cases,''
said company spokesman Bill Donaldson.
   Merrell Dow contends that the drug, which was prescribed to
treat morning sickness among pregnant women, is safe. But it
stopped producing the drug in 1983 in the wake of mounting lawsuits.
   ``The circumstances of the case are tragic and Carita
Richardson's plight evokes the utmost sympathy,'' Circuit Judge
Spotswood Robinson wrote in an opinion joined by Circuit Judges
Laurence Silberman and Douglas H. Ginsburg.
   ``But in a case such as this it not only is appropriate, but
indeed imperative that the court remain vigilant to ensure that
neither emotion nor confusion has supplanted reason.''
   While ``expert witnesses are indispensable in a case such as
this,'' the court said, judges are not forced to ``accept
uncritically any sort of opinion espoused by an expert merely
because his credentials render him qualified to testify.''
   Jackson is only the second judge to set aside a jury's verdict
against the manufacturer over Bendectin. The other trial judge, in
District of Columbia Superior Court, was overruled by another
appeals court, which is considering whether to order a new trial.
   The company has won 22 verdicts from juries that found the drug
was safe. One of those verdicts was rendered in a joint trial of
1,150 claims against the drug.
   Donaldson said the company is trying to overturn four verdicts
that the drug caused birth defects. Those include a $95 million
jury award here last year that was subsequently reduced to $20
million. The jury in that case heard testimony from the same expert
who testified in the Richardson case.
   Barry Nace, the Richardson's lawyer who also won the $95 million
verdict, called Tuesday's decision a ``bad joke.''
   Nace, who vowed to appeal the ruling, said it was based on
political rather than legal reasoning.
   ``The courts have been looking for some way to get rid of these
Bendectin cases and the hundreds of children who have lawsuits they
want to file against the company,'' he said.
   Nace said the court ignored the testimony of seven other experts
who also testified that Bendectin probably caused birth defects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
