<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Terrorism     09-28 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Terrorism,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Palestinian Resuming Libya-Supported Terrorist
Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abu Nidal, the Palestinian terrorist who laid
low in 1987, appears to be resuming his violent campaign with
support from Libya, the top U.S. counterterrorism official said.
   L. Paul Bremer, ambassador-at-large for counterterrorism, said
the apparent re-emergence of Abu Nidal is indirectly linked to the
April 1986 U.S. bombing of Libya, which the Reagan administration
accuses of sponsoring various terrorist activities.
   Bremer also said the number of terrorist incidents worldwide
appears to be headed for a record level of 1,000 this year, but the
number of Americans killed in such attacks has fallen.
   The 1986 U.S. raid on Libya and Western pressure ``has had the
effect ... in the case of Libya ... to drive the terrorism that
Libya supports into different channels, so that instead of using
diplomats and business,'' Col. Moammar Gadhafi is ``doing it more
through surrogates, like Abu Nidal and the Japanese Red Army,''
Bremer said.
   U.S. officials blame Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri Bannah,
for machine-gun attacks that killed 22 people at the Rome and
Vienna airports in December 1985.
   Abu Nidal's organization also has been blamed for attacks this
year that killed nine people on a Greek cruise ship last July and
eight in the Sudan last May. The tactics were similar to those used
in the Rome and Vienna airport attacks.
   Abu Nidal is believed to maintain a core operation of 300 people
to 400 people in the Libyan capital of Tripoli, said Bremer. And
although Syria closed Abu Nidal's offices in Damascus last year, it
still allows him to run training camps in the Bekaa Valley of
Lebanon.
   Despite the increase this year in the total number of terrorist
incidents, Bremer said counterterrorism efforts have been helped by
better international coordination.
   ``We estimate at least several hundred incidents have been
stopped by steps that we and our allies have taken over the last
three years ... maybe as many as 300 ... some major and some not,''
he said. He declined to give specifics.
   ``The bad news is that terrorism is certainly continuing.
According to the figures that we keep, ... 1987 was the worst year
in history. We had 832 recorded incidents in international
terrorism'' up from 774 in 1986, he said.
   For the first six months of 1988, ``terrorism is up
substantially over last year, perhaps by as much as a third. So it
is possible that we will end this year with as many as 1,000
incidents, maybe more, which would make 1988 the worst year,'' he
said.
   Three Americans were killed in terrorist incidents in the first
half of 1988, down from 38 in the corresponding period in 1986 and
12 in the first half of 1987, he said.
   The greatest surge in terrorist incidents stems from attacks on
Pakistani civilians by agents of the Kremlin-backed regime in
Afghanistan, Bremer said.
   About half the terrorist incidents last year took place in the
Middle East, and there has been an upsurge in attacks in Peru and
Colombia, he said.
   On another topic, Bremer said the United States has evidence
that Tehran has sponsored terrorist incidents within the past month.
</TEXT>
