<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PesticideSafety     09-28 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pesticide Safety,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time Ripe for Pesticide Safety Action, Farm Lawmakers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heeding a decade of pressure from
environmentalists, farm-state senators say the time is ripe to
speed up safety reviews of pest-killing chemicals, some of which
are finding their way to American dinner tables.
   ``For the first time in many years, we are hopeful that
agreement can be reached on some simple but significant changes,''
said Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., and
four fellow senators in a letter urging support.
   The bill would accelerate to nine years safety reviews of some
600 pesticides begun a decade ago and which would not be finished
for more than 35 years at the present pace. It would send the bill
to the manufacturers rather than to the taxpayers as under the
current system.
   The aim is to ban use of the most dangerous pesticides and limit
the use of others which could pose a threat. A number of the
chemicals, which are used to combat rodents, insects and other
forms of crop blight, have been found to cause cancer and other
severe health defects in laboratory experiments.
   Indemnity payments by the government to buy up stocks of banned
pesticides would be ended for the most part. They have cost $20
million so far, and even if the bill becomes law far greater
outlays are likely before they trail off.
   The bill would reauthorize the 1947 Federal Insecticide,
Rodenticide and Fungicide Act, whose very title might seem
resistant to attempts to glamorize the issue.
   Environmentalists, however, sought to do precisely that Tuesday,
bringing in actress Meryl Streep to lobby in favor of the bill.
Arriving at the office of Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., she said
her chief concern was the safety of her children.
   ``I went to cook dinner tonight and everything I pulled out of
the refrigerator could have been harmful,'' Streep said.
   Lugar is among lawmakers pushing for approval of the
House-passed measure, but no lawmakers are claiming that the bill
is the ultimate answer to the pesticide issue launched by
naturalist Rachel Carson in her 1962 bestseller ``Silent Spring''
and a focus of the environmental movement ever since.
   Missing from the bill is any provision to get the government
moving on a cleanup of groundwater contaminated by pesticides.
   The Environmental Protection Agency is currently surveying the
extent of toxic chemical seepage into groundwater, which feeds 13
million wells nationwide and provides the basic drinking supply for
117 million Americans.
   The Capitol Hill-based U.S. Public Interest Research Group said
recently, however, an inspection of EPA records shows at least 34
different pesticides in groundwater in 34 states, based on 45,000
well samples.
   Most environmentalists are in favor of the measure but only in a
lukewarm way. Some who say they oppose the bill fear that a
bare-bones law with a three-year lifespan will put the entire issue
on ice until 1992 _ ruling out action on the groundwater issue next
year.
   ``It's like there are three seconds to go until the end of the
game and there you are on the 30-yard line,'' said compromise
advocate Maureen Hinckle, a lobbyist for the National Audubon
Society. ``You don't go for the touchdown, you kick the field
goal.''
   ``This isn't kicking the field goal,'' said Dave Baker,
political director of Friends of the Earth and a critic of the
bill. ``This is running out of the end zone and conceding the
safety ... We can't do that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
