<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeaponsReactor     09-28 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weapons Reactor,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watchdog Agency Raises Doubt About Converting Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Accounting Office says converting
a partially completed commercial nuclear reactor to a weapons
production reactor may raise policy questions over separation of
civilian and military nuclear facilities.
   However, a GAO report to Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., said there
were ``no major safety, technical or other barriers'' which would
preclude the Washington state reactor from being considered as an
option for the next new defense materials production reactor.
   The plant, 63 percent complete and owned by the Washington
Public Power Supply System, is situated on the Department of
Energy's Hanford Reservation near Richland, Wash.
   In August, Energy Secretary John S. Herrington recommended
construction of two new weapons production reactors _ a heavy water
reactor at DOE's Savannah River Plant in South Carolina and a
high-temperature, gas-cooled reactor at Idaho National Engineering
Laboratory in Idaho.
   Also, Herrington said research and development should continue
on the possibility of converting the commercial light water reactor
at Hanford, known as Washington Nuclear Plant No. 1 or WNP-1.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said in a report
dated Sept. 21 that ``while DOE's condemnation and completion of a
partially completed commercial power plant as a defense production
plant do not violate the 1968 Non-Proliferation Treaty or existing
law, it may raise policy questions.''
   ``For example, such action may be criticized on the basis that
it breaks away from the traditional separation between peaceful use
of atomic energy and military use,'' it said.
   Although DOE has statutory authority to condemn the WNP-1 plant,
the GAO said, the plant's cost through condemnation is not known.
``The cost could range from $30 million (salvage value) to $2.1
billion (total of the outstanding bonds).''
   A DOE subcontractor has estimated that in addition to the cost
of acquiring the plant, the cost of completing WNP-1 for production
of tritium _ a hydrogen isotope used in nuclear weapons _ is $2.6
billion.
   In addition to the policy questions, the GAO pointed to other
issues including:
   _ Possible need to modify WNP-1's decay heat removal system,
used to remove heat from the core once the reactor is shut down,
and the station's blackout prevention system, to provide auxiliary
power in case regular sources of electric power are unavailable.
   _ Preventing ``recriticality,'' a fuel meltdown condition that
``can result in an extremely severe accident.'' The GAO said this
risk has been precluded by using 10 percent enriched uranium fuel,
rather than the 20 percent enriched fuel initially planned.
   _ Technical issues dealing with the design and manufacture of
tritium ``target pins'' used within the reactor, as well as with
the reactor's capability of meeting tritium production goals.
   _ Establishing safety requirements or standards that may be
needed for completing WNP-1 as a tritium production reactor rather
than a commercial power facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-B-1Bomber     09-28 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-B-1 Bomber,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Half-Billion Price Put on Fixing B1 Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force is trying to decide whether to
approve a contractor's $520 million offer to improve the B-1 bomber
or whether to try another solution to the troubled plane's
electronic problems.
   ``We just got the (Eaton Corp.) proposal in the last month.
We're looking at it and we're looking at other alternatives,'' said
Air Force Maj. Gen. Michael D. Hall.
   ``We're going to put together a plan by the end of the year, but
at this point, we're not sure which option we will pick,'' Hall
said Tuesday.
   Hall commented shortly after Charles Barron, a representative of
Eaton, said it would cost $520 million for Eaton to improve the
electronic defensive systems aboard the 100 B-1s purchased by the
Air Force.
   That $520 million would be atop the $3.5 billion Eaton contract
already spent by the Air Force for the sophisticated computer
systems which form the brains of the swing-wing plane's defenses.
   The comments were made at a Boston University seminar on the
B-1, which has been the subject of criticism ever since it was
resurrected by President Reagan seven years ago.
   President Carter terminated the plane 11 years ago, but Reagan
reversed that decision, saying the B-1 was needed as a replacement
for the aging B-52s that are the heart of the U.S. nuclear bomber
force. Reagan also decided at the same time to go ahead with the
radar-evading ``stealth'' bomber, which is known as the B-2.
   In 1981, Reagan promised Congress that the 100 B-1s could be
purchased for $20.5 billion, a figure that has grown to $28 billion
through inflation.
   All 100 of the planes, model B-1Bs, have been delivered to the
Air Force, but the service has discovered that their electronic
``counter-measures'' systems need to be improved or the planes
won't make it through Soviet defenses and return should they be
used during a nuclear war.
   The costs to improve the B-1 would be in addition to the $28
billion already spent on the planes and some critics, such as Rep.
Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee,
have suggested that Congress should decide whether to go ahead with
the improvements or spend the money for other weapons.
   Rep. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla., a member of the House Armed Services
Committee, told the seminar, ``the problems with the B-1B are real
and have to be fixed.''
   McCurdy said Aspin's suggestion about halting improvements
wasn't likely to be fulfilled.
   ``No, we're not going to park it,'' he said. ``That's not a
realistic suggestion at this point, since we've already bought and
paid for the plane.''
   ``But we do have to make some decisions about what to do,''
McCurdy said. ``The Eaton proposal is very interesting. I'd not
heard that $520 million figure before.''
   Barron said the Eaton proposal would correct flaws identified by
the Air Force. ``There's no fatal flaw in the B-1B,'' he said.
   Pentagon officials again defended the plane Tuesday, as they
have in the past.
   Dan Howard, chief Pentagon spokesman, said, ``It's the best
manned bomber in the world. It's light years ahead of any other
bomber.''
   Brig. Gen. Robert E. Dempsey of the Strategic Air Command, said,
``Can it do the mission? I would say absolutely so,'' although he
added, ``range would be a consideration.''
</TEXT>
