<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EpiscopalBishop     09-28 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Episcopal Bishop,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Diocese Elects Its Next Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard F. Grein, bishop of Kansas since 1981,
was elected coadjutor bishop of the Episcopal Church's New York
diocese on Tuesday, and will automatically succeed Bishop Paul
Moore Jr. upon Moore's retirement.
   The election of Grein, who will serve under Moore, required a
majority of the delegates in the diocesan convention's two
``houses,'' one composed of clergy, one of laity.
   He was selected on the 10th ballot around midnight, said Paul
Gorman, spokesman for the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in
Manhattan.
   More than 900 convention delegates and alternates gathered for
the election on the grounds of the cathedral. They were offered
five nominees by a committee that made a national search for
Moore's successor.
   One was the 55-year-old Grein, who was the only candidate
heading a diocese.He is a native of Bemidji, Minn.
   ``There is no school for bishops. Only by doing it could I learn
how,'' he said prior to the election. He was not present when the
vote occurred.
   A leading candidate, Suffragan Bishop Walter D. Dennis Jr., 56,
collapsed early in the balloting and his name was withdrawn from
consideration.
   Dennis, a Moore assistant elected in 1979, was taken by
ambulance to the St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center after he had
a seizure and fell in the cathedral's Synod House.
   Hospital spokeswoman Cathy Rohan said Dennis was in stable
condition.
   Dennis was the only black candidate for coadjutor bishop.
   The other nominees included:
   _The Rev. C. Hugh Hildesley, 47, rector of the Church of
Heavenly Rest in Manhattan. He left Sotheby's auction house, where
he was senior vice president, to become a priest.
   _The Rev. Thomas F. Pike, 50, rector of Calvary-St. George's
Church in Manhattan since 1975.
   _The Rev. George F. Regas, 57, rector of All Saints Church in
Pasadena, Calif., since 1967. He helped develop one of the church's
largest U.S. congregations, with more than 3,000 members.
   Moore, 68, has indicated he will retire before the mandatory age
of 72. Installed as bishop in 1970, he went on to become one of the
nation's most prominent liberal clergymen. He also decided to
resume construction of St. John the Divine, which is designed to be
the world's largest Gothic cathedral.
   The New York diocese covers Manhattan, the Bronx and Staten
Island and several suburban counties, and includes more than 64,000
Episcopalians. It is the eighth largest Episcopal diocese in the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
