<DOCNO> AP880928-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     09-28 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Met Opera Performs First `Giulio Cesare'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the second night of its season, the
Metropolitan Opera presented a series of firsts.
   Handel's 1724 ``Giulio Cesare,'' set in Egypt in 48 B.C., was
sung at the Met for the first time.
   Trevor Pinnock, a British early music specialist who'd never
conducted an opera before, conducted.
   The Met never before had a countertenor (male alto) on its
stage. In ``Giulio Cesare'' it had two.
   Kathleen Battle was the vocal star of Tuesday evening, singing
Cleopatra. Her voice is delicate but so focused that it never
sounds weak. Sound comes from her like a golden thread. The
coloratura passages aren't especially glittering from Miss Battle
because all her singing is sweetly spun gold.
   The musical style, vocal and orchestral, was exemplary. The
orchestra, of only 30 pieces, did not consist of original
instruments, which often are out of tune. Handel's music has
serenity, as beautiful melodies are stated, repeated and
embellished without haste. Pinnock managed to conduct so that often
there also was urgency and excitement.
   Tatiana Troyanos sang Julius Caesar. She began with much florid
singing, making a strenuous effort to get it right, which she did,
but sounding as though she had about half a voice. In the last
act's florid singing, her voice was much fuller, and rich, though
effort could still be heard. Her Julius Caesar didn't step forward
as an opera's title character should.
   Jeffrey Gall, a native of Cleveland, made his Met debut as
Ptolemy, Cleopatra's brother, a countertenor role. His voice is
interesting and not unpleasant, though it doesn't sound entirely
human. It sounds like a cross between a female mezzo-soprano and
words coming through a hollow reed.
   The other countertenor, whose role as Cleopatra's confidant is
smaller, is Derek Lee Ragin, who was born in West Point, N.Y., and
grew up in Newark. His voice sounds warmer and more a cross between
a mezzo and a tenor's falsetto.
   Sarah Walker as the wife of Pompey and Martine Dupuy as their
son were exceptionally effective in large parts. Bass Julien
Robbins also was admirable as commander in chief of Ptolemy's army,
one of the opera's few low voices.
   The production was created by the English National Opera in 1979
and has been performed at the San Francisco Opera and in Geneva,
Switzerland. The women's costumes are lavish and don't attempt to
look Egyptian. Gowns are basically Elizabethan, with bustles and
ruff collars.
   The concept of the stage sets was pleasing. Each scene had a few
pillars or monuments or thrones. Before scenes ended, singers would
step forward and a screen would drop behind them so the stage could
be changed for the next scene. It was orderly without being
symmetrical.
   John Copley, in charge of production, John Pascoe, sets, and
Michael Stennett, costumes, were making Met debuts.
   This opera is remembered here for the New York City Opera
production which transposed the title role so that bass-baritone
Norman Treigle could sing it. And it made the Cleopatra, Beverly
Sills, a star.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0038 </DOCNO>
