<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Thatcher     09-28 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thatcher,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Thatcher Sees Benefits For West From Gorbachev's
Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher says it
will be ``in the Western interest'' for Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
succeed in his efforts to reshape the Soviet Union.
   In an interview published today in The New York Times, Mrs.
Thatcher was asked what particularly appeals to her about
Gorbachev's policies. She said it's ``the idea that enlarging the
liberty and responsibility will give you greater economic
prosperity.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, interviewed in London on Tuesday, said when she
visited the Soviet Union last year she wondered whether it would be
``in the Western interest'' for Gorbachev to succeed. She has
decided it would be, Mrs. Thatcher said.
   Concerning those efforts, the prime minister said: ``It's a
great, massive turnaround, where you have in fact been saying to
people for 70 years, you don't do anything unless you've got
permission, to turn round and say, well now, look you've got to do
quite a lot on your own initiative.''
   Mrs. Thatcher also said Britain will support the changes in the
Soviet Union ``in every way we can without interfering.'' She cited
an increase in East-West contacts and in joint ventures between
Soviet state enterprises and British companies.
   But she also said this uncertain period of change in the Eastern
bloc ``requires total Western unity and preparedness.''
   She said Britain will insist that the NATO alliance modernize
conventional and nuclear weapons in Western Europe.
   On another subject, the prime minister said she didn't watch the
debate between presidential candidates George Bush and Michael
Dukakis.
   ``I'm not going to get involved in your election problems for
very obvious reasons,'' she said.
</TEXT>
