<DOCNO> AP880928-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LoveCanal Bjt   09-28 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Love Canal, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Love Canal Resident Can't Wait To Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of Love Canal has been declared
safe for resettlement, and Nunzio LoVerdi, who spent years trying
to stay in the neighborhood that became synonymous with chemical
contamination, vowed to be the first back.
   ``Your home is your home no matter what happens to it,'' LoVerdi
said Tuesday. ``I'm going back.''
   State health officials announced Tuesday that hundreds of former
Love Canal residents may return to the homes they left after the
neighborhood was declared a disaster by President Jimmy Carter 10
years ago. Up to 80 other families were hoping the study would
confirm their decision to stay in their homes near the former
chemical dump site.
   The state health commissioner, Dr. David Axelrod, said that as a
result of state and federal cleanup efforts, most areas of Love
Canal contain no more chemicals than other neighborhoods in this
industrial city.
   Axelrod met with about 200 former residents Tuesday night to
announce his findings. Axelrod said, however, that some blocks
remain unsafe, affecting about 10 families.
   The long-anticipated finding was hailed by former residents who
feared that their neighborhood would be left boarded up and mostly
abandoned as a symbol of environmental disaster.
   ``We didn't want to be a symbol of anything. We just wanted our
lifestyle back,'' said LoVerdi, a retired laborer who led a group
of renters fighting city and state plans to tear down the Lasalle
Housing Project and other homes in the area.
   LoVerdi was among the renters evicted this spring from the
project, where state officials never found contamination. It is
scheduled to be torn down because it would cost too much to
renovate.
   Niagara Falls Mayor Michael O'Laughlin said Axelrod's decision
will be good for the city of 71,000, which borders Canada and the
famous falls.
   ``It won't mean a landslide of people moving back,'' O'Laughlin
said. ``But it will mean the city will begin to put the nightmare
behind it.''
   Phyllis Festor, president of the Niagara Falls Board of
Realtors, said the city is having a real estate boom, and that
housing prices have increased in the Love Canal area during the
last three years.
   ``The decision was so long in coming that, for most people, it
doesn't matter anymore,'' she said.
   Former resident Lois Gibbs, who now heads a Washington-based
environmental group, said that despite resettlement, Love Canal
would always remain a ``monument to disaster.''
   Ms. Gibbs pointed out that while most of the residential areas
may be free of chemicals, that only meant the chemical threat had
been contained, not removed.
   Ms. Gibbs said the state would have serious liability problems
if new contamination were discovered in resettled areas.
   Love Canal, an abandoned waterway, was used by the Hooker
Chemical Co. to dispose of thousands of pounds of chemical wastes
in the 1940s. The company made herbicides and pesticides.
   In the 1950s, the canal and its contents were filled in and
homes and an elementary school were built on top. It wasn't until
the early 1970s that residents began to notice foul smells in their
basements and oily puddles in their yards.
   They also began to notice higher-than-usual incidences of
miscarriages, birth defects, cancer, leukemia, neurological
disorders, allergies, epilepsy and suicide.
   There were near riots at town meetings in the late 1970s when
the dangers from the chemicals were revealed to residents.
Eventually, 728 homes in a 50-block area were evacuated. The
elementary school and 228 houses were demolished.
   The state and federal governments filed multimillion-dollar
lawsuits against Hooker's parent company, Occidental Petroleum
Corp. Much of that litigation is pending.
   The dump site has been fenced off and surrounded with clay and
plastic liners to prevent the chemicals from leaking into the air
or ground water. Corroding drums of dioxins and other chemicals
have been separated and complex runoff and monitoring systems built.
   As part of the state ruling, a committee of local officials will
create a plan to resettle the neighborhood and assist homeowners in
renovation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-28 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Board To Police Film Colorization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed legislation that
sets up a government board to police the practice of film
colorization.
   The National Film Preservation Board and its $100,000 budget was
included in the $10.5 billion appropriation for the Interior
Department and related agencies Reagan signed on Tuesday.
   The board is to establish a national film register labeling
movies according to their cultural, historical and aesthetic
interest and then report on alterations, such as colorization, that
are made in a registered film.
   If the Patent and Copyright Office found a copyright
infringement, it would be required to apply to the appropriate U.S.
attorney's office for a temporary restraining order and make
recommendations for civil proceedings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Report: Pentagon Has Trouble Managing Huge Inventory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has more than doubled its
collection of spare parts and other materials under President
Reagan's military buildup, leaving the Defense Department unable to
properly manage the stockpile, a congressional report concludes.
   ``The enormous, unprecedented, and unsustainable growth in the
Pentagon's secondary inventory has simply overwhelmed the
Pentagon's depots, warehouses, and accounting and control
systems,'' the study issued Tuesday by the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee said.
   The study of so-called ``secondary items'' _ such things as
spares, repair parts, supplies, food and clothing _ has grown from
$43 billion in value in 1980 to $94 billion.
   The report, the latest study by the Democratic-controlled panel
on defense inventories, said the Pentagon is still doing a poor job
of managing the stockpile despite reforms.
   Concluding that management of the materials ``has not kept pace
with the Pentagon's ability to spend money on new goods,'' the
report said the Defense Department should reduce the growing volume
of items it has in its inventory.
