<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Soviets     09-28 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Soviets,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Propose Converting Siberian Radar Station</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviets-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says it will turn a
controversial radar complex into an international space research
center and has asked the United States to follow suit with radar
sites in Britain and Greenland.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze made the offer
during a speech at the 43rd General Assembly on Tuesday.
   Shevardnadze said the disputed radar complex in Siberia near the
city of Krasnoyarsk could be used by a world space organization.
The United States has said it will not sign a treaty to cut
superpower nuclear arsenals unless Moscow agrees to dismantle the
radar, which is not yet completed.
   U.S. officials say the radar violates the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty because it is not on the outskirts of the Soviet
Union facing outward, as the treaty requires.
   Earlier this month, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev made a
proposal similar to that of Shevardnadze. He also suggested the
United States take ``appropriate action'' concerning its disputed
phased-array radars in Greenland and Britain, which the Soviets say
violate the ABM Treaty.
   ``By doing that we would not only lay the material groundwork
for international cooperation in space but would also strengthen
the ABM Treaty regime,'' Shevardnadze said Tuesday. His statement
appeared to be the most specific Soviet proposal yet concerning the
disputed radars.
   The speech came a day after Reagan delivered his seventh and
final address to the 159-member world body.
   The Soviet minister shared Reagan's view of the benefits of
improved Soviet-U.S. cooperation and supported the President's call
for an international conference to strenghten the global ban on
chemical weapons.
   But he criticized Reagan _ not by name _ for lecturing the world
body on the supposed superiority of U.S. democracy and respect for
human rights.
   ``Why can the great American people have their own great dream,
and why should the Cuban or the Nicaraguan, the Angolan or the
Vietnamese people be deprived of the right to have their own
ideals?'' he asked.
</TEXT>
