<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Tourism     09-28 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Tourism,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Coast Ready and Eager for Shuttle Hordes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From portable toilets to souvenir stands
and first aid stations, the Space Coast is geared up for the
tourists who are coming to watch the shuttle launch _ and maybe
spend some money while they're at it.
   ``Nobody's ever ready for something like this, but we are more
prepared than we have ever been in the past,'' said Ralph McMullen,
director of the Brevard County Tourist Development Agency.
   The county's 8,300 hotel-motel rooms and 4,000 campsites are
filled, the roads are heavy with traffic, and restaurants and
merchants for 50 miles up and down the coast are doing a booming
business. And today is only T-Minus One, the day before the nation
is scheduled to resume its space program.
   Tourism officials and business people are ecstatic. Their
``Green for Shuttle Go'' program is turning out to mean greenbacks
as well as the green lapel bows being worn by residents and
visitors alike.
   But all is not peachy.
   Police and transportation managers warned of traffic deadlock by
the time the shuttle is due to lift off at 9:59 a.m. Thursday.
   Traffic backups are expected into the next county on State Roads
50 and 520 and the Beeline Expressway as county and local officials
expect the mass of visitors to equal or surpass other launch
crowds, including the Apollo moon missions and the first shuttle in
1981. Some advance estimates of this week's crowd have reached 1
million, twice the number here for the first shuttle flight.
   ``We're excited about the launch. I love space. I'd love to be
on the flight,'' said Cletus Schiermann, here with his wife,
Dorothy, from Webster Groves, Mo.
   Hotels as far away as Daytona Beach and Orlando were getting
business from space buffs, and many of the tourists are expected to
be stuck on the highways at launch time.
   ``The majority of the time, traffic is going to be at a
standstill,'' said sheriff's Lt. Vernon Weekly.
   At least 250,000 people are expected to vie for viewing spots
along the banks of the Indian River in and around Titusville, the
self-styled ``Gateway to Space'' that's home to 43,000 residents.
Cars, vans, and motor homes have already staked out choice areas.
   All of this means ``megabucks,'' says Joe Catrambone, executive
vice president of the Titusville Area Chamber of Commerce.
   And if the launch is delayed, extending visitors' stays and
bringing in more tourists this weekend? ``We could double or triple
what we could take in,'' Catrambone said.
   On top of the free-spending tourists, a record 5,000 journalists
have been accredited and most are expected to be here, far
surpassing the previous high of 2,700, NASA officials said.
   ``The media are spending money everywhere,'' said McMullen.
   Then, of course, there are the invited VIPs, who will have to do
little of the sweating in getting around or the worrying and
jostling for good viewing spaces.
   About 2,000 of them, including at least 50 members of Congress,
actor John Travolta, former astronauts and a Saudi Arabian prince,
will watch the liftoff from a special NASA VIP site seven miles
from the launch pad. Another 2,000 overflow invitees will be on the
NASA Causeway.
   The destruction of shuttle Challenger 2{ years ago is far from
forgotten in this area that depends on a healthy space industry for
much of its livelihood. But the prevailing sentiment is optimism.
   And it's just like old times for some veteran bartenders, too.
At Rainbows restaurant and bar in Cocoa Beach, they are serving a
red, white and blue concoction made up of grenadine, cocoa creme
and a mint-flavored blue liqueur.
   They're called ``Shuttle Shooters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
