<DOCNO> AP880928-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0643EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-L'AmbianceSettlement     09-28 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-L'Ambiance Settlement,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Settlement Proposed In L'Ambiance Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apartment building that collapsed last
year would be rebuilt and the families of the 28 workers killed
would share in the profits under a settlement proposed by a
mediation panel, a newspaper reported today.
   The proposal to settle cases stemming from the April 23, 1987,
collapse of the L'Ambiance Plaza in Bridgeport is contained in a
memorandum written by the panel and obtained by The Hartford
Courant.
   ``I have heard about it, and I think it is an excellent idea,''
said Joe Eagan, business manager of the Iron Workers Union in New
Haven, which lost seven members in the collapse.
   The panel, named in a bid to settle all litigation in the case,
is composed of U.S. District Judge Robert C. Zampano and Superior
Court Judge Frank S. Meadow.
   Lawyers representing the families and workers met with the
judges last week and accepted the proposal, according to the
memorandum, dated Sept. 21, the Courant reported.
   The panel met with defendants' attorneys Tuesday to outline the
settlement proposal. Those attorneys have until Friday to respond
to the proposal, the Courant reported.
   ``On Friday, hopefully we will have something a little bit more
concrete,'' Meadow said.
   Attorneys familiar with the case who asked not to be identified
told the Courant they didn't know what was the total amount of
money available for the settlement. But they speculated it could
range from $20 million to $30 million for the plaintiffs, with an
additional $20 million for other damages and for settling contract
disputes.
   The memorandum said the judges are still working to include $5.1
million in the settlement for proposed federal safety fines. The
fines were levied against the contractors by the federal
Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   The building was partially erected when it collapsed. Federal
investigators blamed the equipment used in lifting huge concrete
floor slabs into position, a construction method known as lift slab.
   According to the proposed settlement, the building would be
reconstructed under a court trusteeship. Part of the income and
profits from the project would be distributed among the families of
those killed and the 14 injured workers, according to the
memorandum, the Courant reported.
   ``I love that idea,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.,
whose district includes Bridgeport. ``First and foremost, the
victims need compensation, and there is not much to go around. But
secondly, this would be a very important thing for Bridgeport, to
have this meaningful project come out of the ashes.''
   Before the accident, the building was hailed as a symbol of
rebirth for the old industrial city.
   Under the plan, the Connecticut Housing Finance Authority, which
financed the building, would finance the reconstruction. An
attorney for the agency refused to comment Tuesday to the Courant.
   The meetings with the defendants included representatives of the
companies and government agencies that participated in the project.
   At the closed-door meetings, the judges told each defendant what
they were expected to contribute, participants told the newspaper.
The judges also applied pressure in a bid to avoid years of
litigation, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
