<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Sihanouk     09-28 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Sihanouk,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk, Survivor of the Indochina Turmoils, To Meet With Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian Prince Norodom Sihanouk, in favor
again in Washington after a past alliance with the communist Khmer
Rouge, is expected here next month for meetings with President
Reagan and Secretary of State George Shultz.
   Sihanouk will meet with Reagan Oct. 11 and Shultz the following
day on prospects for peacefully ending the 10-year Vietnamese
occupation of his country, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said Tuesday.
   Sihanouk, who in the 1970s condemned ``American Imperialism''
and lived in exile in China and North Korea, ``has been the leading
symbol of Cambodian nationalism during the past 40 years ... and
the United States strongly supports him,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   Sihanouk met Shultz in Thailand last July, the same month he
resigned as president of the anti-Vietnamese resistance coalition
in Cambodia, which included the Khmer Rouge.
   Mrs. Oakley said he continues to lead ``one of the two
non-communist groups struggling to free Cambodia from Vietnamese
aggression and his leadership has been an important element in
rallying the Cambodian people and strengthening international
opposition to Vietnam's illegal occupation.''
   She said the United States insists on complete withdrawal of all
Vietnamese troops and ``restoration of genuine self-determination.''
   Sihanouk, 65, has been in and out of favor with the United
States and in and out of exile the past two decades.
   Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in 1978 and forced the Khmer
Rouge from Phnom Penh after almost four years of brutal rule.
Vietnam earlier this summer said it had withdrawn about 13,000
troops and plans to have the last of the estimated 100,000 soldiers
stationed in Cambodia removed by 1990.
   Sihanouk started patching up relations with the United States in
a 1980 Washington visit that included talks at the State Department
and with members of Congress and Cambodian refugees.
</TEXT>
