<DOCNO> AP880928-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fisherman'sWharf     09-28 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fisherman's Wharf,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishing To Return To Fisherman's Wharf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Years of neglect and wanton commercialism
of Fisherman's Wharf could be dead in the water, according to a $23
million plan to revitalize the waterfront.
   The plan was announced Tuesday by a coalition of city officials,
fishing interests and residents, and comes years after the wharf
became a commercial dock for T-shirt shops and souvenir hawkers,
tainting its once shining reputation as a thriving Gold Rush-era
fishing village.
   ``Thirty years I've been waiting for this,'' said Pat Flanagan,
head of the committee that helped develop the plan.
   ``People don't come to San Francisco to look at secretaries in
the high-rise buildings,'' quipped Flanagan, who owns Standard
Fisheries on the wharf.
   At a news conference, Mayor Art Agnos announced that marketing
studies conducted for the Port of San Francisco indicate that
fishing industry improvements at the wharf can be financed without
revenues from a commercial development.
   The preceding mayoral administration had proposed funding
improvements at Fisherman's Wharf from the construction of a
high-rise hotel on Pier 45.
   ``At one time, it appeared that this vital industry was going to
be allowed to die because of lack of investment in modernization,''
Agnos said. ``I am delighted we have, at last, been able to develop
a plan for preservation and expansion of our fishing industry.''
   Under the plan, which officials hope to begin by 1990, the Hyde
Street Pier would be converted into a working pier for fishermen,
containing 88 new berths for active commercial fishing vessels and
transient berthing.
   The pier also would have a three-berth marine fuel station, a
work dock and hoist, a convenience store, restrooms and showers for
fishermen.
   The study by a consulting team showed that enough industry
demand for space on the pier exists to make fish handling viable.
   ``The fishing industry believes a wharf address will enhance the
marketability of their product,'' said Carol Brown, one of the
consultants. ``They foresee developing a product trademark _
`Fisherman's Wharf Seafood' _ that will have the same appeal as
`Fisherman's Wharf Sourdough.'''
   She said the project will cost an estimated $22.8 million, with
the funds to come from state and federal grants, revenues generated
from the plan and perhaps an outside developer.
   ``Our studies show that individual businesses can thrive here,''
Brown said. ``The bay area is a very large market for fresh fish,
and the diversity of our population provides a market for fish
products that do not have mass appeal elsewhere.''
   The plan is under review by the Citizens Advisory Committee of
the Fisherman's Wharf Redevelopment Project. The committee's
co-chair, Chris Martin, said this project will succeed where others
have failed because of the city's commitment to the fishing
industry, instead of merely commercial interests.
   ``This is without question, without compromise,'' explained
Martin, who also manages The Cannery at the wharf, a complex of
shops and restaurants. ``The other (proposal) was conditional on
the hotel.''
   Along the wharf, plastic carvings of sailors and rugged
fishermen have replaced the real thing, and neon signs promoting
every conceivable tourist-type item permeate the waterfront.
   However, tourists still flock to one of San Francisco's most
popular attractions, though at times they come away disappointed.
   ``It's kind of touristy along the strip,'' said Derek Schroder,
of Tucson, Ariz., visiting the Wharf on Tuesday. ``But we like the
restaurants here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti     09-28 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Meet with Avril; No Accord on Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti's new military leaders met
with three former presidential candidates and agreed to restore the
constitution but balked at setting an election date, a spokesman
for one candidate said.
   ``The government seems to desire the advancement of the
democratic process,'' said Claude Roumain, political director for
Marc Bazin, one of the former candidates.
   Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, Haiti's new president, and Sgt. Joseph
Heubreux met Tuesday with Bazin, Gerard Gourgue and Louis Dejoie
Jr., local radio stations said. The three former presidential
candidates belong to a pro-democracy group called Committee for
Democratic Understanding.
   They asked Avril for a return of the constitution, which was
approved by referendum but later suspended by Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy, who was ousted as Haiti's leader in a Sept. 17 coup by
lower-ranking members of the Presidential Guard.
   Avril, administrative head of the army under Namphy, was named
president by Heubreux and other coup leaders. Heubreux is believed
to be running this impoverished Caribbean country in concert with
Avril.
   ``The principle of a return to the suspended 1987 Constitution
was admitted by the new government. Amendments will be considered
only when a new duly elected legislature is in session,'' Roumain
said.
   ``Our points of view differ, however, on a date for elections.
The Committee and the Military Government agree, nevertheless, that
the date will be set by an independant Electoral Council, and not
by the de facto government,'' Roumain added.
   Avril and Heubreux have met with other political factions but
have set no timetable for bringing democratic rule to Haiti.
   Haiti was ruled for nearly three decades by dictators Francois
``Papa Doc'' Duvalier and then his son, Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc''
Duvalier. The younger Duvalier was swept from power by a popular
uprising in February 1986 and fled to France.
   Namphy, exiled now to the Dominican Republic, led a provisional
government after Duvalier's departure that was interrupted for four
months in June by the civilian presidency of Leslie Manigat.
   Manigat was elected in military-run balloting that was boycotted
by the most popular presidential candidates and marked by
widespread irregularities.
   What might have been the nation's first free elections in 30
years were thwarted last November when armed thugs killed at least
34 people at polling stations.
</TEXT>
