<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slides Downward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today while share prices closed higher on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   Following Tuesday's 165.81-point gain, the 225-issue Nikkei
Stock Average gained 225.10 points shortly after the market opened
and closed at 27,752.01, up another 252.45 points, or 0.92 percent.
   The trading was hectic with volume on the first section
estimated at 1.8 billion shares for the second straight day, the
largest amount since July 15 when more than 2 billion shares were
traded.
   ``Because the new financial year started, investors who had been
pessimistic and selling stocks regained buying interest, which
increased the volume and share prices,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of
the Nikko Securities in Tokyo.
   Most Japanese companies began their new fiscal year Tuesday.
   Although some investors are worried about the U.S. unemployment
rate for September, scheduled to be announced Oct. 7, it was not
acting as a negative factor, Shimoyama said.
   ``The market in Tokyo has regained its energy and is in good
shape,'' he added.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed slightly lower
at 134.20 yen, down 0.38 yen from the previous day's close of
134.58 yen.
   Opening higher at 134.70 yen, the currency moved between 134.20
and 134.75 yen, unaffected by any market news, according to a
dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   The dollar gradually fell after banks in New York and Europe
sold the currency Monday to force the rate down, but ``the dollar
is unlikely to keep falling,'' said the dealer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
