<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MosbyElection     09-28 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mosby Election,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Of Mosby Elects Mayor On Fourth Try</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSBY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus driver was elected mayor of this
tiny town after the opponent who had tied him in three elections
this year moved away.
   Thomas Ledford won the election Tuesday night by an unofficial
count of 25-5 over Harold Hartman. In contests this spring and
summer, voters had split 17-17, 20-20 and 34-34 between the two.
   The winner said turnout was down this time because people got
tired of going to the polls for the same race.
   ``I'm glad it's over, and I'm certainly pleased at the
outcome,'' said Ledford, whose predecessor, Mayor Hattie Mae
Shelton, is resigning because of health problems.
   Hartman, Ledford's only opponent, sold his farm and moved this
month to Excelsior Springs, five miles away. Although his name
appeared on Tuesday's ballot, he would not have been eligible to
serve had he won. The town council would have had the authority to
appoint a mayor.
   Stories about the town's troubles in getting a mayor were
reported in newspapers from Washington state to Washington, D.C.
   ``It really put us on the map,'' said Kenneth Schneiter, one
Mosby's 280 residents. ``Whenever I say `Mosby,' people say,
`That's the town that's trying to get the mayor.'''
   Ledford said he's eager to put the campaign behind him and get
on with city business, such as organizing more social events for
town youth and having oil sprayed on gravel roads to keep the dust
down.
   ``When the publicity is over, everyone is going to forget that
the city of Mosby exists,'' he said. ``We'll be a forgotten little
city that carries on as usual.''
</TEXT>
