<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Lithuania     09-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Lithuania,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Nationalists Roughed Up At Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shoved and beat people in the Lithuanian
capital as they prepared to protest the forced incorporation of
their republic into the Soviet Union, a witness reported.
   Valdas Analuslias, a Lithuanian nationalist who attended the
rally, said about 300 people gathered Tuesday in a square of
Vilnius to advertise a demonstration scheduled for today.
   About 100 policemen moved in, shoving and pushing some of those
gathered.
   Two middle-aged women shouted, ``Freedom to Lithuania,'' and
police attacked them, beating them on the ground as dozens of
people watched in horror, Analuslias said by telephone.
   The women were taken away, apparently to the local office of the
state security agency, the KGB, he said.
   The crowd did not disperse and sang religious songs.
   Several prominent Lithuanian activists were unable to leave
their homes because they were surrounded by police preventing them
from attending today's rally, which was scheduled to begin at 6
p.m. (11 a.m. EDT), Analuslias reported.
   The activists planned to demonstrate against a secret protocol
to the non-aggression agreement signed in 1939 by Soviet Foreign
Minister Vyacheslav Molotov and German Foreign Minister Joachim von
Ribbentrop.
   Under the protocol, the two powers divided Central Europe and
the three Baltic nations of Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia were
assigned to the Soviet sphere of influence.
   Today's rally, which authorities banned, was called to demand
publication of the pact in the Soviet press and official
acknowledgement that Lithuania was forcibly incorporated into the
Soviet Union.
   Estonian and Moscow-based newspapers published the secret
protocol last month.
</TEXT>
