<DOCNO> AP880928-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma-Profiles     09-28 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Profiles,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Military Leaders and Housewife Lead Burmese Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former military leaders and the
daughter of a national hero have emerged as the three top
opposition leaders to Burma's military autocracy. Here are brief
profiles of the leaders, including the posts they now hold in the
new League for Democracy opposition alliance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AUNG GYI, 70, alliance chairman.
   Aung Gyi, a retired brigadier general, fought against the
Japanese in World War II, and after independence rose to become the
No. 2 man in the military after Ne Win, the armed forces leader who
seized power in a 1962 coup.
   Aung Gyi was considered a possible successor to Ne Win, but the
two men split over economic policy. Aung Gyi advocated a more
pragmatic and liberal policy than Ne Win's ruinous ``Burmese Way to
Socialism'' of complete state control.
   After resigning from government in 1963, Aung Gyi was jailed in
1965-68 and 1973-74.
   He became a businessman and owned several tea and pastry shops
in the Burmese capital of Rangoon. He re-emerged this year as the
regime's leading and most outspoken critic when he issued letters
addressed to Ne Win and other leaders criticizing the nation's
decline. The letters were widely circulated.
   ``That the country has gone from bad to worse (26) years after
the seizure of power is evident to anyone not living in a fool's
paradise ...'' he wrote in a May 12 letter. ``The country has
plunged to the bottom politically, economically and socially, the
moral decay is the most deplorable.''
   Aung Gyi's outspoken criticism got him thrown in jail at the end
of July by Sein Lwin, a hard-line supporter of Ne Win who tried to
break up the pro-democracy movement with force.
   Soon after civilian Maung Maung replaced Sein Lwin as head of
government, Aung Gyi was released Aug. 25 and resumed his
opposition activities.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TIN OO, 62, alliance vice chairman.
   Tin Oo, a retired general widely respected by the military and
the public, was removed as defense minister and army chief of staff
in 1976 by Ne Win. At the time, he was considered the third-ranking
member of the ruling hierarchy.
   Student and labor demonstrators a year earlier put up posters
saying, ``Down with the Ne Win-San Yu Clique!'' and ``Long Live
General Tin Oo!'' His popularity may have been intolerable to
strongman Ne Win and his ally San Yu, who was then general
secretary of the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Tin Oo was later jailed after an investigation into an alleged
plot against the government. He remained popular, however, and
emerged to address pro-democracy demonstrations in this year's
anti-government unrest.
   ``Following the recent public demonstrations against the
one-party regime, the light of democracy has now been visible,'' he
told a rally of 50,000 people in downtown Rangoon on Aug. 27.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AUNG SAN SUU KYI, 42, alliance general secretary and spokeswoman.
   Aung San Suu Kyi is the expatriate daughter of a revolutionary
martyr assassinated 40 years ago during Burma's fight for
independence from British and Japanese imperialsim.
   She was 2 years old when her father, Aung San, was gunned down,
and she was later educated in Burma and in India, where her mother
was ambassador from 1960 to 1967.
   She obtained a bachelor's degree from Oxford University in 1967,
worked at United Nations headquarters in New York and married a
British professor of Tibetan culture in 1972.
   Her world as an expatriate housewife was turned upside down when
she returned to Burma from her home in England in April to care for
her ailing mother.
   Despite her lack of political experience, she became a leading
member of the pro-democracy opposition because her father remains
widely revered.
   ``It's like if George Washington's son had come along in 1830
and said, `I'd like to be president of the United States.' It would
have a certain ring to it,'' explained British Burma expert Robert
H. Taylor.
   In a recent British Broadcasting Corp. interview, she said, ``In
my thoughts, I have never been away from my country and my people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
