<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WorldBank-IMF     09-28 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Bank-IMF,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Calls Gives Plan on Third World Debt Amid Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady gave
world financial leaders a formula for relieving Third World debt,
and leftists smashed bank windows in a protest against the talks.
   More than 100 people were arrested during Tuesday's scattered
demonstrations, police said.
   Brady said creditors should act to slash crippling Third World
debt, but only in ways that private markets accept. He also ruled
out turning over risky loans from private banks to governments and
their taxpayers.
   ``If we embark on a course that involves the transfer of risk
from the private to the public sector, a true and lasting solution
to the restoration of sustained growth among debtor nations will
have escaped,'' he said in Tuesday's speech.
   Several hundred demonstrators on Tuesday marched from the
offices of the West German drug company Schering to a subway
station, police said. Some masked marchers hurled pieces of
pavement at the windows of a bank, said a police spokesman, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Riot police hauled away about 100 of the demonstrators, said a
police spokesman who asked not to be identified.
   Earlier Tuesday, about 160 leftist radicals threw stink bombs
and tried to block traffic to West Berlin's Tegel international
airport, police said. Four people were arrested.
   The violence followed about four hours of rioting in downtown
West Berlin Monday night, when leftist militants smashed many store
windows, dragged a car across a major boulevard, and battled with
police. About 130 people were arrested, and several protesters as
well as police officers were injured, according to witnesses and
police.
   The protests coincide with the annual meeting of the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund with most of the finance
ministers from 151 member governments attending. The sessions of
the sister organizations, which make international loans for
development projects, will continue through Thursday.
   The left-wing protesters accuse the bank and fund of
impoverishing the Third World by forcing nations to adopt austerity
measures to meet the $1.2 trillion in debt to international and
private banks as well as other governments.
   Brady, who was making his first appearance on the international
stage at the formal opening of the talks Tuesday, recommended
several devices to reduce debt. One of the most important is the
use by banks of the money owed them by debtor countries to buy
shares in industry in those countries.
   Brady left for Washington right after his speech on Tuesday
without giving any public indication whether or not he was
criticizing a proposal by Satoshi Sumita, head of the Japanese
delegation.
   Sumita, governor of the Bank of Japan, outlined details of the
Japanese plan earlier Tuesday. It would convert some Third World
debt into bonds, thus further delaying repayments. The bonds would
be backed by money from the debtors themselves and held in trust by
the fund.
   The Japanese plan has been viewed as a rival to the Reagan
administration's ``Baker Plan,'' which calls in part for providing
new loans to developing countries that enact economic
liberalization policies. Brady on Tuesday defended the Baker Plan,
devised by former Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III.
   Treasury Secretary Gustavo Petricioli of Mexico, whose country
is one of the heaviest debtors with bills amounting to $104
billion, appealed for still other means of reducing debt.
   Some Mexican debt was being sold last month for 48 cents on the
dollar.
</TEXT>
