<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Olympics-Newspage     09-28 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympics-Newspage,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Deny United States a Chance at Gold Medal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet basketball team today
defeated the United States 82-76 in an Olympic grudge match,
breaking a U.S. basketball winning streak that began in 1972.
   It wasn't the best of days for Carl Lewis either. The American
lost his bid for a second consecutive gold medal grand slam when
Joe DeLoach beat him by less than a stride in the 200 meters,
leaving Lewis with a silver medal.
   Lewis already has a gold in the long jump and was awarded the
100-meter gold when Ben Johnson was disqualified for taking
steroids.
   The Soviet basketball victory advanced to the team to the
gold-medal game.
   ``I am very happy, and thank you United States basketball,''
said coach Alexander Gomelski, whose team played several U.S. pro
and college teams as it tuned up for the Olympics.
   As it did 16 years ago in Munich, this U.S.-Soviet matchup came
down to the final few seconds.
   At one point, the Soviets led 51-37, but the Americans trimmed
it to 79-76 with just three seconds left.
   But after a Soviet free throw, the Americans were hanging their
heads on the bench while the Soviets exchanged high-fives.
   Danny Manning, most valuable player of Kansas' national
collegiate championship last spring, didn't score a point.
   ``I don't know what to say,'' said Manning. ``I had a chance to
do some things out there, but things just weren't falling
together.''
   David Robinson led the Americans with 19 points and 12 rebounds.
   In 1972 at Munich, America met the Soviet Union for the gold
medal, and, after the final three seconds were played twice because
of referee error and a scoreboard malfunction, the Soviets won
51-50.
   So angered was the U.S. team that it refused to accept the
silver medal. This time, the Americans can win a bronze medal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
