<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Firms Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slide downward against most foreign
currencies in early European trading today, slightly pressured by
overnight sales in the Far East, traders said. Gold prices steadied.
   Traders in London said the dollar was expected to inch lower in
a continued reaction to Monday's intervention by central banks.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.38 yen to close at 134.20. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 134.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8780 West German marks, down from 1.8790
   _1.5925 Swiss francs, up from 1.5910
   _6.3980 French francs, up from 6.3945
   _2.1161 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1185
   _1,400.50 Italian lire, down from 1,402.95
   _1.2185 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6850, compared with $1.6785
Tuesday.
   Gold steadied again in quiet trading.
   The precious metal opened in London at a bid price of $398.90 a
troy ounce, up from $395.30 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today,
the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$397.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $397.50, up from $395.75 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 48 cents to close at a bid of
$401.64.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.17 a troy
ounce, slightly up from Tuesday's $6.15.
</TEXT>
