<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefectorsReturn     09-28 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defectors Return,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Back Home From Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed couple who defected to the Soviet
Union a year ago in search of a better life are back home and
determined to claim what they say were incentives from the U.S.
government to return.
   ``By Monday, we will be broke, so we are going to move into the
U.S. Courthouse (in Erie) to live,'' Theodore Branch, 42, said
Tuesday from a small motel here.
   Branch and his wife, Cheryle, 40, said that after Soviet
officials gave them a furnished apartment and jobs at Radio
Moscow's North American Service, officials at the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow offered them the same benefits plus help resolving their
troubled finances if they returned to the United States.
   But State Department officials in Washington said the Branches
were offered only the same loan available to any stranded U.S.
citizen to finance passage to the United States.
   ``They made promises there, and now they are backing out,''
Branch said.
   The couple will look for work but do not plan to stay with any
of their relatives in the area because ``it's not up to our
relatives to take care of us,'' he said.
   The Branches moved to the Soviet Union last October because ``we
were so mad at the U.S. government, but not at the people.''
   ``We're really mad now,'' he said.
   Branch said that after arriving in Moscow, the Soviets asked
them to visit the Embassy because American officials were worried
about them. He said they refused because ``we vowed we would never
step inside another federal building. They weren't worried about us
there, why would they be worried about us here?''
   The Soviets asked them in February to assure the U.S. Embassy
that they were not being held against their will. Branch claims
that during a subsequent meeting, Jill Farrelly-Byrnes, the
embassy's second secretary and vice consul, said ``Do you need
money? We have jobs for you. We have a place for you to live and
medical care.''
   At an August meeting, the embassy officials said they could not
help solve their problems unless the Branches returned to the
United States, he said.
   No one greeted them in Washington as promised, Branch said.
   ``I think we have been deceived. We have been stripped of
everything,'' said Mrs. Branch. ``It is hard to believe that in a
democratic society, two people could be in such a predicament.''
   The Branches want to be reimbursed for their $3,000 airfare to
return home and for their motel room.
   ``We wouldn't be here looking for a job if they hadn't promised
us,'' Branch said.
   Branch said they might return to the Soviet Union, but are
``tired of moving back and forth across the ocean at somebody's
whim.''
   The troubles that made the Soviet Union look good included the
couple's inability to collect $10,000 in back wages from Central
Florida Broadcasting Co. despite a federal court judgment in their
favor. The two had worked for a radio station run by the company,
which filed for bankruptcy reorganization.
   Land they owned in Erie County was declared part of a flood
plain by the federal government and is worthless, Mrs. Branch said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
