<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneBuzzing 1stLd-Writethru a0503 09-28 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Buzzing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stolen Plane Distributes Anti-Reagan Tracts, Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, ``I've got ...,'' to
UPDATE with additional quotes from pilot; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
``Police did ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot crash-landed a stolen plane in
foggy Golden Gate Park after apparently dropping anti-Reagan
pamphlets on San Quentin Prison, authorities said.
   ``I've got political news: There's more people to vote for than
just (presidential candidates Michael) Dukakis and (George) Bush,''
the uninjured student pilot, Allen Dale, said as police took him
into custody Tuesday.
   Dale told the San Francisco Examiner in an interview published
in today's editions that he was a Vietnam combat veteran who was
troubled by what he called the Reagan administration's failure to
determine the fate of service personnel missing in Southeast Asia.
   ``Reagan and evidently Bush ... promised the families of the
MIAs and POWs that he would make it an A-No. 1 national priority to
get remains and search for survivors,'' Dale said in the telephone
interview from jail.
   Police did not say whether Dale was licensed to fly solo.
   The 40-year-old San Francisco man was arrested shortly after his
landing for investigation of stealing the single-engine plane from
Palo Alto Airport. He was carrying a backpack filled with political
pamphlets.
   ``It was material about wanting to get Reagan, Meese and Bush,''
said police officer Barry Cooper.
   Some people said pamphlets had been tossed out over the
Haight-Ashbury neighborhood, which the plane also buzzed, but
police could not confirm the reports.
   The 1979 red-and-white Bellanca Citavria had ``Nasty Nancy'' and
other anti-Reagan slogans painted on it. It was not damaged except
for a bent propeller, said Cooper.
   Federal Aviation Administration investigators examined the plane
and found that it had fuel in it and no apparent engine defects.
   ``It kind of points to the fact he did it (crashed it) on
purpose,'' said FAA spokesman John Evans.
   Police Sgt. Jerry Senkir said the pilot faced possible
additional charges for carrying what authorities suspect was a
false passport and for landing in the park.
   Scattered around the landing site were leaflets titled
``American Revolution 1988.''
   ``We the peoples of the Army Air Corps (A Team) are arming to
demonstrate disapproval of the criminals in Washington and to save
the planet Earth NOW!,'' said the pamphlets.
   The tracts called for the impeachment of President Reagan, Bush
and a number of other political leaders.
   About 15 minutes before the plane's crash landing, an
unidentified small plane dropped ``numerous'' radical pamphlets as
it flew over San Quentin, 15 miles north of San Francisco, said
prison Lt. Cal White.
   ``It (the plane) came out of the fog, very, very low,'' said
prison spokesman Vernell Crittendon, adding that astounded inmates
and guards scooped up the material.
   No one was injured when the plane Dale flew crash-landed on the
park's Polo Field. The plane had been reported stolen earlier in
the day by the West Valley Flying Club.
   Joyce Dowling, who was jogging in the park, said the pilot was
wearing an Army-issue field jacket and boots.
   ``The (plane's) tail end was straight in the air,'' said
Dowling. ``It bounced about three times before it landed. ... We
just thought the guy's got to be hurt, but he wasn't.''
   The plane is an older-style aircraft normally used for aerobatic
stunts.
   Dale was about halfway back to Haight-Ashbury on foot when
officers in a truck apprehended him.
</TEXT>
