<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0482 09-28 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Rebels, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede GHAY BAW BO, Burma</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soldiers Block Protesters From Fleeing Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with report of soldiers sealing off cities.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KLE DAY, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers are sealing off urban areas to
prevent students and Buddhist monks from fleeing to border regions
to carry on the fight for democracy, arrivals at this frontier
rebel camp said today.
   ``There are tens of thousands of students and monks who want to
leave the cities but cannot,'' said Ko Ko, a 35-year-old teacher
from Rangoon who arrived Tuesday at this camp of about 500 ethnic
Karen rebel soldiers next to the Thai border.
   Gen. Saw Maung, who seized power in a Sept. 18 coup, ended weeks
of massive pro-democracy demonstrations last week by ordering
troops to fire on protesters.
   The official death toll since the coup is about 350, although
Western diplomats believe more people have been killed.
   On Tuesday, Burmese who fled to the rebel stronghold of Ghay Baw
Bo, said they saw soldier summarily execute unarmed protesters who
took to the streets to agitate for democracy.
   Soe Hlaing, a 36-year-old lawyer from Pegu, said he saw nine
people executed by soldiers on a bridge in the town of Tharrawdy
during his flight to the Karen-controlled areas.
   ``Each was shot with a gun. One bullet to the heart,'' Soe
Hlaing said.
   A student from the Rangoon Institute of Technology said he
witnessed the ``sysematic killing'' of 10 persons in Mudon, south
of the coastal city of Moulmein.
   Many anti-government student leaders have gone underground to
escape the brutal suppression, fleeing from military-controlled
cities to wild, frontier areas controlled by ethnic rebels who also
are fighting the central authorities.
   In Kle Day, Ko Ko said ``the army is blocking routes. We came
here because the army is killing students.''
   He said troops are manning roadblocks in Mangladon district of
Rangoon and Kyaito district of Pegu, about 40 miles northeast of
the capital.
   Students have been forced to take detours and are traveling at
night to avoid the checkpoints, said Ko Ko, who has been writing
underground anti-government pamphlets under a pen name since 1975.
   About 270 students have straggled into Kle Day, and Ko Ko quoted
them as saying they plan to take up arms to fight the clique that
has repressively ruled Burma for 26 years and crippled the
country's economy through isolationist economy policies.
   ``We cannot fight with simple weapons,'' said Ko Ko, pointing to
hand-made catapults, sharpened bicycle spokes known as ``jinglees''
and swords. He said students reaching the frontier who have formed
an All Burma Students Democratic Front will try to get arms from
other countries, he said.
   Min Ko Naing, one of the top student leaders in Rangoon, left
the capital the day after the coup and plans to join his
compatriots at the border region, Ko Ko said.
   The Karen army's vice chief of staff, Maj. Gen. Tamala Baw, said
he received instructions from Karen leader Mo Bya that 200 students
will leave Kle Day for Ghay Baw Bo, about 40 miles away, to receive
military training with another 400 students already there.
   Other students will go to bases closer to military installations
in the country's interior, he said.
   Tamala Baw said the Karens will ask international organizations
to help feed the Burmese students escaping to the regions under
rebel control.
   This border area is controlled by the Karen National Union,
which claims to field 17,000 guerrillas and is allied with nine
other rebel groups under the National Democratic Front. The front
does not include the Burma Communist Party, which wages its own war
against the central government from bases along Burma's border with
China.
   The Karens and other minorities have denounced the Rangoon
government for breaking promises to allow them greater autonomy
under a federal system of government which strongman Ne Win
abolished after seizing power in 1962.
   Ne Win resigned in July, but is widely believed to still lead
the government from behind the scenes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
