<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms, Rain and Fog Blanket Most Of The Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers, thunderstorms and fog blanketed much of the nation
today, bringing heavy downpours, hail and gusty winds.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed Tuesday evening through the
central Plains and middle Mississippi Valley.
   In Kansas, 1\-inch hail pounded Burr Oak.
   In Nebraska, areas near North Platte were pelted by hail almost
an inch in diameter. Heavy downpours drenched Gibson, where nearly
1\ inches of rain was measured; Wood River received more than inch
of rain in 20 minutes.
   A thunderstorm over west-central Illinois dumped almost an inch
of rain in 15 minutes on Peoria, and generated gusts up to 45 mph.
Ottumwa, Iowa, was splashed by 2.15 inches of rain and more than an
inch fell at Norfolk, Neb.
   Showers and thunderstorms also swept over the eastern Gulf Coast
and the southern half of the Florida peninsula. Showers were
scattered through the Dakotas, northern Wyoming and Washington.
   Fog over the northern California coast reduced visibility to as
low as an eighth of a mile this morning. Fog also nestled over
portions of the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, Alabama and
Mississippi.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
through the northern and central Plains, the middle and upper
Mississippi Valley and Oklahoma; numerous thunderstorms, possibly
severe, through eastern Kansas, central Oklahoma and northwest
Missouri; showers and thunderstorms over the southern third of
Florida; showers scattered through northern Maine; cloudy skies
through the central Rockies; and mostly sunny skies for the rest of
the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s from North Dakota to
northern sections of the upper Mississippi Valley and upper Great
Lakes, and the northern half of Maine; in the 60s over Washington
state, the northern and central Rockies, the central Plains, the
lower Great Lakes and northern portions of New England; in the 90s
over Texas except the Panhandle, the desert Southwest, the inland
valleys of California, and portions of the Florida peninsula; and
in the 70s and 80s throughout the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 81 degrees at Corpus
Christi, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 61 fair; Boston 59 fair; Buffalo 58 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 67 cloudy; Cincinnati 56 partly cloudy; Cleveland
63 cloudy; Detroit 59 cloudy; Miami 77 fair; New York 61 fair;
Philadelphia 59 foggy; Pittsburgh 55 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
56 cloudy; Washington 59 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 48 showery; Chicago 61 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 74 fair; Denver 48 fair; Des Moines 59 cloudy; Indianapolis
58 cloudy; Kansas City 69 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 fair;
Nashville 62 fair; New Orleans 74 foggy; St. Louis 65 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 60 fair; Anchorage 41 fair; Las Vegas 77
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt Lake City
48 cloudy; San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco 55 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 fair; Toronto 50 fair.
</TEXT>
