<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Party     09-28 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Party,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Warns Members To Obey, Promote Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's ruling Communist Party issued a strong
warning today to its 47 million members to end reckless spending
and graft, which have plunged the nation's 10-year-old economic
reform program into crisis.
   The party, which of late had preached a more relaxed line
allowing some criticism of central policies, published a front-page
editorial in its paper, the People's Daily demanding unity and
discipline.
   ``The individual must submit to the organization,'' it said.
``The party Central Committee and State Council have repeatedly
ordered reductions in the scale of capital construction, and
forbidden party and government organs to do business. But these
still go on to an unbearable extent.''
   The editorial said: ``Those who don't abide by the party's
discipline must be punished.''
   The warning came as the party's policy-making Central Committee
met for a third day in Beijing's Great Hall of the People to
approve a two-year moratorium in price reforms and other measures
to reduce inflation of more than 20 percent.
   The meeting of the 175-member committee is closed and there has
been no word on its proceedings since Monday, when the official
Xinhua News Agency said the session opened with delivery of a
report by party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang.
   The highest inflation in two decades, intermittent panic buying
and hoarding, a late summer run on banks, and widespread
profiteering have convinced party leaders that the economy is out
of control and that a pause in economic reform is needed to restore
order.
   A party work meeting before the Central Committee session
announced that restoring order would be the main task of the next
two years, putting planned price and wage reforms on hold.
   Xinhua said Zhao reiterated this decision in his report.
   The People's Daily editorial emphasized the importance of the
new policy and the need for united action to achieve the top
leadership's goal of modernizing the long stagnant economy by
replacing cumbersome central planning with market mechanisms.
   The party insists it has not deviated from this long-term goal.
   Although China's worsening inflation is in part due to loose
central bank control and the overissuing of currency, a major
factor has been the failure of provincial and local officials to
comply with repeated orders to approve fewer loans and spend less
money on new office buildings and imported luxuries.
   Most of the purchases of cars, televisions, computers, furniture
and expensive appliances that have boosted national consumer
spending to record levels in recent months have been made by
government offices and state-run factories.
   Officials, including party members, also have contributed to the
economic problems by engaging in black market profiteering and
graft. Party discipline and morale, which never recovered from the
leftist purges of the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, has crumbled in
the face of the get-rich-quick temptations presented by China's new
prosperity.
   The People's Daily lectured, ``Our party is the faithful
representative of all China's peoples. We cannot become ... a party
of just one region, just one department or just one work unit.
   ``The party's central leadership always comes first.''
   This emphasis on discipline and central leadership ``does not
contract the development of democracy,'' it added, maintaining that
strong central discipline is necessary for openness and reform.
   The editorial did not specify what punishment would be meted out
to party members who disregard the call to fall in line.
   It also gave no indication whether the Central Committee plans
steps to remove the economic temptations that have led to
widespread corruption.
   For example, with prices only semi-decontrolled, many goods can
be bought both at low prices in state stores and high prices on the
free market. A common trick is to buy large quantities of an item
at low state prices and resell them for profits on the free market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
