<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-Thatcher     09-28 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Thatcher,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Makes Surprise Visit To Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher made a surprise visit to strife-torn Northern Ireland
today amid intense security against a terrorist attack.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who escaped an IRA assassination attempt at a
1984 conference of her governing Conservative Party, was to meet
businessmen and members of the security forces in several areas of
the province.
   For security reasons, the Northern Ireland office said no
advance information on her itinerary would be released.
   Danny Morrison, publicity director of Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal
political wing, said the fact that Mrs. Thatcher could only visit
Northern Ireland when her travel arrangements were kept secret and
when she was guarded by thousands of soldiers and police ``shows
how vulnerable she feels and just how tenuous is British rule
here.''
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army is fighting to oust Britain
from predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite the
province with the Roman Catholic Irish Republic under a socialist
government.
   The IRA has stepped up its attacks on British soldiers this
year, killing 27 in Northern Ireland, mainland Britain and
continental Europe.
   In the October 1984 IRA bombing of the Grand Hotel in Brighton,
where Mrs. Thatcher and several hundred Conservative Party members
were staying, five people were killed.
   A huge security operation swung into action when Mrs. Thatcher's
plane touched down at the Andergrove Royal Air Force base outside
Belfast this morning.
   Accompanied by her husband, Denis, and Northern Ireland
Secretary Tom King, the Cabinet member responible for the province,
she traveled to Londonderry, the province's second largest city.
Her first stop was at the Desmonds shirt factory, which earlier
this year announced a major expansion.
   Mrs. Thatcher's visit was her second to Northern Ireland in less
than a year. Last November, she attended a memorial service in
Enniskillen for 11 people killed when the IRA bombed a
commemoration ceremony for Britain's war dead.
</TEXT>
