<1ST_LINE>r i PM-StoicSoldier     09-28 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stoic Soldier,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Soldier Forgotten At Bridge Stands Guard For Five Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARMSTADT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stoic Dutch soldier left behind
by his unit during NATO maneuvers guarded a bridge in the West
German countryside for five days, a newspaper said today.
   Sympathetic local villagers brought food and drink to Dutch
soldier Johann Romers, 19, who last week refused to leave his post
at the Leine River in northern West Germany, The Stars and Stripes
newspaper said.
   The guard became especially noticeable to West German police
after other Dutch soldiers had left the area, said the U.S.
military's authorized unofficial publication.
   ``That's what I call obedience,'' the Darmstadt-based newspaper
quoted police officer Siegfried Meyer as saying. ``I thought that
kind of discipline had died out.''
   Meyer first became concerned about the soldier on Sept. 21, when
the NATO exercise Free Lion was wrapping up, Stars and Stripes said.
   Meyer had first noticed Romers standing guard at the bridge on
Monday (Sept. 19), the newspaper said.
   ``On Thursday he was still there, although the Dutch had left
the area. On Friday, he told me his unit must have forgotten him,
and I called the military police, who came and picked him up,'' the
newspaper quoted Meyer as saying.
   The soldier, from the Dutch town of Spykenessen, had been
assigned to guard a bridge over the Leine River in the small
northern town of Freden, the Stars and Stripes said.
   Freden is located 37 miles south of Hanover.
</TEXT>
