<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-USBooks     09-28 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-US Books,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Book Exhibit Opens In Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few dozen Soviets browsed through thousands of
hard-to-get American books, such as a handbook on future NASA
missions, Alex Haley's novel ``Roots'' and an atlas with maps of
their own country.
   The exhibit is the latest foreign joint venture to offer Western
products for the foreign currency that few Soviets are permitted to
hold. Soviets can order the books by mail from publishers.
   Despite the currency limitations and the exhibit's
out-of-the-way location _ behind two gates in a corner of an
international exhibition hall _ the American organizers were
grateful for dozens of Soviets evaluating their wares at the
opening Tuesday.
   ``It ain't Gorky Street,'' a popular Moscow shopping area,
acknowledged Martin Levin of the firm Cowan, Liebowitz and Latham
of New York.
   But Gorky Street is next on Levin's agenda. He hopes a store
that accepts Soviet rubles will open within a year.
   Only the few Soviets with hard currency legally obtained through
such means as a trip abroad will be able to order books from the
exhibit, said Dmitry Mamleev, deputy chairman of the State
Committee on Publishing, Printing and Book Trade.
   The yearlong exhibit will cater to Soviet libraries and
businesses with hard currency. U.S. publishers chose to send
largely scientific and technical works sought by Soviet
institutional customers.
   American fiction was nearly absent. The handful of volumes
included Haley's ``Roots'' and Tom Wolfe's ``The Right Stuff'' and
``The Bonfire of the Vanities.''
   The books can be ordered for the regular U.S. price plus 10
percent, but most customers will have to wait as long as four
months for delivery, according to the Soviet government's
distributor, the International Books agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
