<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AcidSpill     09-28 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acid Spill,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acid Spill Forces Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERCULES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals or thieves are suspected of
causing a spill of 1,000 gallons of highly toxic nitric acid at an
abandoned dynamite factory that forced the evacuation of up to 500
people, company officials said.
   An ugly, yellow-brown cloud hung over Hercules and the adjacent
town of Rodeo for about two hours Tuesday before dissipating.
   A spokesman for Hercules Properties, owner of the former
Hercules Powder Co., said the leak in this town about 20 miles
northeast of San Francisco apparently started when someone
attempted to steal the valves from two stainless steel tanks.
   ``An unauthorized person got into the plant, inside the fence,
and they tried to remove the valves,'' said spokesman Tom Stewart.
``We're certainly going to call on the police to investigate.''
   He speculated someone might want to salvage the stainless steel
that the six-inch valves are made of.
   A firefighter who was overcome by the fumes was treated and
released at Doctors Hospital in Pinole.
   The spill forced the evacuation of 300 to 500 people from
businesses, homes and a school.
   Lt. Bill Spencer of the Hercules-Rodeo Fire Department said fire
crews sealed the valves, and people were allowed to return to their
homes and businesses after the cloud dissipated.
</TEXT>
