<DOCNO> AP880928-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Botha     09-28 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Botha,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Marks 10 Years in Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha
celebrated 10 years in power today and said he felt ``fighting
fit'' with no plans to retire soon.
   Botha, 72, was elected prime minister on Sept. 28, 1978. That
post was abolished in 1984 under a new constitution, and he became
president.
   In an interview with the state-run radio network, Botha said
South Africa had ``great possibilities'' if its people could unite
and ``replace violence with deliberation.''
   Asked to appraise his accomplishments, he replied: ``Nobody ever
achieves what he sets out to achieve. I'm satisfied I've made some
progress.''
   In the radio interview and an interview published in Beeld, a
pro-government newspaper, Botha said highlights of a decade in
power included strengthening of the security forces, prospects of
improved relations with other southern African countries, efforts
to bolster the private sector of the economy, and reforms that have
eased some racially discriminatory laws and given blacks a larger
political role.
   Among the low points, he said, were intensive criticism of South
Africa by many Western countries and a split in his own Afrikaner
community because of right-wing opposition to his reform program.
   Asked by the radio interviewer if he was thinking of retiring,
Botha said: ``Not at this stage. I'm full of vigor.''
   Several newspapers today reported speculation that Botha would
soon make another trip into black Africa. One possibility is Zaire,
where President Mobutu Sese Seko has proposed a regional summit
meeting to discuss the war in Angola and other matters.
   Two weeks ago, Botha held his first summit meetings in black
Africa, traveling to Malawi, a longtime friend of South Africa, and
Mozambique, a longtime adversary.
   Domestically, Botha has come under mounting criticism in recent
years both from right-wing whites, who feel his reforms are
excessive, and from blacks and white liberals who say they are
inadequate.
   The president advocates increased power-sharing with blacks but
wants the white minority to retain ultimate political control and
maintain segregated schools and neighborhoods. He opposes a
one-person, one-vote system for the black majority.
   Business Day, a Johannesburg newspaper reflecting the views of
moderate business executives, described Botha in an editorial today
as a ``flawed leader'' who had backed away from a chance to push
the country toward substantive political change.
   The Citizen, a pro-government daily, this week praised Botha as
``the Great Reformer.''
   ``He may have been tough, ruthless, unbending at times, but he
also has been powerful, steadfast, forward-looking and prepared to
risk political reverses for the sake of what he believes,'' said an
editorial in The Citizen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
