<DOCNO> AP880928-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Elections     09-28 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Elections,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty-Eight Parties Register For November Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-eight parties have registered for
Israel's November elections, many of them splinter groups and
single-issue factions with little hope of winning one of the 120
seats in Parliament.
   One group is headed by a diamond polisher who threw a hand
grenade into Parliament in 1957, wounding Israeli leaders Golda
Meir and David Ben Gurion.
   Another party is led by a Jerusalem news vendor whose single
mission is better housing for army veterans.
   ``In each election we have a few strange guys,'' said Sarah
Yitzhaki, spokeswoman for the Parliament or Knesset. ``This is the
price of democracy.''
   Israel's electoral system encourages the formation of small
parties, and in the 1984 balloting, Israel's nearly 3 million
voters had a choice between 26 different parties. Fifteen won seats.
   When registration closed at midnight Tuesday, 28 parties had
entered their ranked lists of candidates, election officials said
today. Seats in Parliament are assigned according to the number of
votes the party wins.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc registered
its list after a last-minute struggle over the placement of two
candidates, members of the tiny Rafi-Ometz group.
   Earlier this month, five Likud members asked the Supreme Court
to cancel an agreement in which Likud promised two safe slots for
Rafi-Ometz to lure them into the fold of the bloc. The Likud
members dropped their appeal Sunday under pressure from Shamir.
   In a demonstration of unity, Rafi-Ometz member Zalman Shoval on
Tuesday joined the Likud delegation presenting the list to the
Central Elections Committee.
   Another registrant was Moshe Duak, 54, who was sentenced to 15
years in prison after throwing a hand grenade into the Parliament
building in 1957.
   Duak, who refused to discuss the incident, said his Topaz Party
would fight for the rights of Sephardim, or Israelis of North
African origin.
   Duak said he walked across the country, often sleeping outdoors,
to collect the 1,500 signatures needed to register a list.
   He pulled a tattered folder containing 2,144 signatures out of
his red backpack and told the committee: ``I don't have a phone,
but you can leave a message at the place where I'm studying.''
   Parties were also required to pay about $7,700 to register.
Benzion Koren, whose ``Movement for the Homeland'' seeks better
housing for army veterans, sold his Jerusalem news stand to foot
the bill, Israel radio said.
   Koren ran unsuccessfully twice before. He sold his restaurant in
1981 and his coffee bar in 1984 to enter the race.
   All 14 parties currently represented in the Knesset have entered
the 1988 race, including Labor, Likud, Orthodox religious parties,
the leftist Mapam, the centrist Shinui and the right-wing Tehiya
party.
   The elections committee will now examine the applications and
announce Oct. 12 whether they are valid. The panel will also
consider demands that three groups be kicked out of the race.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0490,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Demanding Release of Leader Fight Police</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with anti-American film protest. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students demanding the release
of a jailed leader battled police with firebombs and clubs today
and threatened to disrupt Olympic events.
   About 200 students attacked police in a brief clash at Korea
University after a rally to demand the release of Oh Young-shik, a
top radical leader charged Tuesday with violating national security
laws.
   In a separate incident, police arrested film workers who
occupied a cinema house to protest independent distribution of
American films in South Korea.
   About 50 local directors, producers and other film workers
demonstrated against the screening of ``Fatal Attraction,'' the
first American picture distributed directly in Korea by American
dealers. No injuries were reported.
   At Korea University, students pelted police with scores of
firebombs, and some attacked with wooden clubs. Police fended off
the blows with shields, but some officers were hit by firebombs and
their clothes set on fire.
   ``Why are the Olympics being staged when democratic figures are
behind bars?'' students chanted. ``Release imprisoned students.''
   No injuries or arrests were reported.
   Korea University is in northeastern Seoul about 15 miles from
the Olympic Park where the Games, which end Sunday, are being held.
   Student leaders said they will resume violent protests to secure
Oh's release. Leaders said they had planned to refrain from
violence during the Olympics, but would now retaliate for the
arrest.
   Oh was arrested Sept. 22. Authorities say he organized major
anti-government demonstrations during the summer. Radical leaders
have threatened to disrupt Olympic events, including the marathon
on Sunday, if Oh is not released.
   Radical students protesting the government of President Roh
Tae-woo have mounted anti-Olympic protests to demand the Games be
shared with communist North Korea. But just a handful of students
have turned out for the mostly peaceful protests. Most South
Koreans want the Games to be a success and are critical of the
radicals.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to
co-host the Games was rejected by the International Olympic
Committee. The committee said the Games are awarded to a single
city and cannot be shared.
   Film protests also halted operations today in theaters in two
other cities, Pusan and Kwangju, according to the Yonhap news
agency. Yonhap said about 70 film workers demonstrated in front of
another Seoul theater with fewer than 20 visitors inside.
   American filmmakers are being allowed to distribute movies
directly to South Korean cinemas under trade liberalization
measures. South Korean film workers charge direct film distribution
by U.S. exporters will ruin the South Korean market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0914EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Oswald     09-28 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oswald,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oswald's Widow Says He Didn't Act Alone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years after the assassination of
President John F. Kennedy, Lee Harvey Oswald's widow says she now
believes Oswald did not act alone in the killing.
   ``I think he was caught between two powers _ the government and
organized crime,'' said Maria Oswald Porter in the November issue
of Ladies' Home Journal, published Tuesday.
   Testimony by Oswald's widow, who married Dallas carpenter
Kenneth Porter in 1965, helped the Warren Commission conclude that
a deranged Oswald acted alone in the Nov. 22, 1963, assassination.
   ``When I was questioned by the Warren Commission, I was a blind
kitten,'' she said.
   The commission, appointed to investigate the assassination,
concluded it was the work of a single gunman, Oswald. But in 1979,
the House Select Committee on Assassinations, relying in part on
acoustical evidence, concluded a conspiracy was likely and that it
may have involved organized crime.
   Since then, Mrs. Porter, 47, has drawn new conclusions.
   ``I don't know if Lee shot him,'' she said. ``I'm not saying
that Lee is innocent, that he didn't know about the conspiracy or
was not a part of it, but I am saying he's not necessarily guilty
of murder.''
   ``At first, I thought that Jack Ruby (who killed Oswald two days
after the assassination) was swayed by passion; all of America was
grieving,'' she said. ``But later, we found that he had connections
with the underworld. Now, I think Lee was killed to keep his mouth
shut.''
   Mrs. Porter said that in retrospect, Oswald seemed
professionally schooled in secretiveness ``and I believe he worked
for the American government.''
   ``He was taught the Russian language when he was in the
military. Do you think that is usual, that an ordinary soldier is
taught Russian? Also, he got in and out of Russia quite easily, and
he got me out quite easily,'' said the Russian-born Mrs. Porter.
She had emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1961 after marrying
Oswald, who had defected to the Soviets and then changed his mind
and returned to the United States.
   In the months preceding the assassination, a man posing as
Oswald reportedly appeared in several public places in the Dallas
area.
   ``I learned afterward that someone who said he was Lee had been
going around looking to buy a car, having a drink in a bar. I'm
telling you, Lee did not drink and he didn't know how to drive.
   ``And afterward, the FBI took me to a store in Fort Worth where
Lee was supposed to have gone to buy a gun. Someone even described
me and said I was with him. This woman was wearing a maternity
outfit like one I had. But I had never been there,'' she said.
   Mrs. Porter said she hopes the truth will emerge when the Warren
Commission materials are declassified.
   ``Look, I'm walking through the woods, trying to find a path,
just like all of us,'' she said. ``The only difference is, I have a
little bit of insight. Only half the truth has been told.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
