<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0473,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Opposition Political Party Emerges In Burma</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with opposition alliance
sending teams to organize grass-roots opposition and second major
opposition group formed. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``The government...''
TRIMS thereafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition alliance said today it
is sending teams around the country to organize grass-roots
opposition to the powerful military autocracy that has ruled Burma
for 26 years.
   The announcement was made by the National League for Democracy,
which named retired brigadier general Aung Gyi as its chairman on
Tuesday.
   A second opposition group, made up of followers of former Prime
Minister U Nu, also has emerged to challenge the government,
state-owned Radio Rangoon reported Tuesday. The radio said the
Democracy Party was formed with Bohmu Aung as its patron and Thu
Wai as chairman.
   Bohmu Aung was a member of Burma's ``Thirty Comrades'' who
fought for independence from Great Britain during World War II. Thu
Wai was an aide to Nu when the ousted prime minister led an
unsuccessful guerrilla movement against strongman Ne Win from bases
along the Thai-Burmese border in the early 1970s.
   Two other key pro-democracy leaders _ former Defense Minister
Tin Oo and Aung San Suu Kyi, daughter of Burma's main revolutionary
martyr _ were named as top officers in National League for
Democracy.
   Win Htein, an aide to Tin Oo, said in a telephone interview the
alliance has started a campaign to organize at the grass-roots
level. ``We have already sent some people to the countryside,'' he
said.
   Two teams of 10 people are traveling from town to town toward
the central city of Mandalay to help organize local chapters of the
league, he said.
   The alliance will have an uphill battle against the National
Unity Party, formerly known as the Burma Socialist Program Party,
which has been the sole political party since 1962 and has a
well-established, amply funded network throughout the country.
   Western analysts say Gen. Saw Maung, who seized power in a
military coup on Sept. 18, is unquestionably behind the National
Unity Party. He ordered troops to gun down anti-government
demonstrators who for weeks had filled Rangoon's streets with
massive protest marches.
   Saw Maung has called for multiparty general elections but has
set no date.
   The government decreed Tuesday that rebels, foreign-aided
groups, the military, civil servants and ``organizations which
misuse religion'' will not be allowed to form political parties.
   Under the law, political parties will have to register with the
government to contest general elections, but none has yet done so.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann announced the official death toll
since the Sept. 18 coup rose to 348 people, and protesters fleeing
the crackdown on dissidents claimed soldiers had executed
demonstrators.
   The government previously acknowledged more than 250 deaths but
has not mentioned executions. Western diplomats believe troops
killed up to 400 civilians in the first days after the coup.
</TEXT>
