<DOCNO> AP880928-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial     09-28 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attendant On TWA Jet Says Stethem Was Brutally Beaten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy diver aboard a
hijacked TWA jetliner was beaten so savagely before being killed
that when he was given food, he was too weak to feed himself, a
witness testified today.
   Elizabeth Howes, a flight attendant on TWA Flight 847, said she
was shaken when she saw the condition of Robert Stethem after the
beating.
   Ms. Howes said another flight attendant, Uli Derickson, helped
Stethem to the back of the plane after the beating.
   ``I was very upset to see him, and I used to be a nurse. She
(Mrs. Derickson) had to hold him by the arm, support him so he
could walk,'' Ms. Howes testified during the murder and air piracy
trial of Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   ``I spoke to him (Stethem) one time when we were serving food.
As I handed him the tray, the Australian girl sitting next to him
said she would help him with the food,'' Ms. Howes said.
   ``I said to him `How are you doing,' and he just nodded. He was
so badly injured,'' she said.
   Stethem of Waldorf, Md., later was shot to death during the
ordeal in which 39 Americans were held captive for 17 days.
   The jet was hijacked on an Athens-to-Rome flight on June 14,
1985, and Stethem was shot to death the next day.
   Hamadi has admitted taking part in the hijacking but denies
involvement in Stethem's murder. Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt's
airport on Jan. 13, 1987, after customs officials discovered liquid
explosives in his luggage.
   Ms. Howes said she feared Hamadi less during the hijacking than
a second terrorist on the airplane.
   The second hijacker, known to the passengers as Said, has been
identified in a U.S. indictiment as Hassan Ezzeddine.
   ``I believe I was more afraid of Said. He appeared to be more
nervous, especially with a hand grenade in his hand. Hamadi
appeared to be more relaxed with the gun in his hand, and did most
of the negotiating,'' said Ms. Howes.
   Asked if she ever saw Ezzeddine with the gun in his hand, Ms.
Howes said: ``I don't remember. No.''
   Other witnesses have testified that Hamadi had a gun just before
and after Stethem, 23, was shot and thrown onto the runway in
Beirut.
   Asked to comment on Ms. Howes' testimony, Hamadi said: ``I have
absolutely nothing to say.'' Hamadi has often been asked to comment
on testimony without taking the witness stand.
   On Tuesday, another flight attendant said she did not believe
Hamadi killed Stethem.
   Hazel Hesp also testified that Ezzeddine boasted that one of his
friends carried out the 1983 bomb attack that killed 241 U.S.
servicemen in Beirut.
   Asked by Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger if she had an opinion
about who killed Stethem, Ms. Hesp said: ``Yes. But I did not see
the shot, so it is only my opinion. It would be my opinion that it
would be Said who shot.''
   Referring to the Beirut bombing, Ms. Hesp said Ezzeddine told
her and others on the jet that a friend of his had driven the
explosives-laden truck onto the U.S. Marine compound in Beirut in
October 1983.
   ``And he seemed to be very proud of this and told of how he
hates Americans, and wondered how non-Americans could work for an
American airline,'' said Ms. Hesp.
   Ms. Hesp also testified she felt Hamadi was taking orders from
Ezzeddine.
   ``I think Said (Ezzeddine) was the leader. He seemed to be
giving the orders,'' she said.
</TEXT>
