<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Judges-Election     09-28 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judges-Election,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania High Court Cancels Judicial Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania's high court has canceled
judicial elections seven weeks before the contests, saying the
state constitution dictates that the elections be held in
odd-numbered years.
   Politicians immediately expressed disappointment over Tuesday's
ruling, which came after primary races.
   ``It is unfortunate for the voters who have already cast their
primary ballots, and the candidates of both parties who have
campaigned for many months, that these elections will not be held
this year,'' said Morey M. Myers, general counsel to Democrat Gov.
Robert P. Casey.
   Republican State Chairman Earl Baker said he had hoped the court
would have allowed the campaign to go forward because candidates
had been selected in the primary.
   Four candidates who had won primary victories for respective
spots on the Supreme and Superior Court found months of campaigning
undone.
   Acting on a suit by attorney Richard Sprague, the state Supreme
Court issued the five-sentence decision saying the constitution
calls for statewide judicial elections be held apart from other
political races.
   Sprague said he learned about the issue after reading an article
by Duquesne University Law School professor Bruce Ledweitz.
   ``I knew that if it wasn't challenged now it would be challenged
by the first litigant who lost a case before the Supreme Court in
January,'' Ledweitz said Tuesday.
   Six years ago, the court, acting on a Superior Court judge's
request, permitted a Supreme Court election in an even-numbered
year, along with other political contests.
   Casey's administration said it had based its decision to hold
the election on the 1982 decision, which said statewide judicial
elections could be scheduled ``as circumstances require'' despite
separate language calling for them only in odd-numbered years.
   One Superior Court candidate, Walter Cohen, former state welfare
secretary, said he was ``disappointed, a little discouraged but not
surprised.''
   ``The biggest losers are the voters who will be without a fully
elected Supreme Court for another year,'' said Mark Keisling, a
spokesman for another candidate, former U.S. Rep. Allen Ertel, who
was running for the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
