<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CharlestonDesegregation     09-28 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Charleston Desegregation,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Ends in Charleston, S.C., School Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony has ended in a lawsuit
charging that Charleston County schools are unconstitutionally
segregated, but it will be spring at the earliest before a decision
is announced.
   The lawsuit, which was filed in January 1981 and went to trial
last October, alleges that the 1967 consolidation of county schools
fostered racial segregation.
   The consolidation created a countywide school board to oversee
the operations of eight existing local school districts. But the
consolidation left faculty and student assignments in control of
the local district boards.
   Fifty-five percent of the county's 43,512 students are black,
and more than a third of them attend classes in schools that are
more than 90 percent black.
   The plaintiffs _ the Justice Department and the NAACP Legal
Defense and Education Fund _ are asking U.S. District Judge Sol
Blatt Jr. to abolish the local district lines and order better
racial mixing of the district's students.
   The case went to trial last October and, since then, 80
witnesses have appeared in 34 days of testimony spread over 11
months. The last witnesses testified Tuesday.
   Blatt, who is hearing the case without a jury, will receive
final briefs from attorneys for both sides by late winter; no oral
arguments are planned.
   Also Tuesday, the judge ruled against a school district motion
seeking release of a 1980 memo written by the Justice Department
attorney who recommended filing the case.
   The district felt the memo, which was believed to outline
arguments both for and against filing suit, could contain
admissions damaging to the government's case.
   Portions of the memo appeared in a 1983 newspaper article, and
school district attorneys argued that since it appeared in the
press, it was no longer confidential as the Justice Department
maintained.
   But Blatt said simply because a former employee disclosed the
information, it didn't mean the government waived its right that it
was privileged.
   He added, ``I don't think this report contains any information
that is of a dire need to the school district.''
   During the trial, the school district presented testimony that
the consolidation was a financial tool that allowed poorer rural
districts to tap the countywide tax base.
   Some schools were in ``abysmal'' shape when the district was
consolidated and many failed to meet state standards, Billie
Holladay, who served as director of elementary instruction in the
county from 1968 through 1985, testified Tuesday.
   In one school, 30 elementary students were taught in a trailer
without air conditioning. In another, there were no instructional
materials for a special education class, she recalled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
