<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0426 09-28 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KANSAS CITY, Mo.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says He's Ready to Lead Nation, Suggests Quayle Isn't</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Bentsen speech</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen told students at Harry
Truman High School today that ``I'm ready'' to lead the nation, as
Truman did, if something should happen to the president.
   The same cannot be said for Republican Dan Quayle, suggested
Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential candidate. And he also
criticized Republican George Bush for choosing Quayle as his
running mate and for not being a stronger vice president himself.
   ``I think anyone who runs for vice president must earn the
respect of the American people,'' Bentsen told the students in the
late president's hometown. ``And he must enjoy the trust and
respect of his running mate.''
   ``If a presidential candidate does not choose a running mate
with those qualifications he does not respect the importance and
dignity of the office of vice president,'' said Bentsen, who will
debate Quayle next Wednesday night in Omaha, Neb.
   Bentsen, the Texas senator, recalled that Vice President Truman
became President Truman in 1945 when Franklin Delano Roosevelt died.
   ``Harry Truman was ready. Because he was smart enough,
courageous enough and loaded with the integrity necessary to lead
the forces of the free world. He was up to the job,'' Bentsen said.
   ``Like Harry Truman, I'm ready,'' he said. ``Ready to run and
serve with Mike Dukakis. Ready to help lead America to a new era of
greatness. ... And, if anything should happen to Mike, if a tragedy
should occur, I'm ready to lead America.''
   Bentsen's job on the stump generally has been to tout Dukakis
and attend events that complement those of the presidential
nominee. But, with polls showing voter unease with Bush's choice of
Quayle, the campaign decided to use the visit to Truman's
birthplace to step up its attack on Bush's judgment in choosing
Quayle and on the Indiana senator's qualifications for the vice
presidency.
   Bentsen, without mentioning the 41-year-old Quayle by name,
discussed his own experience _ noting that he met Truman during
Bentsen's first term in Congress _ to suggest the Republican was
not up to the job.
   ``Just as we expect a president to be qualified for office and
to be ready to lead America, so must we expect the same of those
who might _ like Harry Truman _ become president at a moment's
notice,'' the 67-year-old Bentsen said.
   Bentsen also likened Dukakis to Truman, telling the students
that during Sunday night's debate with Bush they saw a ``Democrat
in the tradition of Harry Truman, proud of his family and proud of
his country, talking to the people about housing and health care
and national defense.''
   And, in a swipe at Bush, Bentsen praised Dukakis for wanting an
activist vice president not always in agreement with the president
and willing to stand up for his actions.
   ``He does not want his vice president to ever hide behind a lame
excuse that he `wasn't in the loop,''' a phrase Bush has used when
saying he was not fully aware of arms-for-hostages dealing with
Iran.
   On Tuesday in Kansas City, Bentsen lashed out at Republican
trade and budget policies and invited Democrats who supported
President Reagan to ``come home to the party that cares.''
   At a rally at the Kansas City airport, he chided Quayle for
opposing legislation to give workers 60 days' notice before they
are laid off and accused the Reagan administration of sitting idly
by as America lost its dominance in the world marketplace.
   ``They've watched us exporting jobs instead of American
products,'' said Bentsen, who suggested that a George Bush
presidency would bring lax enforcement of the new trade law
designed to open up foreign markets to U.S. products.
   ``One of the messages we send out is Democrats come home,''
Bentsen said. ``Come home to the Democratic Party. Come home to the
party that cares.''
   At his airport rally, Bentsen declared that, ``Dan Quayle lost
the fight against plant closing and the American people won.''
   He also delighted the crowd of about 250 people by saying:
``We're going to open the Quayle season a little early this year.''
   Earlier, at a news conference in Detroit, Bentsen predicted
Quayle would be a formidable debate opponent. ``I think Dan Quayle
is going to do very well in the debate,'' Bentsen said. ``I'm not
so confrontational.''
   Quayle ventured into Bentsen's home state of Texas on Tuesday
but the Democrat said he wasn't worried.
   ``I have great faith in the judgment of the people of Texas,''
the senator said with a smile.
</TEXT>
