<HEAD>With PM-World Bank-IMF</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activists Say Nearly 300 Detained During Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police detained nearly 300 people who staged
protests against finance talks they claim are unfavorable to poor
Third World nations, activists said today.
   A West Berlin police spokesman said 226 people were taken into
custody while protesting the joint World Bank-International
Monetary Fund talks, which began last week and end Thursday.
   Some protesters hurled stones, beer cans and paint-filled
balloons at banks and store windows Tuesday night, said the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said two fires were started at gas stations in West Berlin's
Kreuzberg section during the night.
   Just before midnight on Tuesday, about 600 shield-carrying riot
police broke up a noisy demonstration by hundreds of protesters in
downtown West Berlin, witnesses said.
   Police officers raised their shields and encircled the shouting
demonstrators, then forced them to move toward a subway station,
where they were ordered to disperse, said the witnesses. They spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   At least five protesters were taken into custody for refusing to
obey the police orders, according to the witnesses.
   Kurt Jotta, a spokesman for a committee of activists, said 281
demonstrators were detained during various actions betweeen Tuesday
and today. He said that 106 of those held were freed by this
afternoon.
   Since Sunday, thousands of demonstrators have been protesting
what they say is unfair financial treatment of heavily indebted
Third World lands by the industrial nations.
   About 10,000 police, including 2,700 from other cities in West
Germany, are on duty in West Berlin to guard the city during the
talks.
</TEXT>
