<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrisisLineCrisis     09-28 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crisis Line Crisis,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crisis Lines Face Own Crisis Because of Party Line Confusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELK GROVE VILLAGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crisis hot line for youngsters
that won a presidential award last year is receiving fewer calls
and faces a loss of funds because of confusion with costly ``party
lines,'' its founder says.
   Lorraine La Susa-Weymouth, who started Kids Line in this Chicago
suburb three years ago, said her service was running smoothly until
June 1987, when the party lines _ some call themselves ``hot
lines'' _ became popular.
   The 24-hour crisis line for troubled youths is run by
volunteers, and the only cost is the price of a regular phone call.
   The for-profit party lines allow kids to chat with several peers
at once. Young callers have frequently racked up huge phone bills
and created an uproar among parents.
   Many prevented their children from calling any hot line, and
operators who get calls from youths seeking the crisis line number
often mistakenly give them the number of a party line, said state
Sen. William Mahar, who has joined efforts to clear up the
confusion.
   Ms. La Susa-Weymouth said at one time Kids Line was receiving
1,800 calls a month, but that number has since dropped to 400 a
month. She said the confusion threatens crisis lines nationwide.
   ``Children will call us ... even if they are suicidal, and say,
`Does this cost?''' she said.
   In one instance, a teen-age boy who asked the operator for the
number of Teen Line _ an adjunct to Kids Line for teens _ was
mistakenly referred to a party line, she said. It was not until he
had started discussing his problem that the boy realized his
mistake.
   ``He was just absolutely unhinged because his peer group on the
party line made fun of him,'' she said.
   The service received a President's Volunteer Action Award in
Public Safety, Ms. La Susa-Weymouth said.
   ``Kids are being told that we're a friend they can talk to with
their problems,'' she said. ``It would be a shame if we weren't
there to listen.''
   Mahar said he has been meeting with the Citizens Utility Board
and Illinois Bell to try and iron out the confusion. He said
announcements on radio and television also are planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
