<HEAD>Convicted Killer Gets Wish To Watch TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted killer who asked a judge to
quickly confirm his death sentence so he could watch television in
his cell has been ordered to death row.
   Allegheny County Common Pleas Judge Jeffrey A. Manning formally
imposed the death penalty Tuesday on Gary Lee Starr, 47, who was
sentenced in August to die in the electric chair for murdering his
daughter. Starr said nothing during the sentencing.
   Starr was convicted of fatally stabbing his daughter, Wanda, 20,
in February after accusing her of stealing rent money. He was an
apartment complex manager in suburban Moon Township.
   Since his conviction, Starr had been writing to Manning, asking
the judge to confirm his death sentence as soon as possible so he
could watch television in his cell. He was being housed in an area
of the prison where televisions are prohibited.
   ``Please bring me in and sentence me,'' Starr said in a letter.
   Starr requested the quick action because it would put him in a
section of the State Correctional Institution at Pittsburgh where
televisions are permitted, prison officials said. He threatened to
stage a hunger strike if he wasn't sentenced quickly.
   Manning said the letters demonstrated Starr's ``perverse''
priorities in life.
   ``People may conclude that this man may be nuts, but I don't see
it that way,'' the judge said.
   During his trial, Starr admitted having a six-year incestuous
relationship with his daughter. Sixteen years ago, he was convicted
of fatally shooting his wife, Linda, as she slept. He served 8{
years in prison for that crime.
