<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraq-POWs     09-28 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-POWs,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed Iraqis Say They Were Tortured In Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi prisoners of war recently freed by
Iran said today they were systematically tortured by Iranian
Revolutionary Guards, and some said they were punished for refusing
to defect or convert to Islam.
   About 30 of 72 ailing and wounded POWs released last week told a
news conference they were constantly under pressure to defect. The
press conference was organized by the Information Ministry.
   Christians among the released prisoners said their Shiite Moslem
captors tried to force them to convert to Islam. Some said they had
been in captivity for six years.
   ``When I told them I was a Christian, they asked me to convert
to Islam before they would give me any medical help,'' said Wa'd
Aziz Na'mou, who said he was captured in January 1987 in the
southern Shalamcheh sector after he was wounded in the eyes during
a major Iranian offensive against the port city of Basra.
   ``I refused and they left me without treatment. I lost both
eyes,'' said Na'mou, an agronomist who was serving as an enlisted
man.
   The Iraqis were the first prisoners released by Iran since an
Aug. 20 cease-fire in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war. A full-scale
prisoner exchange, provided for under the United Nations-sponsored
cease-fire agreement, has been stalled because peace talks are
deadlocked.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross has registered
50,182 POWs held by Iran and 19,284 by Iraq.
   Diplomats in Baghdad and Tehran, however, believe that Iran
holds 60,000 to 70,000 prisoners and Iraq 30,000 to 50,000.
   The freed Iraqis showed reporters injuries and scars they said
they suffered at the hands of Iranian guards in POW camps.
   Ministry officials said all 72 men freed last week were disabled
soldiers handed over at the border.
   Na'mou said Christian prisoners were isolated from Iraqi Moslem
POWs by their guards, who considered them to be ``unclean.''
   ``Many of the Christian soldiers were forced to convert to Islam
under psychological pressure and torture,'' he said.
   There are an estimated 250,000 Christians among Iraq's 16
million Moslems.
   The former prisoners said that after the cease-fire was
announced, Iranian pressure on them to seek asylum in Iran
intensified.
   They did not disclose how many Iraqi POWs defected in captivity,
but they insisted that they underwent ``unprecedented pressure.''
   ``We refused and insisted that we had to go back to our
country,'' said Ali Hussein Salman, 26, who said he was captured in
the Tiab area east of the southern Iraqi city of Amara in 1982.
   Salman said he was beaten by guards the day that Iranian
pilgrims were killed in rioting in the holy city of Mecca in Saudi
Arabia.
   More than 400 people, 275 of them Iranians, were killed July 31,
1987 in the violence the Saudis said was instigated by militant
Iranian fundamentalists in defiance of a ban on political protests
during the annual Hajj pilgrimage.
   Salman said his Iranian guards at the Takhti POW camp near
Tehran injured his skull, paralyzing one side of his face and body.
   ``When the news broke that some Iranians had been killed in
Mecca, the guards went mad,'' he said. ``They started beating us at
random. They killed three prisoners and injured many others.''
   Other prisoners spoke of being left out in the snow at night as
punishment for refusing to shout slogans against President Saddam
Hussein and his Baath Arab Socialist Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
