<DOCNO> AP880928-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     09-28 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Ban Rightist Group From Visiting Temple Mount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police kept a right-wing Israeli group away
from the Temple Mount today because its visit last year caused
violent Palestinian protests at the sacred site claimed by Jews and
Moslems.
   Police officers, some armed with tear gas canisters, turned back
about 30 members of the Temple Mount Faithful, a group that demands
Jewish control over the area known in Arabic as Haram el-Sharif.
   Also today, Israeli troops shot and wounded six Palestinians in
the occupied territories, including a 10-year-old boy who was shot
in the head while playing on the roof of his home, hospital
officials said. The officials did not give the boy's condition.
   The army forced nearly 200,000 Palestinians in the West Bank and
the Gaza Strip to stay in their homes after violence in the past
few days.
   In Gaza City, mourners poured into the home of Rashad al-Shawwa,
the former mayor of Gaza who died of a heart attack Tuesday at the
age of 79.
   Thousands of Jewish pilgrims, some singing and dancing, prayed
below Temple Mount at the Western Wall, the last remnant of the
temple, to commemorate the harvest holiday of Sukkot.
   Haram el-Sharif is sacred to Jews as the site of the Holy Temple
destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70 and to Moslems as the place
where the prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven in the 7th century.
   The mount, dominated by the golden Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa
mosques, is administered by the Moslem Waqf, a religious
institution responsible for the care of Islamic holy sites.
   A visit by the Temple Mount Faithful to the site last year
caused violent protests by hundreds of rock-throwing Palestinians.
   Police feared that Moslem protests would be more severe this
year because of the 9-month-old Palestinian uprising against
Israel's 21-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Since
the uprising began in December, 278 Palestinians and six Israelis
have been killed.
   Gershon Solomon, head of the group, said today's ban was
``painful, humiliating and anti-Jewish.''
   ``Jews have no other holy site,'' said Solomon, wearing a
yarmulke, or head cover used by observant Jews, and flanked by
supporters holding Israeli flags. ``We can pray in New York, London
or Paris but not here. It's absurd.''
   In the West Bank, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded two
Palestinians from the village of Zeita, near Nablus, after a group
of youths stoned the troops, Arab reporters and hospital officials
said.
   Earlier, a 20-year-old Palestinian was shot in the left arm in
Nablus, while two other Arabs were wounded by plastic bullets in
the Gaza Strip town of RAfah, hospital officals said.
   Israel radio reported that a Jewish woman was injured when an
unidentified object was thrown at the bus in which she was
traveling in Nablus.
   The army clamped curfews on four refugee camps in the Gaza
Strip, confining over 130,000 Palestinians to their homes following
violent disturbances in the past few days. About 17,000
Palestinians in three towns and refugees camps were ordered to stay
in their homes in the West Bank.
   In Gaza City, hundreds of cars were parked outside the home of
the late mayor, a moderate Palestinian known for his pro-Jordanian
views. Members of his family set up a tent in the garden to
accomodate the mourners.
</TEXT>
