<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brawley 1stLd-Writethru a0497 09-28 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutor Supports State Probe Of Brawley Lawyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `Sharpton said...', to UPDATE with news
conference postponed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. attorney says ``a serious inquiry'' is
needed into the ethics of lawyers representing a black teen-ager
who, a grand jury reportedly determined, lied about being abducted
and raped by whites.
   The case of Tawana Brawley led to an intensive investigation and
charges of a racially motivated cover-up.
   ``I think the way in which this case developed and the way in
which people acted is something that should be a matter of concern
for the legal profession, it should be a matter of concern for the
state,'' said U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani.
   ``It's certainly worth a serious inquiry,'' he told reporters
Tuesday.
   But the prosecutor steered clear of criticizing either Alton H.
Maddox Jr. or C. Vernon Mason, the Brawley family's legal advisers.
   ``I'm not going to single out any individuals and I'm not going
to suggest that anybody did anything wrong,'' he said.
   The state grand jury investigating the case has developed
``overwhelming evidence'' that Miss Brawley fabricated the story,
The New York Times reported Tuesday.
   Miss Brawley, now 16, and her mother, Glenda, refused to testify
before the grand jury. A contempt citation was lodged against Mrs.
Brawley, but she avoided arrest and prosecution by living in a
church. Mrs. Brawley, her boyfriend and her daughter have left the
state.
   Maddox, Mason and the Rev. Al Sharpton, another Brawley adviser,
accused state and local officials of a cover-up, without providing
evidence to back up the claim.
   The Brawley family reportedly was seen leaving their home in
Virginia Beach, Va., early Tuesday in a van loaded with suitcases
for an unknown destination.
   Sharpton said Miss Brawley, her mother and the attorneys would
respond to the report within 24 hours. A news conference scheduled
for this morning was postponed until later in the day.
   On Tuesday, Sharpton called the Times article ``nothing but a
whole series of reckless speculations by someone who cannot back it
up with one iota of fact.''
   As in the past, the black activist charged that the criminal
justice system does not treat minorities fairly.
   ``Tawana is only the last race case that a grand jury has
suggested (was) a fantasy,'' Sharpton told reporters.
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams, whose office presented the
case to the grand jury, said in a statement he would not ``confirm
or deny the accuracy of any aspect'' of the Times story.
   Giuliani's office entered the case when Samuel McClease of
Jersey City, N.J., claimed to have tapes of Brawley advisers
expressing doubts about her story.
   The tapes never surfaced, McClease was charged with obstructing
justice and Brawley advisers accused Giuliani of hiring him to
secretly tape their conversations.
   The Times said the grand jury decided not to indict anyone and
by law cannot criticize ordinary citizens that it does not indict.
   Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28 outside an apartment complex in
which the family once lived in Wappingers Falls, 75 miles north of
New York. She was inside a garbage bag, smeared with dog feces,
seemingly dazed, and with racial slurs written on her body.
   The Times said the grand jury found plenty of evidence to show
she was not abducted on Nov. 24 as she claimed. The panel instead
determined she stayed in the nearby apartment where her family had
lived.
   It said she, possibly with an accomplice, smeared herself with
the feces, wrote the racial slurs, tore and scorched her clothes
and crawled into the bag and pretended to be in a traumatized daze,
according to the newspaper.
   It said that for weeks, she misled doctors, social workers,
police, reporters and others with medical complaints and false and
fragmentary accounts of her fabricated episode.
   The grand jury speculated that her motivation may have been fear
of punishment from her mother's boyfriend for her late nights out,
and that drugs and her relationships with shady characters may have
played a role, the Times said.
   The grand jury report is expected to be released within weeks,
the Times said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
