<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czech-Britain 1stLd-Writethru a0559 09-28 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czech-Britain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Expels Two British Diplomats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to ADD details, background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia has ordered two
British military attaches out of the country for activities
``incompatible with their diplomatic status,'' the official news
agency CTK reported today.
   The expulsions came six days after Britain accused three
Czechoslovak diplomats, including two military attaches, of spying
and gave them two weeks to leave Prague's embassy in London.
   CTK named the two Britons ordered out of Prague as Wing
Commander John Maynard and Warrant Officer Graeme Addy.
   British diplomat Richard Todd said both men have been at the
Prague embassy since the summer of 1986 and were given 14 days to
leave the country.
   British charge d'affaires John Macgregor was summoned to the
Czechoslovak Foreign Ministry today and informed of the decision to
expel the two men for ``activity incompatible with their diplomatic
status,'' CTK said.
   That phrase is commonly used in diplomatic parlance to describe
activities viewed as espionage.
   On Sept. 22, Britain expelled Czechoslovakia's assistant
military attache, Maj. Bedrich Kramar, air attache Maj. Vlastimil
Netolicky and Pavel Moudry, a member of the commercial section.
   The British Foreign Office said the expulsions were a signal
that while Britain seeks better relations with Czechoslovakia, it
will not tolerate ``the sort of activities'' in which Prague's
three diplomats engaged.
   In relaying word of Czechoslovakia's expulsions, CTK used almost
identical language.
   The Czechoslovak side told Britain the activities of the two
Britons contradicted ``the interest in constructive relations
between Czechoslovakia and Britain and is an obstacle to their
further development,'' CTK said.
   In London, a Foreign Office spokesman denied the expelled
Britons were spies. He said the move was ``definitely a
retaliation'' for Britain ordering the expulsion of three
Czechosolvak envoys on Sept. 22.
   ``We have said we want to develop relations with Czechoslovakia,
but the action of the three diplomats in London didn't help and
this does not help either,'' the spokesman told The Associated
Press.
   ``They (the Czechoslovakian authorities) gave us the usual thing
that these men were involved in the gathering of information of an
intelligence nature,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
