<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FatalFires 1stLd-Writethru a0540 09-28 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fatal Fires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Young People Die in Dallas Fire; Burglar Bars Hamper
Firefighters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with further quotes on burglar
bars; grandmother hospitalized, other detail. Picks up 5th graf,
`On Tuesday...'. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM LOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire raced through a house today as firefighters
struggled to break through burglar bars blocking the windows, and
three young children and two teen-agers were killed, authorities
said.
   Fire investigator Don Howard said the blaze began shortly after
4 a.m. on the city's south side.
   Firefighters got there in just a few minutes because a fire
station was not far away, but they were unable to get into the home
quickly because of burglar bars and some furniture at the
residence, Howard said. He says all the victims were found in and
around one bedroom.
   ``Just guessing, I'd say it took at least five minutes longer
getting in,'' because of the bars, said fire investigator Doug
Preston. ``It could have been longer. A few minutes can be the
difference between life and death.''
   Firefighters had to use a circular saw to enter the house,
Preston said. The bars were apparently installed before a change in
city codes required bars that can be opened from the inside, he
said.
   Beverly Handy of the Dallas County medical examiner's office
identified the victims as Jasmine Jordan, 1; Ericka Jordan, 9;
Jamal Jordan, 6; Bernard Jordan, 16; and Demetra Jordan, 18.
Officials were unsure whether they were all brothers and sisters or
whether they were cousins.
   Another child, a boy of about 9, was taken to Parkland Memorial
Hospital in critical condition, officials said, and the children's
grandmother was hospitalized for shock after learning about the
fire.
   On Tuesday, another fire killed a father and three of his
children near Camden, S.C. Authorities said it apparently was
started by one of the candles used to light the family's mobile
home after electricity was cut off the day before.
   The victims were identified as Johnny Lee Gaither, 28;
Stephanie, 4; Sheirka, 3; and Johnny Jr., 7 months. They were
pronounced dead at the scene, Kershaw County Coroner Tommy Horton
said.
   Sheriff Hector DeBruhl said the children's mother, Mary Ann
Gaither, and her daughter, 10-year-old Latasha Kelly, had gone to
an uncle's home nearby to prepare breakfast when the fire broke out.
   Mrs. Gaither returned to find the mobile home in flames. She was
unable to rescue anyone inside the home because of thick smoke.
   Her uncle, Roosevelt Wilson, said the fire ``started all of a
sudden.''
   ``It was a big blaze and we couldn't do a thing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
