<2ND_LINE>PM-Building Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0485,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Body Found In Collapsed Apartment Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with another body found. TRIMS. No
pickup.
^By CAM ROSSIE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers today recovered a third
body from a six-story apartment building that collapsed in
Monterrey and continued to search for three other people believed
trapped in tons of rubble.
   The rescuers, aided by dogs, located the body of a woman. Soon
after the building collapsed on Tuesday, the body of a man and an
infant were found.
   The search continued for two women and a 19-month-old baby
believed trapped when the building collapsed and part of it fell
down a steep hillside.
   Authorities said Hurricane Gilbert may have been partly
responsible for the collapse of the 3-year-old, cement building.
State prosecutor Alejandro Garza said four people were rescued
after the collapse.
   Rescue teams dug by hand and carried out buckets of broken
concrete that had been the building's walls and floors.
   ``The goal is to preserve the life of those that may be
inside,'' worker Trevino Berchelman said. He said three teams of
dogs brought in to sniff through the rubble all pinpointed the same
area where the victims may be trapped but that concrete slabs
prevented rescue workers from searching there.
   Salinas Garcia, who was in his second-floor apartment when the
building collapsed, said he didn't realize what was happening at
first. ``I woke up and the roof was on top of me,'' he said, his
face and T-shirt covered with blood.
   Francisco Javier Nakashima, a local police investigator, said
heavy rains from Gilbert, which struck this northern industrial
city Sept. 17, must have contributed to the collapse. However, he
said neighbors also reported the structure was leaning to one side
six months ago.
   Gilbert caused widespread flooding, killing at least 140 local
people, most of whom died in buses that were overturned by flood
waters.
   Garza identified the dead man as Antonio Rodriguez, 25 to 30
years old, and said he did not know the name of the dead infant,
who was less than 1 year old.
   Hospital officials said two of the four people who were rescued
were treated for minor injuries and released from a local hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
