<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0429 09-28 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Defends Proposal for Tax-Deferred Savings Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Bush quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today defended
his proposal for a tax-deferred savings plan while saying a college
loan program advanced by Michael Dukakis would put ``the IRS on
your tail for the rest of your life.''
   Bush made the comments at Illinois State University as he began
a 150-mile campaign swing through rural central and northern
Illinois, riding in the refurbished campaign bus that had been used
by one-time rival Pat Robertson.
   He told a spirited college rally that Illinois was ``vital to
the election'' and that he planned to be in the state ``again and
again.'' His visit followed by one day a Dukakis campaign swing
through Illinois, which holds 24 electoral votes and is viewed as
critical by both sides.
   Although Dukakis has scorned Bush's new plan for tax-deferred
savings, claiming it will save Americans no more than $20 a year,
Bush insisted his day-old proposal would ``give taxpayers a little
nest egg.''
   He slashed at Dukakis' plan for college loans that would be paid
back according to an individual's future earnings through tax
withdrawals.
   ``We do not need to put the IRS on your tail for the rest of
your life,'' Bush said. ``Under his approach, the government would
give you a loan, then take a bit out of your paycheck for the next
40 years.''
   ``He wants to spend more and I want to put more money in the
hands of individuals, not in the hands of government,'' Bush said.
   Traveling with Bush were country singers Loretta Lynn and her
sisters, Crystal Gayle and Peggy Sue Wright. Bush has been ``behind
the president, watching every move he makes. We're ready for him,''
Miss Lynn said.
   Bush also ridiculed Dukakis for driving a tank during a recent
campaign stop. ``I know what it is doing dumb things but the one
that takes the cake is him riding around in that tank,'' Bush said.
``Don't tell me he doesn't have a sense of humor.''
   Later, Bush chatted with patrons in a small restaurant and
bowling alley in El Paso, Ill., and also planned brief rallies and
stops in six other small Illinois communities.
   Bush's tax-deferred savings plan, which he calls an ``individual
savings account,'' would allow low and middle-income savers to
defray paying taxes on interest income on savings of up to $1,000 a
year so long as the money was kept in such accounts for five or
more years.
   The vice president, unveiling the plan in a speech Tuesday to
the Ohio Republican Convention, said it would help Americans be
``better able to afford a home, pay for college, or start a
business.''
   ``Americans have increasingly gotten away from the sensible
frugality that says, `put some away for a rainy day','' Bush said.
   But Bush advisers suggested afterward the plan was far less
ambitious.
   ``The idea was designed to encourage people to put money into a
savings account, that's all,'' said Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of
staff. ``It's an incentive. A little incentive.''
   Michael Boskin, a top Bush economic adviser and co-architect of
the proposal, says it would only yield about $14 a year in tax
savings for the maximum deposit.
   But, the Stanford University economist added, ``This will be an
important additional incentive for savings.''
   Dukakis was quick to attack the proposal.
   ``Twenty bucks a year _ that's Mr. Bush's solution for average
Americans,'' Dukakis said referring to his calculations. ``He says
it will make them, and here I'm quoting, `better able to afford a
home, pay for college, start a business.' Twenty bucks a year,
who's he kidding?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0108 </DOCNO>
