<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   09-28 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0722</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Sept. 23
   The Sun, Bremerton, Wash., on abortion:
   Supreme Court Associate Justice Harry Blackmun, author of the
1973 Roe v. Wade decision that legalized abortion nationwide, now
is warning the decision may not last another high court session.
   Talking in the circumspect language implicitly required of high
court justices, Blackmun hinted in a law school speech ... that
Reagan appointments, especially that of Associate Justice Anthony
Kennedy, may end Roe v. Wade.
   Blackmun is doing one of at least two things. He actually may be
warning that with the appointment of Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and
Sandra Day O'Connor, Roe v. Wade's days are numbered and so is
abortion on demand in the United States _ at least for some women
in some states.
   Or he's implicitly urging the presidential candidates to bring
the issue to the fore, so ``freedom of choice'' backers can vote
for Gov. Michael S. Dukakis. Vice President George Bush opposes
abortion.
   Or he's hinting that he soon may resign from the court, and the
Senate can allow a ``right-to-life'' majority to slip in if it
isn't careful. ...
   The nation may be continuing its move to the right, enough to
restrict what was basically a 1960s abortion decision. But neither
is Congress ready to make all abortions out of reach for all women.
   Blackmun correctly sees the nation turning a corner on the
issue. But that's not the same thing as reversing one's course.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   The Columbus (Ohio) Dispatch on eliminating trans-Atlantic trade
barriers:
   In 1992, exactly 500 years after Christopher Columbus charted an
important new trade route, trans-Atlantic trade will mark another
advance.
   The 12 nations of the European Economic Community have targeted
1992 for completion of 285 steps to eliminate remaining trade
barriers and thus to create a dynamic single market of 320 million
people. ...
   The marketplace has its own built-in logic. It ought to be
allowed to function with a minimum of artificial, special-interest
barriers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 22
   The Columbus (Ind.) Republic on air pollution:
   Those hazy days of summer are behind us. Too bad the same can't
be said for air pollution.
   According to a report ..., acid rain has landed in our own
backyard. No longer can we smugly dismiss it as someone else's
problem.
   Acid rain occurs when sulfur dioxide emitted by the tall stacks
of power plants and factories mixes with moisture in the
atmosphere. The six states bordering the Ohio River account for
almost 40 percent of this country's sulfur dioxide pollution.
   But prevailing winds were thought to carry the pollutants north
to Canada and east toward New England. ...
   Industry, particularly Midwestern power companies, has long
maintained that the costs of ... additional anti-pollution
equipment will drive up consumer costs while making it less
competitive.
   Those arguments sounded convincing enough when Midwesterners
thought they had little to worry about. Now there's another price
to pay.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on the state of education in the
United States:
   Do we as a nation have to worry about scientific illiteracy as
we march into the 21st century?
   The U.S. Department of Education reported last week that
American young people continue to perform poorly on science
proficiency, both in comparison with their counterparts in other
nations and in comparison with U.S. school students two decades ago.
   The study found that only 7 percent of the nation's 17-year-olds
have enough scientific knowledge to do well in college science
courses, and that more than half of Americans of that age are so
ill-educated in science that they cannot perform jobs requiring
technical skills or benefit from special job training.
   But perhaps more alarming than that, the study found that
science proficiency for black and Hispanic students aged 13 to 17
is at least four years behind the levels of white students of the
same ages, and that a considerable difference in science exists
between males and females of that age group.
   One thing is clear. All is not well with education in America.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   09-28 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: in America.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 21
   The Press-Courier, Oxnard, Calif., on language:
   If there was any doubt that English is a vital, continually
changing language, take a look at the Third College Edition of
Webster's New World Dictionary.
   The recently completed edition _ the first revision since 1970 _
adds 20,000 new words and definitions in an attempt to keep pace
with the restless and innovative society.
   The ruthless world of Wall Street contributed the words ``junk
bonds'' and ``golden parachutes.'' Computer technology added
another definition of boot, as in ``to load, as from a disk.'' The
Soviets gave us ``glasnost'' and weekend loafers inspired the term
``couch potato.''
   The Webster editors who decide which of the new offerings make
it into the dictionary and which don't say they reject suggestions
from children. Does that mean one of the newly included words,
``kissy-face,'' was proposed by an adult? As a Valley girl (a term
that dictionary editors considered, but rejected) might say, ``Gag
me with a spoon!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 21
   The Saginaw (Mich.) News on U.S. support of the United Nations:
   President Reagan's decision to pay the United Nations $532
million in back support represents a ``change of heart,'' according
to the Washington Post.
   We're not so sure. Our hunch is that the president planned all
along to eventually pay the cash, but he wanted to make a point
about bloated spending among bureaucrats and U.S. bashing in the
General Assembly.
   Reagan was right to cut off the money and he was right, if
somewhat belatedly, to pay it back.
   The United Nations still pays salaries that are too fat and
consulting fees that are too generous, but reins have been applied.
Reagan's spotlight stemmed some of the financial abuse.
   Meanwhile, the United States is gaining more respect within the
United Nations, and the United Nations is taking more steps that
favor Western interests. Tentative agreements respecting
Afghanistan, southwest Africa, the Iran-Iraq war and the
Turkish-Greek division of Cyprus are recent examples. ...
   Reagan did what needed to be done. As a result, the United
Nations' most useful years could be still to come.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on government ethics:
   The Office of Government Ethics has used the case of Edwin
Meese, the badly discredited former attorney general, to convey a
strong lesson on ethical criteria for public servants.
   In a report admirable for independence and clarity, the agency
says that ``while Mr. Meese's personal reputation could not but
have suffered as a result of this investigation (by the special
prosecutor), the public's confidence in the Justice Department has
also suffered.''
   The Ethics Office extolled the ``clarion standard ... which
exhorts an employee to avoid any action that adversely affects the
confidence of the public in the integrity of the government.''
   Meese's great fault was that he conspicuously spurned this
standard.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   Farmington (N.M.) Daily Times on Jim Wright:
   House Speaker Jim Wright has once again exercised poor judgment
by commenting publicly on U.S. activities involving Nicaragua.
   The Texas Democrat, who in the past has sympathized with
positions of the communist regime in Managua, criticized what he
called a covert CIA operation fomenting demonstrations against the
Nicaraguan government.
   Wright denies that he arrived at his conclusions from secret
information provided to Congress concerning Central Intelligence
Agency activities.
   Wright and some of his congressional colleagues like to jump on
the administration for ``not keeping Congress properly informed''
on U.S. activities in the international arena.
   When even the speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives
cannot be trusted to respect the confidentiality of classified
information, it is little wonder that the administration is
reluctant to ``tell all'' to the blabbermouths in Congress.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 21
   North Jersey Advance, Flanders, N.J., on higher immigration
quotas:
   In a surprising development, the Reagan administration ...
proposed a sharp increase in admission quotas for the next fiscal
year. It wants to admit 94,000 refugees from around the world,
compared to its request last year of a limit of 72,500.
   The dramatic increase proposed is a laudable response to both
humane appeals and practical foreign affairs concerns.
   The Thais and other Southeast Asian governments, hard-pressed
financially with their upkeep of Vietnamese refugees, implore the
United States to let more of those emigrate to this country.
   And the United States has a special obligation in this regard,
because that flood of boat people stems in some degree from a
failure of U.S. policy in Vietnam.
   The administration has suppressed its budgetary concerns to
advocate this enlargement of the nation's welcome mat, and Congress
should not hesitate to vote the additional funds that will be
needed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
