<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 09-28 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0565,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He'd Bar Former Aides From Lobbying Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after lead</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis said today that as president he would sign an executive
order barring top administration officials from lobbying the
government if they leave their federal posts.
   He strongly criticized the Reagan administration's conduct,
trying to turn the issue against his Republican opponent.
   ``George Bush may be satisfied with this administration's `Hall
of Shame' _ dozens of top administration officials who broke the
law and violated the public trust. He may be satisfied with letting
Japan make the cars while his former colleagues make the license
plates. I say America can do better than that,'' Dukakis said.
   ``George Bush may be satisfied with the revolving door between
the administration and private lobbying firms, where self-service
replaces public service and dishonest consultants are ripping off
the Pentagon. I say we can do better than that,'' he said.
   ``High government office is a public trust, not a training camp
for foreign lobbyists or a vehicle for private gain,'' he told a
rally in Pennsylvania. The executive order would prevent top
officials from lobbying for the duration of a Dukakis
administration.
   Dukakis said he also would issue a second executive order
``curbing agency and department contact with former members of
Congress for some period of time.''
   The Massachusetts governor said he would close what he called
the ``Deaver loophole,'' a reference to Reagan administration
officials who left the White House and began lobbying their former
executive office colleagues. Top Reagan aide Michael Deaver was
convicted of perjury for lying about his contacts with
administration officials on behalf of corporations who paid him
huge fees for his services.
   Dukakis has often criticized the Reagan administration for lax
ethical standards, but this was his first specific proposal to deal
with it.
   His proposal to limit agency contact with former members of
Congress would be certain to cause controversy on Capitol Hill.
Many former members of Congress have joined Washington law firms
and receive large retainers for lobbying their former colleagues as
well as executive-branch agencies.
   Dukakis said his executive order, which he would sign ``the day
I take office,'' would cover all presidential appointees confirmed
by the Senate and all senior White House staff, a total of about
800 people.
   Current law prohibits government officials from lobbying the
agencies or offices in which they work for one year after leaving
government service. Dukakis would broaden that and expand the time
period to the duration of his administration.
   Dukakis lost no time Tuesday attacking a George Bush proposal to
allow low- and middle-income Americans to contribute up to $1,000 a
year to tax-deferred savings accounts.
   ``Twenty bucks a year,'' Dukakis said slowly, his tone leaving
no doubt what he thought of Bush's plan to help middle class
Americans.
   ``Twenty bucks a year,'' he repeated. ``Who's he kidding.''
   Dukakis was also traveling to New York City today for a meeting
with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Dukakis aide Jim Steinberg said the meeting was arranged before
the recent session between Shevardnadze and Bush, during which the
Soviet official praised the vice president for his role in recent
improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations.
   Steinberg said there was no set agenda for the meeting, but that
it would cover the ``whole range'' of U.S.-Soviet concerns.
   He said the meeting would give the two a chance to ``meet each
other and discuss common interests and concerns and to understand
better their respective approaches to U.S.-Soviet relations and
issues that affect both countries.''
   Steinberg said, ``The governor looks forward to substantive
discussions with Shevardnadze, at the same time he's going to make
clear that he's not the president of the United States.''
   Dukakis also had a meeting with French President Francois
Mitterand scheduled for Thursday morning.
   A number of foreign leaders were in New York for the opening of
the United Nations General Assembly session.
   Outlining his plan for an ``individual savings account,'' Bush
said it would allow taxpayers to ``put something away for a rainy
day.'' A Bush aide said the plan would enable small savers to defer
paying taxes on interest income on savings of up to $1,000 a year
as long as the money is kept in such accounts for five or more
years.
   The campaign said the plan, which would be available to those
with adjusted gross incomes up to $50,000, would only yield about
$14 a year in tax savings for the maximum deposit. Dukakis' aides
calculated it would add up to a $20 benefit.
   ``Twenty bucks a year, that's Mr. Bush's solution for average
Americans,'' said Dukakis.
   ``He says it will make _ and here I'm quoting him _ Americans
better able to afford a home, pay for college or start a
business,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic nominee juxtaposed Bush's support for a cut in
the capital gains tax with the GOP nominee's savings plan.
   ``Today, after I pointed that out to him on Sunday night, he
discovered the rest of America and he told just what his priorities
are,'' Dukakis said. ``He wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of
Americans $30,000 and the rest of us are going to get 20 bucks.
That's a new definition of trickle-down.''
</TEXT>
