<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Egypt-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0549 09-28 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0549,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Source: Egypt Warns Israel Not To Delay Implementing Taba Ruling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New througout to CLARIFY that warning issued by Egyptian
Foreign Ministry source, rather than by ministry. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Failure by Israel to act quickly on an
international ruling about an occupied border area claimed by Egypt
could threaten the two countries' peace treaty, a Foreign Ministry
source said today.
   An arbitration agreement signed on Sept. 11, 1986, commits Egypt
and Israel to carry out the ruling, due Thursday from a panel in
Geneva, Switzerland.
   If, as expected, the ruling is in Cairo's favor, it would
require Israel to surrender the Taba border enclave near Elat,
Israel, which the Jewish state has held since the 1967 Middle East
war. The dispute over the 250-acre beachfront area has been a key
sticking point in Egyptian-Israeli relations. The two countries
signed a U.S.-mediated peace treaty in 1979.
   ``Any delays from the Israeli side (in implementing the ruling)
will affect the surviving peace between Egypt and Israel,'' said
the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   However, the spokesman for traveling Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said neither the ministry nor anybody else in the
Egyptian government would have anything to say about Taba before
the panel's decision is announced.
   In Jerusalem, an official of the Israeli Foreign Ministry said
Israel has ``no intention to get around'' the ruling ``or go beyond
the deadline.'' He noted the agreement setting up the panel allows
51 days to carry out the ruling. ``We have said we will obey
according to the letter and the spirit of the arbitration,'' he
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Tuesday, Radio Israel and other Israeli media reports said
the arbiters have decided against Israel.
   ``The ruling on Taba has to be carried out by Egypt and
Israel,'' the Egyptian Foreign Ministry source said. ``The carrying
out of the ruling does not need negotiations, but there will be
negotiations about the civilian procedures to settle the position
of the Israeli structures in the area.''
   After Israel took over the barren beach, Israeli entrepreneurs
established a modern hotel and a beach cabana on it. The reference
in the Egyptian statement was to possible compensation for the
facilities and rules governing Israeli visits to Taba.
   Israel refused to hand over Taba when it withdrew in 1982 from
the Sinai Peninsula under stipulations of the 1979 accord, Israel's
only treaty with an Arab state.
</TEXT>
