<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--JohnsonBetting     09-28 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Johnson Betting,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Those Who Bet On Johnson Are In Luck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Britons who bet on Ben Johnson to win
the Olympic 100-meter dash at 2-1 odds can keep their winnings,
licensed bookmakers said Wednesday.
   The Canadian was stripped of the gold after failing a drug test,
but the four major British bookmakers already had paid out by the
time the results were announced.
   That means that bettors who backed American 4-9 favorite Carl
Lewis, who was given the gold after Johnson's disqualification,
will not receive anything.
   Mike Dillon, a spokesman for Ladbrokes, compared the event with
a horse race.
   ``Once a man is given his medal, that is akin to a horse being
weighed in. Johnson's disqualification came after the `weigh in'
and, therefore, we are settling bets on first past the post,''
Dillon said.
</TEXT>
