<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EngineeringAward     09-28 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Engineering Award,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Technology Prize Established To Reward Engineering Advances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Engineering announced
Wednesday the establishment of a major new international award for
achievement in engineering and technology that it hopes will match
the prestige of the Nobel Prizes.
   ``This award is designed to focus worldwide attention on the
critical role that engineering and technology play in improving the
quality of everyday life,'' Robert M. White, the academy's
president, said in announcing the award named after aeronautical
engineer Charles Stark Draper.
   Draper developed the theory and invented the technology of
inertial guidance systems now universally used in aircraft,
submarines, missiles and space vehicles.
   White noted that ``our society tends to reward the discoverer of
basic scientific principle but overlook the engineer who puts that
principle into practice in products and services that yield
societal and economic benefits.''
   ``We hope that in years to come, the Charles Stark Draper Prize
will be just as well-known and respected an award in engineering as
the Nobel Prizes are today for chemistry, physics and medicine,''
he said.
   According to White, the recipient of the first Draper Prize _
consisting of a gold medal and $350,000 in prize money _ will be
announced in October 1989. The award subsequently will be given
every two years.
   Endowed by MIT's Charles Stark Draper Laboratory of Cambridge,
Mass., the prize recognizes engineering and technology achievements
``contributing to the advancement of human welfare and freedom.''
   Announcement of the award came as the National Academy of
Engineering, a sister organization of the National Academy of
Sciences, held its 24th annual meeting.
   In a speech to the meeting, White called for efforts by the
government to develop a more coherent, vigorous technology policy.
   ``As a consensus emerges on the need for the federal government
to participate in the support of the nation's civil technology base
there is no recognizable or effective governmental mechanism for
doing so,'' he said. ``Whereas we have a reasonably well-defined
science structure in the federal government for support of
scientific research, a technology structure is nonexistent.''
   ``We neglect support for engineering and technology at our
peril,'' White said. ``We have a science policy, but no technology
policy.''
   Also addressing the session was MIT President Paul E. Gray, who
called for renewed development of nuclear power as a way of coping
with the ``greenhouse effect'' global warming largely caused by the
burning of fossil fuels.
   ``We must make an earnest and sustained effort to educate the
public about the risks and benefits of nuclear power in terms that
permit quantitative comparison with other energy sources,'' he said.
   In addition to achieving a solution to the problem of nuclear
waste disposal, Gray said, ``we must develop, build and test
radically different reactor designs that pose entirely negligible
risks of the accidental release of radioactive materials as a
result of overheating.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-28 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Clash With Riot Police To Demand Release Of Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Olympic Security, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students demanding the release
of a jailed student leader fought riot police with clubs and
firebombs Wednesday and threatened to stage violent protests during
the closing days of the Olympics.
   The radicals have been able to mount just a few minor protests
during the Games, and authorities said they could stop any attempt
to disrupt events.
   Student leaders issued their warning after about 200 radicals
battled police at Korea University to demand the release of Oh
Young-shik.
   Students pelted riot troopers with dozens of firebombs, and some
attacked with wooden clubs during the brief clash. Troopers fended
off the blows with shields, but some officers were hit by firebombs
and their clothes were set ablaze.
   ``Why are the Olympics being staged when democratic figures are
behind bars,'' students chanted. ``Release imprisoned students.''
   Police in combat fatigues and visored helmets made several
charges to push protesters back and hurled a few tear gas grenades.
   The fighting was confined to the street in front of the school's
main gate and ended when a shop hit by firebombs caught fire.
Students offered police hoses to fight the fire until firefighters
arrived.
   No injuries or arrests were reported.
   Korea University is in northeastern Seoul about 15 miles from
the Olympic Park, where the Games are being held.
   Student leaders said they refrained from violence during the
Olympics but now would retaliate for the arrest of Oh on Sept. 22.
   Radical leaders earlier threatened to disrupt Olympic events,
including the marathon on Sunday, if Oh was not released. Police
refused to release Oh and charged him Tuesday with organizing major
anti-government demonstrations during the summer.
   Park Seh-jik, head of the Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee,
said authorities were ready to deal with any threat from the
radicals. ``We're all prepared,'' he told reporters.
   A huge banner with a picture of Oh was hanging on the wall of
the student union building inside the campus.
   Radical students opposed to the government of President Roh
Tae-woo have staged anti-Olympic protests to demand the Games be
shared with communist North Korea.
   Just a handful of students have turned out for the mostly
peaceful protests. Most South Koreans want the Games to be a major
success and are critical of the radicals.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to be
a co-host at the Games was rejected by the International Olympic
Committee. The committee said the Games are awarded to a single
city and could not be shared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
