<DOCNO> AP880928-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene     09-28 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene,0941</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fish from the Farm; Hype for Hogs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in six years, the
Agriculture Department is reporting on U.S. aquaculture and how it
stacks up as part of the nation's food machine.
   Overall, the department's Economic Research Service reported
Tuesday, aquaculture production has grown 20 percent a year since
1980. Production includes food and non-food fish, shellfish and
aquatic plants.
   ``Domestic production of food fish and shellfish amounted to an
estimated 700 million pounds in 1987 and was worth almost $550
million at the farm gate, compared with 203 million pounds and $191
million in 1980,'' the agency said. ``Last year, non-food
aquacultural production included, among other items, $71.5 million
of baitfish and $23 million of tropical fish.''
   As aquaculture began to move up as an agricultural enterprise,
reports were issued in 1980, 1981 and 1982, but then they fell
victim to USDA budget cuts. However, people kept eating more fish,
and commercial enterprises kept producing them.
   ``During the 1980s, Americans have substantially increased the
quantity of fish and shellfish in their diets despite the fact that
seafood prices have risen considerably faster than those for some
major competing sources of dietary protein,'' the report said.
   Per capita consumption of all fishery products rose 18 percent
to 20.2 pounds in 1987 from an estimated 17.1 pounds in 1980.
   The largest sources of U.S. fishery products are domestic wild
harvests and imports, the report said. Commercial fishermen landed
a record 11 billion pounds of fish and shellfish last year, with a
wholesale value of $3.6 billion, an increase of 1.8 billion pounds
and $500 million from 1986.
   Imports were valued at a record $8.8 billion in 1987, led by
$1.7 billion worth of fresh and frozen shrimp. Lobster and tuna
were next at $600 million and $500 million, respectively.
   ``Catfish farming, the large aquaculture industry, produced over
372 million pounds of products in 1987,'' the report said. ``Prices
paid to farmers for catfish rose from 60 cents per pound in
September 1987 to a record 80 cents this summer due to tight
supplies.''
   Most of the catfish farms are located in the South, with
Mississippi the largest producer.
   ``Salmon production based in Washington, Oregon, California and
Maine, and trout production centered in Idaho are the second and
third largest aquacultural food fish industries,'' the report said.
   Crawfish production, mostly in Louisiana, was estimated at 95
million pounds in 1987, making it the largest aquacultural
shellfish industry in the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says hog producers
and importers have approved a program of mandatory assessments on
themselves to promote pork and help boost the image of the swine
industry.
   Assistant Secretary Kenneth A. Gilles said Tuesday that 33,534
or 77 percent of the 43,532 valid ballots cast were in favor of the
checkoff plan. Only a simple majority was needed for approval.
   The department conducted the referendum Sept. 7-8 at county
offices.
   Gilles said that since a majority supported the program, the
National Pork Board, which administers the program, will continue
to collect the assessments of one quarter of 1 percent of the
market value of all hogs and pigs sold in the United States and an
equivalent amount on ``all imported porcine animals, pork and pork
products.''
   The USDA issued its order setting up the program on Sept. 5,
1986, and assessments began on Nov. 1, 1986. But the 1985 law
authorizing the program specified a referendum on the checkoff
within 24 months to 30 months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No new long-term grain agreement is in sight
yet, but the Agriculture Department says the Soviet Union continues
to buy U.S. corn.
   Sales of an additional 550,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery during the coming year were announced on Tuesday.
   The sales brought total corn sold to the Soviets in the last
four weeks for delivery in the 1988-89 year that started Sept. 1 to
more than 3.5 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 550,000 tons of
corn would be about 21.7 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.61 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $57 million.
   A five-year long-term grain agreement with the Soviet Union will
expire Sept. 30 and negotiators are trying to work out a new one,
or at least an extension of the current agreement, to take effect
on Oct. 1.
   But officials say the details of a new pact probably won't be
worked out before the present agreement expires. However, the
absence of a new agreement does not prevent further sales to the
Soviet Union.
   According to the current agreement, the annual purchases are
supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and
corn. The Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million
tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting
as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   Prior to sales announced since Sept. 1, the Soviet Union had
purchased 9.05 million tons of wheat and 5.17 million tons of corn
for delivery in the fifth year of the agreement, plus 830,000 tons
of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
