<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CadetsStricken 1stLd-Writethru a0501 09-28 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadets Stricken, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law Enforcement Officials To Study Police Academy Training
Routines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with attorney general
announcing investigation, Dukakis calling relatives of transplant
patient, other detail, Picks up 12th graf pvs, `Grady said...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen police academy cadets who were
hospitalized, including one who required a liver transplant, were
not denied water or abused, school officials said. But the state's
top law official said the incident would be investigated further.
   ``In the last 10 years we've trained 9,800 cadets,'' Gary F.
Egan, executive director of the Massachusetts Justice Training
Council, said Tuesday. ``I don't know what went wrong.''
   The police cadets were treated at hospitals beginning Sept. 19,
the first day of classes, for ailments ranging from exhaustion and
dehydration to kidney failure. A trainee who quit after the first
day charged that access to water was limited.
   At a Boston news conference today, state Attorney General James
Shannon said his department was conducting the only probe into what
happened at the training center, and described Egan's conclusions
as ``his opinion based on a very preliminary, cursory
investigation. It's certainly not the final word.''
   The academy, located in Agawam just south of Springfield,
reopened today for academic classwork only after being shut for a
week. Physical training has been suspended indefinitely.
   Egan said cadets had access to water during training and that
activity on the first day was no more strenous than any other
group's first day at the western Massachusetts academy.
   ``There was strenuous physical activities, as there always was
on that first day ... (but) we have found no one to date that was
denied water upon request,'' he told a news conference at council
headquarters in this Boston suburb.
   The most seriously ill cadet, Timothy Shepard, a 25-year-old
Pittsfield police trainee, collapsed from heat stroke while running
on the academy track and has been in a coma for a week.
   He received a liver transplant early Tuesday at
Presbyterian-University Hospital in Pittsburgh and remained in
critical condition today. A spokesman for family members said that
Gov. Michael S. Dukakis had telephoned them, but relatives had
asked that no details of the call be given out.
   George F. Grady, the state's chief epidemiologist, said the
cadets who became ill suffered from dehydration and exhaustion. He
said 50 cadets who were tested showed slight to mild signs of
kidney damage, which can result from dehydration.
   Lawmakers and law enforcement officials said they would
investigate training at Massachusetts' 12 police academies and
conduct hearings on procedures.
   Shannon said that his department's chief civilian investigator,
a former FBI special agent, has been appointed to head an
investigation. ``No one should make premature judgments. There are
many unanswered questions,'' the attorney general said.
   The training council's chairman, Winchester Police Chief John P.
McHugh, apologized to the stricken cadets. However, several police
chiefs in the western part of the state called upon the academy to
reassign two state troopers who were leading the class that was
stricken.
   Grady said it was believed the cadets became ill because they
drank about one-third of the water they needed for the exercise
they were doing.
   Asked if the cadets were at fault for not drinking enough water,
Egan replied, ``Some of them were unaware of the fact that they
were doing damage to themselves. They had a chance to go home every
night to rehydrate.''
   Several stricken cadets told reporters they could not comment on
their experiences at the academy without permission from
supervisors there.
   The cadet who quit after the first day, Mike Purcell of
Northampton, said the routine was severe and that trainees were
allowed only two small cups of water before Shepard collapsed.
   ``I've been through basic training in the Army and it was twice
as bad as that,'' he said. ``The doctors told me that if I had gone
back for a second day, I could have suffered permanent kidney
damage.''
   A spokesman at Baystate Medical Center in Springfield said
Shepard also suffered kidney problems and several of the other
cadets received kidney dialysis. Six remained hospitalized.
</TEXT>
