<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito-Sales     09-28 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito-Sales,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Buy Rising Sun Flags And Books On Ailing Emperor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since Emperor Hirohito fell seriously ill, Japanese
have been buying more Rising Sun flags and books about the
87-year-old monarch.
   ``We sold 50 (flags) the day after the emperor vomited blood,''
said a saleswoman for Odakyu, a major Tokyo department store. ``In
addition to individual customers, some companies have ordered
almost 50 flags for their employees, but now we're out of stock.''
   Odakyu has sold more than 100 Rising Sun flags during the past
week, the saleswoman said on condition of anonymity.
   The Mikami Flag Store, a flag wholesaler in Tokyo, said it has
sold three times as many Japanese flags to retailers since Hirohito
vomited blood Sept. 17.
   ``Our clients used to order flags only on special occasions like
(for the) New Year's ceremony, but orders have dramatically
increased since about 10 days ago,'' said Haruhiko Mikami, an
executive with the store.
   Mitsukoshi Department store in Osaka has sold about 15 flags
daily for the last few days, a saleswoman said.
   ``Most of the customers are middle-aged, and some asked how to
set (the flags) at half-staff,'' she said.
   At the Asahiya bookstore's branch in the Ginza area of Tokyo,
sales of books on the emperor began picking up after the emperor's
illness was reported, a spokesman said.
   ``Pro-emperor books sell well, but criticism of the emperor
system or himself don't attract readers,'' he said, also speaking
anonymously.
   A Tokyo company rented about 30 sets of the thin, quilt-like
futon on which many Japanese sleep to a national newspaper and has
received inquiries from police stations in recent days, said the
store owner, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the newspaper, which he did not identify by name, rented
the futons in case it had to keep employees overnight to work on
the emperor story.
</TEXT>
