<1ST_LINE>u a PM-US-Israel     09-28 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Dismisses View PLO Moving Toward Accepting Jewish State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres today
dismissed the view held by some senior U.S. and Egyptian officials
that the Palestine Liberation Organization was undergoing an
evolution toward acceptance of the Jewish state.
   ``They continue their acts of terror to this very day in spite
of hints to the contrary,'' Peres said after a meeting with
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   A change in PLO policy toward Israel could remove a major
roadblock to Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid told President
Reagan during a meeting on Monday that senior PLO leaders had come
around to the view that Israel had a right to exist and were trying
to persuade other elements of Yasser Arafat's organization to go
along.
   This view is shared by senior State Department officials, who
detected signs of moderation in a recent speech by chairman Arafat.
   But Peres, who participated in the meeting with Reagan and
Meguid, said he did not understand ``when people say there are
moderate people'' in the PLO.
   ``I know only about moderate decisions because we are not
dealing with the psychology of people,'' Peres said. ``We are
dealing with the nature of the situation.''
   Peres said he discussed with Shultz steps that might be taken to
promote peace talks in the remaining four months of the Reagan
administration. Shultz has warned against a continuing ``vacuum''
in the region.
   But there was no indication that a way had been found to break
the stalemate.
   Peres said there were ``some sweet, sweet definitions'' in
Arafat's speech in Strasbourg, France, but it lacked ``any
realistic suggestions.''
</TEXT>
