<DOCNO> AP880928-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     09-28 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Declares He's Ready to Be Heartbeat Away From Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen, in a symbolic trip to
Harry Truman's hometown, said Wednesday he was ``ready to lead
America'' if tragedy befell the president and he questioned whether
his Republican counterpart could rightly say the same.
   Bentsen, stepping out of Michael Dukakis' shadow to deliver his
assessment of the vice presidency, did not mention either George
Bush or Dan Quayle in his speech. But he made it clear he
questioned Bush's judgment as well as Quayle's qualifications to be
``a heartbeat away from the nation's highest office.''
   ``Like Harry Truman, I think I'm ready,'' the Texas senator told
students at a high school named after the former president,
recalling Truman's elevation from vice president in 1945 when
Franklin Roosevelt died. ``Ready to run and serve with Mike
Dukakis. Ready to help him lead America to a new era of greatness.
... And, if tragedy should ever strike the president of the United
States, I think I'm ready to lead America,'' Bentsen said.
   At a news conference after the speech, Democrat Bentsen meade it
clear he did not view his colleague from Indiana as being up to
that task.
   ``I'll tell you, if they were elected, I'd pray for the good
health of George Bush every night,'' Bentsen said.
   Polls have shown voter uncertainty over the 41-year-old Quayle
and, after weeks of trying to make Quayle a major campaign issue,
the Dukakis campaign decided to dedicate an entire Bentsen event to
a discussion of the vice presidency.
   Bush and Quayle have tried to portray Dukakis as a liberal far
to the left of the American mainstream, but Bentsen tried to turn
the issue around, saying Quayle is an arch-conservative ``much more
in tune with ... Jesse Helms and Gordon Humphrey than he is with
George Bush.''
   Asked if Bush was in the mainstream, Bentsen characterized the
vice president as someone who has repeatedly flip-flopped on
important issues.
   ``I'd have to look at Vice President Bush's latest positions on
the issues to be sure of that,'' Bentsen told reporters.
   And he criticized Bush for selecting Quayle, saying even
Republican senators were shocked by the choice.
   In his speech, Bentsen recalled hearing of Roosevelt's death
while flying back from a World War II bombing mission, and he also
spoke of meeting President Truman during Bentsen's first term as a
congressman from Texas. Later, Bentsen said, he was given the
Senate office formerly used by Truman.
   ``Somehow, sitting in Harry Truman's office made me feel I had a
lot to live up to in Washignton,'' Bentsen said.
   After listing his experience as a representative, businessman
and senator who rose to chairman of the Finance Committee, Bentsen
took an oblique swipe at Bush and the relatively unknown Quayle.
   ``I think anyone who runs for vice president must earn the
respect of the American people,'' Bentsen said. ``And he must enjoy
the trust and respect of the president. If a presidential candidate
does not choose a running mate with those qualifications he does
not respect the importance and dignity of the office of the vice
presidency.''
   That office, Bentsen said, should be occupied by a trusted
adviser to the president willing to ``speak out when someone comes
up with the idea of selling arms to the ayatollah in exchange for
hostages.''
   Bentsen, in another salvo at Bush, said the ``vice president
must be more than a back-up chief executive,'' and he praised
Dukakis for selecting a running mate who differs with him on
several issues.
   ``He does not want his vice president to hide behind some lame
excuse by saying `I just wasn't in the loop. I wasn't in the loop
all 17 times that was discussed.''' Bush has used terms such as
``not in the loop'' to say he was not fully informed about the deal
at the center of the Iran-Contra affair.
   Bentsen also used his visit to Truman's hometown to paint
Dukakis as a Democrat in the Truman mold, willing, unlike Bush, to
take responsibility for his actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
