<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     09-28 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Receives Another Blood Transfusion, Stength Waning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received another blood transfusion
Wednesday and more intravenous doses of nutrients, but a newspaper
said the 87-year-old monarch's strength was waning dangerously
after nine days without solid food.
   The 0.43-pint transfusion was Hirohito's eighth in six days and
brought the total since his condition worsened on Sept. 19 to 6.8
pints, more than two-thirds the usual amount of blood in the
emperor's body, news reports said.
   Kyodo News Service reported that a vehicle carrying blood was
seen entering the Imperial Palace Wednesday evening, but the
Imperial Household Agency said there was no immediate plan to give
the world's longest reigning living monarch another transfusion.
   Palace officials said earlier that the emperor had discharged a
small amount of blood, a sign his internal bleeding had not stopped.
   They said his condition was stable and that by evening he was
resting, but after nearly two days of stable readings his
temperature rose to 100 degrees in the afternoon. By evening it
eased to 98.9 degrees, still above his normal temperature of 95.9
degrees.
   Chief palace physician Akira Takagi said the large transfusions
apparently did not harm Hirohito's heart or kidney functions, so
doctors planned to continue them to compensate for blood lost in
internal bleeding.
   But news reports quoted several private physicians as saying the
emperor's condition remains unpredictable due to lack of nutrition
and high levels of bile, causing jaundice.
   The doctors have said they believe the emperor's swollen
pancreas may have interferred with the flow of bile, possibly
contributing to a festering internal infection also linked to the
internal bleeding.
   In its evening edition, the Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest
newspaper, quoted sources close to the court doctors as saying that
``the intravenous feeding has clearly left the emperor without
enough nutrition, and the weakening of his overall condition is
causing concern.''
   Hirohito has had no solid food in nine days. He has been in
serious condition since he vomited blood on Sept. 19. On Saturday,
his temperature reached 102.6 degrees, but doctors were able to
bring his fever down with antibiotics.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny news reports
that the emperor has cancer and have urged the media to refrain
from such speculation because it might dishearten the emperor, who
they say is conscious and has been watching television.
   Imperial Household Agency officials said that as of Wednesday,
about 647,000 people had signed their names to registries set up at
the palace and at 11 other agency-related facilities around the
country to wish for the emperor's early recovery.
   Another 1.36 million others also signed their names in
registries set up by local governments across Japan, according to
National Police Agency figures.
   Under the Constitution, the emperor has no political power but
signs documents already approved by the government and serves as a
symbol of the unity of Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
