<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Adams-Sex 1stLd-Writethru a0438 09-28 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Adams-Sex, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adams Says Secretary's Overnight was Mistake, Denies Assault Claim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7 grafs new material for grafs 3-4 pvs, With his</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Brock Adams says he made an ``error in
judgment'' by allowing a 26-year-old woman to spend the night at
his house last year, but he denies allegations that he sexually
assaulted her.
   ``These charges are absolutely false,'' Adams, D-Wash., told
reporters on Tuesday. ``I have never had a desire to hurt this
woman or her family, and I don't know why they are trying to hurt
me and my family.''
   The woman, Kari Tupper, a former congressional secretary whom
Adams has known since she was a child, has been unavailable for
comment in Washington State, where she now lives with her husband.
   But she has previously given interviews to a reporter from The
Washingtonian, which plans to publish a story in November's
editions. The story will also appear in Friday's editions of a
Seattle newspaper, the magazine said in a statement today.
   The statement said Ms. Tupper told a reporter that Adams began
making sexual advances to her in April 1985.
   She also said that on the night of March 27, 1987, Adams offered
her a glass of wine at his home and bragged about his sexual
conquests. After finishing the wine, the magazine paraphrased her
as saying, her last memory was going to the bathroom.
   ``She awoke the next morning, naked, in bed besides Adams, and
his hands caressing her body,'' the magazine said in the statement.
She claimed she was drugged.
   Adams' spokeswoman did not immediately return a telephone call
to discuss the article, which the magazine declined to provide to
The Associated Press.
   But on Tuesday, Adams claimed Tupper ``threatened to file a
civil lawsuit unless I paid $400,000 in hush money ... Betty and I
refused her demands _ I will not be blackmailed.'' Adams' wife,
Betty, was at his side during the press briefing.
   Adams, 61, a former transportation secretary in the Carter
administration, said he should never have invited Tupper to spend
the night at his house on March 27 when Mrs. Adams was not around.
   ``I made an error in judgment that put me in a position where I
could be falsely accused,'' he said. ``For that I apologize to my
family, friends and the people of the state of Washington.''
   Tupper was an $18,000-a-year secretary with the House Select
Committee on Aging at the time. She filed a report with the
Metropolitan Police Department on July 24, 1987, alleging that
Adams had ``fondled her breasts and buttocks.'' Adams was not
identified by name in the complaint.
   She alleged that the incident took place in Adams' house in an
exclusive residential section nearly four months earlier _ between
9:15 p.m. on March 27 and 6:30 a.m. on March 28 _ according to the
report.
   Capt. William White III of the District of Columbia police said
the allegation of simple assault was investigated. ``We consider
the matter closed,'' White told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer,
which first reported the story. The U.S. attorney's office reviewed
the case but did not press charges.
   In a two-page statement, Adams gave the following account of the
events on March 27. He refused to answer any questions.
   Adams said Tupper had asked to meet him March 27, 1987, at a
swank Italian restaurant in Georgetown to discuss her job
situation. At the request of Tupper's family, Adams had helped
Tupper secure a position on Capitol Hill after his election in 1986.
   Adams said he called her office that day to confirm the dinner
date, but was told she was ill. Assuming the meeting was off, Adams
went home to play tennis with three friends.
   Later that night, Tupper, upset that Adams had not showed up at
the restaurant, called him at his home to ask if she could drop by,
Adams said. She had visited the house in the past and had stored
belongings in the basement.
   After she arrived, the pair went to a neighborhood restaurant
but it was closed. Neither was feeling very well, Adams said, so
the pair returned to his home to get her car.
   Once there, the woman came back into the house. ``At this point
I told her I was exhausted and was going to sleep,'' Adams said.
   ``I told her that she was welcome to stay at the house if she
was not well enough to drive home. She said she preferred to stay
and then I went to bed, alone. I did not sexually assault the woman.
   ``Looking back, I should have called her a cab, but at the time,
the suggestion seemed appropriate for a family friend who was upset
about her job and not feeling well,'' Adams said.
</TEXT>
