<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-28 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Group Accuses Government Of Killing Nearly 1,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition group accused the
military government Wednesday of killing nearly 1,000 people since
a Sept. 18 coup, and it registered as a political party to
challenge 26 years of authoritarian rule.
   A second pro-democracy group, made up of followers of former
Prime Minister U Nu, also registered Wednesday, and a third
opposition political party announced its formation.
   Some Burmese said soldiers were sealing off urban centers to
prevent people from fleeing to rebel-controlled areas to carry on
the fight for democracy.
   Several hundred students have fled to the Thai-Burmese border,
where large areas are controlled by the Karen, Mon, Shan and other
minority groups. The students are seeking military training from
the Karens, perhaps the most powerful of the rebel groups.
   ``There are tens of thousands of students and monks who want to
leave the cities but cannot,'' said Ko Ko, a 35-year-old teacher
from Rangoon who arrived Tuesday at a Karen camp next to the Thai
border.
   Soe Hlaing, a 36-year-old lawyer from Pegu, said he saw nine
people executed by soldiers on a bridge in the town of Tharrawdy
during his flight to the Karen-controlled areas.
   ``Each was shot with a gun. One bullet to the heart,'' Soe
Hlaing said.
   The key opposition alliance, the National League for Democracy,
said it had not decided whether to participate in elections
promised by the government. Under Burmese law, it had to register
with the government to take part in the vote.
   League spokesman Win Htein said the government must create a
``democratic situation'' by ending random arrests and allowing free
speech and press before the league can contemplate participation in
elections.
   Win Htein accused the military government of killing nearly
1,000 people since Sept. 18 but said he had no proof of summary
executions of anti-government leaders. The government says about
350 people have been killed.
   Win Htein said the league did not encourage the flight to rebel
areas. Some Western analysts said they believed the rush to rebel
areas would have little effect on the struggle between the military
government and opposition forces.
   ``They will rot in the jungles,'' said one Western diplomat in
Bangkok. ``They may kill a few Burmese soldiers, but the great
strength of the pro-democracy side was the mass, peaceful
demonstrations and strikes in Rangoon. And those appear to be
over.''
   Win Htein said the league has started to send teams from Rangoon
to organize grass-roots opposition to the military-backed political
apparatus that has rule Burma for 26 years.
   Retired brigadier general Aung Gyi was named league chairman on
Tuesday. Two other key pro-democracy leaders _ former Defense
Minister Tin Oo and Aung San Suu Kyi, daughter of Burma's main
revolutionary martyr _ are top officers in the alliance.
   ``We have already sent some people to the countryside,'' said
Win Htein in a telephone interview.
   The alliance has an uphill battle to challenge the National
Unity Party, the new name for the ruling Burma Socialist Program
Party.
   Western analysts say Gen. Saw Maung, who seized power in the
Sept. 18 coup, is unquestionably behind the National Unity Party.
He ordered troops to gun down anti-government demonstrators who for
weeks filled Rangoon's streets in protest marches.
   Saw Maung has called for multiparty general elections but has
set no date.
   The government decreed Tuesday that rebels, foreign-aided
groups, the military, civil servants and ``organizations which
misuse religion'' will not be allowed to form political parties.
   The other opposition group to register with the government was
The Democracy Party. The formation of the National Democratic Party
also was announced, but it did not register with the government.
</TEXT>
