<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Miller     09-28 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Miller,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Accepts Resignation of Budget Director Miller</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan announced today that he had
accepted the resignation of his director of the Office of
Management and Budget, James C. Miller III.
   The president said he would appoint the deputy director of the
agency, Joe Wright, as the next director. The agency acts as the
president's budget-writing office.
   Miller, who took over from OMB Director David Stockman in
October 1985, has said for some time that he planned to leave
before the end of the administration.
   Wright has held the deputy slot since 1982.
   Reagan said Miller planned to become a fellow at the ``Center
for Public Choice'' at George Mason University in Virginia.
   Reagan made the announcement prior to a speech on the
congressional appropriations process in the Old Executive Office
Building.
   The president hailed Miller for his service at the agency, as
well as for his work as the head of the Federal Trade Commission.
   ``He played a leading role in removing the shackles of excessive
regulation from our economy,'' Reagan said.
   ``Since becoming the director of OMB he has been at the center
of our battle to bring the deficit down. And it's been coming down
almost from the day he took over,'' Reagan said.
