<DOCNO> AP880928-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-BacktotheFuture Bjt   09-28 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Back to the Future, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Flight: America's Most Important Space Mission Since
1969</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You know something important and
dangerous is unfolding here at the Kennedy Space Center because the
NASA people are so nervous, the industry representatives are so
subdued and the tools of technology are so awesome.
   Not space technology. Broadcast technology.
   They are all here: Skylink 11, Starcam 8, Mundo Latino, Skycom
7, Live Star 5, American Uplink Inc., Satel-Link 4, STAR 9 and, of
course, Space Link 13. To say nothing of Eyewitness News 10 Newsat
and a host of Newstars too numerous to mention. Fifty-five
satellite uplinks in all.
   Not to be outdone by the local TV set-ups, someone at ABC
stenciled the words ``Jennings,'' and ``Gibson,'' on a news trailer
door, presumably so the anchors wouldn't get lost among the sea of
network news facilities. Later, the stencil was changed to an
incrementally less pretentious, ``Anchors Office.''
   On Wednesday, NASA approved Discovery for flight.
   There is much to be nervous, subdued and awesome about:
Thursday's scheduled launch is probably the most important American
space milestone since Neil Armstrong planted his one small step on
the moon.
   In the 19 years since, the United States returned to the moon
five times, developed the Skylab space station, conducted a
remarkable joint mission with Soviet cosmonauts and invented a
space shuttle fleet that made 24 successful flights in less than
five years.
   Some of those missions were exciting and all of them important,
but none was so perilous to the American manned space program as
the one scheduled to start at midmorning Thursday. The Challenger
accident in 1986, with schoolchildren watching all across the
world, cast an exceptional pall over the space program and many
believe the shuttle program could not survive a catastrophe to
Discovery or its five-man crew.
   ``It's got to work,'' says Rick Hauck, Discovery's blunt-spoken
commander. ``We clearly cannot afford to lose another vehicle, much
less another crew. I don't think the manned spaceflight program
could withstand another Challenger.''
   No one expects another explosion, but people are spooked by the
eerie string of post-Challenger accidents that doomed a Titan, a
Delta and an Atlas-Centaur, the previously reliable workhorses of
America's unmanned rocket fleet.
   With the past three years so bizarre and unfortunate, no wonder
the buttonmakers have dubbed this flight, ``Back to Future.''
   The nervousness among the NASA people is easy to sense here at
the launch site. Space workers will not soon take for granted that
in a do-or-die business, the good guys always do. Yet aside from
the danger to man and machine, there is an almost palpable threat
to the nation's spirit of adventure and challenge. Notwithstanding
an assurance from one top NASA official that the program would go
on, no matter what, 16,000 people work at Kennedy Space Center and
practically every one of them believes that Hauck is right _ the
loss of Discovery would ground the shuttle program again, probably
forever.
   Industry is subdued in part because NASA has set an all-business
tone to its back-to-spaceflight mission, and in part because a
Utah-based rocketry company named Morton Thiokol Inc. was held
largely to blame for the Challenger accident. Thiokol was an
ambitious self-promoter in the do-not-die days of the shuttle
program, at one point making up posters which showed a waving
American flag against the background of a particularily spectacular
shuttle launch.
   ``Way to go America,'' crowed the Thiokol poster.
   It was shocking to learn during the Challenger investigations
that a Thiokol official had been ordered by superiors to ``take off
his engineering hat and put on his management hat,'' an edict that
undermined company engineers who opposed making the cold-weather
launch.
   Thiokol has been paying liability money ever since to the
Challenger astronauts' survivors, and the launch-site demeanor has
changed for all the contractors. There are still souvenirs floating
around the space center, but the industry news center is a work
room again and the company representatives are less boosterish,
more tentative.
   On the wall behind the Thiokol booth hangs a color photograph
depicting the five Discovery astronauts along with a printed
reminder _ perhaps to the people wearing Thiokol management hats:
``The STS-26 Crew is Counting on You!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITORS NOTE: Jonathan Wolman, AP's assistant bureau chief in
Washington, has covered the shuttle program since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
