<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Party     09-28 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Party,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Criticizes Disunity, Lax Discipline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party on Wednesday harshly
criticized undisciplined members and said they were helping to
increase inflation and corruption that threaten economic reform.
   A front-page editorial in the party newspaper, the People's
Daily, accused local party units of seeking ways to profit
illegally from the inflation and short supplies and ignoring orders
from Beijing to cut spending.
   ``Those who don't abide by the party's discipline must be
punished,'' the party warned in its harshest indictment of the role
that officials and party members have played in the growing
economic disorder.
   The editorial probably was approved by the party's top
policy-making Central Committee, which began a closed-door,
five-day session Monday. The committee is expected to approve a
two-year moratorium on price reform and measures to control
inflation and excessive capital construction.
   China's Supreme Court meanwhile ordered lower courts to punish
government officials found guilty of profiteering and speculation.
   ``Those officials have seriously disrupted the normal economic
environment and hampered the smooth progress of China's reform and
construction,'' the court said.
   It ordered an end to fining guilty officials rather than
bringing criminal charges against them.
   Inflation has soared from about 7 percent last year to more than
20 percent this year. Overspending by government offices and
state-run factories and widespread speculation have been major
factors, although issuing too much currency and loose credit also
is to blame.
   Reports appear in the official media almost daily about local
government officials and factory managers, many party members, who
bought goods at state-subsidized prices and resold them on the
black market for huge profits.
   The People's Daily lectured party members to put the collective
good above individual profit. It repeatedly stressed that ``the
individual must submit to the organization'' and lower-level party
organs to higher ones.
   ``We must enforce party discipline to guarantee the benefit of
the whole,'' it said. ``Strict discipline and unanimous action are
good traditions of our party.''
   The editorial did not address recent unconfirmed reports of
divisions in the party's highest ranks over what economic course to
take.
   Some foreign reports suggest that General Secretary Zhao Ziyang,
who a year ago promoted rapid decentralization of the economy, has
been sidelined in economic policy-making because of the high
inflation and a surge of bank withdrawals and panic buying.
   But foreign diplomats believe Zhao is not in serious political
trouble even though his plan for rapid change has been shelved.
   A party work meeting before the Central Committee session
announced that restoring order would be the main task of the next
two years, putting planned price and wage reforms on hold.
   Officials insist they have not abandoned their long-term goal of
modernizing the economy by replacing cumbersome central planning
with market mechanisms.
   But Chinese and foreign economists note that market mechanisms
cannot function properly until artificially low, state-set prices
are allowed to fluctuate with supply and demand.
   The freeze in price reform also means the irrational pricing
that has encouraged black marketeering will continue, hampering the
party's disciplinary drive.
</TEXT>
