<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UrbanTeachersStudy     09-28 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Urban Teachers Study,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Lack of Resources Stunts Teacher Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of educators in urban schools
indicates that a lack of resources and staff creates a negative
environment which decreases teacher effectiveness, a report
released Wednesday said.
   ``Our study shows what other studies have not looked at _ that
working conditions do make a difference,'' said Tom Corcoran, a
researcher with the Institute for Educational Leadership. ``They
effect people's willingness to commit to the school, perform their
jobs and how much work they are willing to give, their motivation.''
   Corcoran said the institute's study, entitled ``Working in Urban
Schools,'' validates ``what teachers' surveys had been saying for
years.''
   ``It's a practical matter to the extent that if you provide
better working conditions you get better work out of people and
kids,'' he said.
   The non-profit, Washington-based institute interviewed more than
400 teachers, principals and administrators at 31 schools in five
cities: Detroit, Denver, Indianapolis, New Orleans and Rochester,
N.Y.
   The findings in the 161-page report were endorsed by the
nation's main teacher unions _ the American Federation of Teachers
and the National Education Association.
   Of the educators interviewed, 75 percent said resources such as
teaching material and equipment were inadequate and more than 85
percent said insufficient staff was a problem.
   Thirty-four percent said poor working conditions _ including
run-down school buildings and heavy workloads for teachers _ were
hurting teacher performance. More than 40 percent said these
conditions were undermining teacher morale.
   ``We can't allow short-term needs _ supplies, physical plant,
etc. _ to denigrate teachers' morale to the point that long-term
goals and objectives are put off or forgotten,'' Michael Usdan,
institute president, said in a statement.
   Corcoran added: ``There was little disagreement among
respondents _ not just disgruntled teachers crying for more
dollars. Principals and school administrators echoed these
concerns.''
   Rachel Hedding, a member of the Rochester, N.Y. school board,
said the study ``tells you specifically what things will make it
better for adults and, therefore, for children.''
   More than half of the school staff members surveyed reported
problems with inadequate working space, which they attributed to
overenrollment, reductions in class sizes and space requirements
for special programs.
   The study said ``one respondent underscored the pessimism by
noting that her school had turned closets into classrooms, placed
the ditto machine in the women's restroom and the special education
staff into an unsafe closet with no ventilation, no windows and
exposed heating pipes.''
   Teachers often requested more support staff _ counselors,
specialists, social workers, security staff, nurses, teachers aides
_ rather than more classroom teachers.
   One teacher said, ``We are just able to deal with crisis
intervention _ no time for follow-through.''
   The survey recommended that school districts try to duplicate
conditions found in the best schools _ adequately maintained
physical plants, staff collegiality, teacher involvement in
decision-making and a sensitive but strong administrative
leadership.
   ``When these (factors) are present,'' the study said, ``teachers
are ready to commit long hours, under minimally adequate
conditions, to meet the needs of students.''
</TEXT>
