<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-28 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTER, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This little piggy is to go to the market,
but her friends want her at home.
   Park officials at the Indiana Dunes National Lakeshore plan to
take Adrienne the pig to the butcher, but some people have launched
a save-the-pig petition drive.
   The pig, which is more than a year old, is one of several
animals at Chellberg Farm.
   ``The farm is being run as it was in the 1880s, and pigs go to
market,'' said Glen Alexander, assistant lakeshore superintendent.
``We don't feel that it's in the interest of good historical
representation ... to not market pigs.''
   But Adrienne's friends say she is no ordinary pig.
   ``It's like a petting zoo here,'' said Susie Cutler, a lawyer
who works in Chicago. ``Everyone's gotten attached to her. .. .This
is a silly policy.''
   Alexander counters that it is the park service's role to educate
children about the facts of life. He says one of those facts is
that pigs aren't pets.
   ``We're trying to teach children that one raises little pigs for
market size and markets them and makes them into the things they
eat for breakfast,'' he said.
   Adrienne's supporters will present 300 signatures on its
petition next week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENOA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxpayers here danced the night away, and may
have paid for street lights at the same time.
   About $35,000 was raised during Genoa's ``Candy Dance,'' a town
fund-raiser held last weekend. The dance started in 1919 as an
alternative to taxes to pay for improvements in this tiny town.
   Organizers said the take beats last year's dance revenues of
about $28,000. This year's dance, dinner and crafts fair drew an
estimated 20,000 people.
   Lillian Finnegan, daughter of a Genoa judge, started the event
after seeing a shipboard fund-raiser during a sea cruise. Women
passengers made candy and sold it to men. She suggested Genoa try
the same thing.
   The idea caught on, and since then, with only one lapse in 1963,
the dance has raised money to pay for street lights, fire trucks,
copy machines, snowplows and other items.
</TEXT>
