<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0644,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Commander Says Lebanon Will Not Be Partitioned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with three killed, 20 wounded
from bombing, no claim of responsibility; pickup 3rd graf pvs,
`Aoun, 53...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONA-ABU NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun
said Wednesday his troops will prevent Lebanon from being
partitioned. Rival Moslem and Christian cabinets appeared to take
steps to avoid a confrontation.
   Late Wednesday, a car bomb exploded at a Syrian army checkpoint
just south of Beirut, killing five people and injuring 21, police
said. They said five Syrian soldiers were among the injured. No one
claimed responsibility.
   Aoun, 53, made his pledge in an order of the day to the
42,000-man army.
   ``The Lebanese army is the only source to save Lebanon from
partition in spite of all regional and international pressures. ...
The solution is through you, and with you the crisis will end,''
the order said.
   ``Any other solution without you will fail. You know perfectly
well that nothing but the army can save Lebanon from occupation and
partition,'' Aoun said.
   Aoun was rejected by Lebanon's Moslem majority after he was
appointed prime minister by President Amin Gemayel on Thursday in
the last minutes of the president's term.
   Parliament failed to elect a new president, and Gemayel named a
new cabinet to serve as an interim government. The appointment
violated an unwritten covenant requiring the president to be a
Christian, the prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the Parliament
speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   Aoun directly controls four brigades of about 15,000 men based
in east Beirut and the Christian heartland north of the capital.
   Five other brigades of about 18,000 men based in west Beirut and
southern, northern and eastern Lebanon, have pledged allegiance to
the government of Syrian-backed acting prime minister Salim Hoss, a
Sunni Moslem.
   The Hoss government was scheduled to meet on Wednesday with the
intention of firing Aoun and naming a pro-Syrian Maronite Catholic
officer as commander of the army, sources close to Hoss said.
   ``But Hoss called off the meeting and delayed the appointment of
a new army commander to avert a further escalation in a conflict
between the two governments,'' one source said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   In another move apparently aimed at defusing the tension, Hoss,
who heads the Syrian-backed five-man cabinet, told reporters at his
west Beirut residence that his cabinet will not make any decisions
that will confuse government and civil service departments.
   ``We shall try to keep them going the way they have been before
the crisis developed,'' Hoss said.
   Aoun and Hoss have issued contradictory directives to civil
servants since last Thursday.
   Aoun, in his statement to the army, did not mention the Hoss
government, which all his previous statements branded illegal.
   Also Wednesday, former president Suleiman Franjieh, one of
Syria's strongest Maronite Catholic allies in Lebanon, arrived in
west Beirut a day before the start of a conference of pro-Syrian
leaders opposed to Aoun.
   It was Franjieh's first visit to Beirut's Moslem sector since
the outbreak of Lebanon's civil war in 1975 when he was president.
   Syria, Lebanon's main power broker, backed 78-year-old Franjieh
in August's presidential election, touching off a confrontation
with right-wing Christian militants.
   In a related development, the new U.S. ambassador urged Moslems
and Christians to speedily elect a new president to resolve the
impasse.
   Ambassador John McCarthy met with Moslem leaders to discuss the
current deadlock.
   He met with Sheik Hassan Khaled, spiritual head of the Sunni
Moslem sect; Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin, spiritual head of the
Shiite sect; and Nabih Berri, the main Shiite Moslem militia
chieftain.
   McCarthy told reporters he stressed to the Moslem leaders the
importance of carrying out the elections as soon as possible.
   ``It seems to me that the religious leaders of Lebanon have a
very firm grip on what is needed for this country,'' McCarthy added.
</TEXT>
