<1ST_LINE>u p AM-JacksonAds     09-28 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Ads,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Black Ad Campaign Thus Far Lacks Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dukakis campaign unveiled advertisements
aimed at the black community Wednesday, but they lacked the voice
and image of the nation's most prominent black leader, Jesse
Jackson.
   Producers of the $3 million-plus ad campaign said Jackson thus
far had been unavailable to spend two or three hours taping radio
and television spots, but said they were confident of recording him
this week.
   ``He is committed to making advertising,'' said Frank L. Mingo,
president of the agency hired by Michael Dukakis' presidential
campaign to produce the ads. ``We simply haven't been able to catch
up with him.''
   Jackson last visited New York on Saturday. ``He is planning to
tape,'' said a spokeswoman in Chicago, Tanya Mitchell. Asked when,
she said, ``We don't have any information to release on that just
yet.''
   Mingo's print ads for Dukakis do not include a photograph of
Jackson. They do bear a quote _ ``10 reasons why we must work for,
fight for, vote for Michael Dukakis'' _ over Jackson's name and a
listing of the reasons.
   The print ads show a photo of Dukakis shaking hands with a black
woman as another black woman looks on.
   ``We made the decision that if we made a photo of Rev. Jackson
maybe it looks more like a Rev. Jackson ad,'' Mingo said at a news
conference in his Manhattan office. ``This is a Dukakis ad. I mean,
he is the candidate.''
   There has been friction between Jackson and the Dukakis campaign
over Jackson's role in the campagin. However, Mingo said that has
passed, citing Jackson' praise for Dukakis last week before the
Congressional Black Caucus.
   Other black leaders in the advertising campaign include Reps.
William Gray of Pennsylvania, Mickey Leland of Texas, John Lewis of
Georgia, Mervyn Dymally of California and Floyd Flake of New York
and the Washington, D.C., delegate, Walter Fauntroy.
   Mingo said ads would be placed in national black magazines and
newspapers and in 15 broadcast markets, beginning this week.
   ``It is far easier for me to go to Washington and grab a bunch
of congressmen and sit them down in a room than it is to find Rev.
Jackson,'' Mingo said. ``You have to track him down on his own
terms and you have to sit him down.''
   ``We are working with his staff to schedule time to do it,''
Mingo said. ``And of course, some of that has to be when he wants
to do it.''
</TEXT>
