<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ShuttleRescue Bjt   09-28 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Rescue, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Pararescue Jumpers Poised to Aid Shuttle Astronauts</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force ``pararescue
jumpers'' will be on alert Thursday across the Atlantic Ocean from
Cape Canaveral, ready to help rescue the Discovery astronauts
should they need to use the space shuttle's new escape system.
   Eighteen of the so-called ``PJs'' were dispatched last Wednesday
from here to Gambia and Morocco on Africa's northwest coast. They
are members of the 1730th Pararescue Squadron, the only unit in the
U.S. military dedicated solely to rescue work.
   Nine jumpers from the New York Air National Guard are stationed
at Patrick Air Force Base near Cape Canaveral to provide rescue
assistance should the astronauts bail out of the shuttle closer to
Florida than to Africa. Also working out of Patrick are 18 other
PJs aboard rescue helicopters.
   Members of the 1730th _ all experienced jumpers and trained as
paramedics _ approached the shuttle assignment with enthusiasm.
   ``They usually trample each other to get a mission,'' Col.
Edward Behling, the squadron commander, said in an interview.
``It's like a fire department. You only get a fire once in a
while.''
   The shuttle escape system, ordered by Congress after the
Challenger disaster nearly three years ago, can be used only after
the spacecraft's solid rocket boosters are jettisoned two minutes
into the flight. Thus the new system would not have saved the
Challenger astronauts.
   If the shuttle fails to reach orbit once the boosters drop off,
the astronauts could attempt to slide out an escape hatch and
parachute into the ocean. With the mission more than two minutes
underway, the escape would likely be closer to Africa than the U.S.
Atlantic coast.
   ``We'll be there to catch them if they fall,'' said Tech. Sgt.
John Smith, who heads the group deployed in Morocco.
   Each of the two nine-member groups jump from a C-130 Hercules
cargo plane. The astronauts probably would scatter several miles
apart. Each has an emergency transmitter that would automatically
activate and a motorized rubber boat and medical supplies would be
parachuted from 3,000 feet _ along with the PJs _ once astronauts
were located.
   Three-person PJ teams would man their boats and begin picking up
astronauts, each working toward the middle of the drop area where
several life rafts and survival material would be located.
   ``Our first concern is finding the astronauts,'' said Smith.
``The second is that the C-130 have enough fuel to stay above the
search area and give us vectors to where each of the astronauts
are. If you're out there in rough waters you can't see someone
who's 20 feet away because of the swells.''
   Each PJ is trained to administer drugs and intravenous solutions
if necessary, Behling said. Experience with pilots who have ejected
from aircraft indicates medical attention often is necessary to
treat broken bones and other injuries.
   The shuttle duty is similar to normal rescue operations
performed by the squadron. But it did require development and
acquisition of the motorized inflatable boats, equipment long in
the planning stage but stuck there until NASA requested assistance
with the astronaut rescue system.
   ``NASA for some reason raises people's priorities in the Air
Force,'' Behling said. He said the motorized boats will improve the
unit's overall rescue capability.
   The 1730th has a long association with the space program.
   The Navy had primary responsibility for recovering space
capsules that landed in the Atlantic after their missions. The
1730th was on standby during those earlier flights and Behling said
at least twice Air Force PJs located astronaut crews from
spacecraft that landed further than expected from Navy ships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0151 </DOCNO>
