<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Maffie     09-28 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Maffie,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Survivor Of Those Convicted in Brink's Robbery Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph ``Jazz'' Maffie, the last survivor of those
convicted in the 1950 Brink's robbery that was then the largest in
U.S. history, has died. He was 77.
   Maffie died Sunday at Brigham and Women's Hospital after a long
illness.
   There were 11 participants in the Jan. 17, 1950, robbery, in
which seven men wearing Halloween masks took $1.2 million in cash
and $1.5 million in checks and securities from the Brink's counting
room in Boston.
   It took the FBI six years to solve the case, and eventually nine
men went to prison. But only $57,000 was ever recovered.
   Where did all the money go?
   ``Gambling and supporting a family for six years prior to our
arrest,'' Francis ``Sandy'' Richardson said during a 1977 publicity
stunt at the scene of the crime to promote ``The Brink's Job,'' a
book and film about the heist.
   Authorities sai the robbery was planned in Maffie's living room.
   Maffie was convicted of armed robbery in 1956 and sentenced to
life in prison, but his sentence was commuted by then-Gov. John
Volpe, and he was released on Dec. 22, 1969, after serving nearly
14 years.
   The other men convicted in the robbery who were still alive got
out of prison between 1967 and 1971. Five of the robbers worked
with the authors of ``The Brink's Job'' for a share of the profits.
   After being released, Maffie joined his family in Quincy and
worked as a car salesman.
   He had scrapes with the law as a youth and was convicted of tax
evasion in 1952.
   He is survived by a son, a daughter, three brothers, a sister,
four grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
   A funeral Mass was scheduled Thursday in Sacred Heart Church in
North Quincy.
</TEXT>
