<HEAD>FBI Investigating Police Activities Following Clash After Football
Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI confirms it is investigating
allegations that officers beat three black people during a clash
between high school students and police outside a pizza parlor
earlier this month.
   ``Police were extremely barbaric and instigated the incident,''
said the Rev. George Ferrell. ``We are not going to stand for this
type of behavior.''
   J. Stewart Murphy, a spokesman for the FBI in Jackson, said
Tuesday that the complaint was being investigated, and findings
will be sent to the U.S. office of civil rights in Washington.
   Ferrell, a member of a black citizens group that is conducting
its own investigation of the incident, said a black man and his
wife were struck by police on Sept. 16 in the parking lot of the
restaurant. Police had been called there to quell fights among high
school students after a football game.
   In addition, Ferrell said, racial slurs were directed at the
couple and their 4-year-old daughter. He said that a short time
later, a man was beaten after he inquired about the police's action
against the couple.
   All three adults were arrested _ Ercolani D. Pauline, 22; his
20-year-old wife, Bettina; and Wilbert Green, 20, all of Clinton.
They were each charged with disorderly conduct, resisting arrest
and assault on a police officer, Police Chief Don Byington said.
   Ferrell said the three had been to the Friday night Callway
High-Clinton High football game and stopped by the restaurant
afterward.
   Byington said he believed his officers acted properly during the
clash at the restaurant, which carried over from trouble among fans
at the football game.
   ``There were several fights that were broken up at the game,''
he said. After the game, several hundred young people converged at
the restaurant, and the restaurant manager called police when
fights developed in the parking lot, Byington said.
   Ferrell said he believed the Sept. 16 incident was behind recent
shoving and purshing incidents between black and white students at
Clinton High School.
   Green said he had been advised not to comment. The Paulines
couldn't be reached for comment; there was no answer Wednesday at
the telephone listed in Clinton.
