<DOCNO> AP880928-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Risk     09-28 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Risk,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA: Another Accident Would Mean ``One Heck of Another
Investigation''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA officials, who have said since
the Challenger disaster that spaceflight will never be risk-free,
were asked on Wednesday what would happen if there were another
catastrophe.
   ``I think the space program certainly will survive in any
case,'' deputy administrator Dale D. Myers told reporters on the
eve of Discovery's flight.
   ``We've done everything we know to make a safe flight out of
this thing; we are certainly aware there is risk in programs of
this nature. We think it's a low enough risk that we are
recognizing it and accepting that risk.''
   Myers said it is inevitable that spaceflight will continue.
   ``Americans want to explore,'' he said. ``I think the world
wants to explore. A manned spaceflight program is the next frontier
that man has always reached for. I don't think there would be a
secession of manned space flight.''
   But, Myers added, ``I think there would be one heck of another
investigation before we got under way again.''
</TEXT>
