<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathRow     09-28 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Row,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Remains On Death Row 18 Months After Execution Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severely retarded prisoner is still on
Georgia's death row 18 months after a state Supreme Court barred
his execution.
   His trial judge retired, his attorneys went on to other matters
and the prisoner, Johnny Mack Westbrook, apparently fell through
the cracks.
   ``The whole thing sort of slipped my mind,'' said Joe Briley,
district attorney for the Ocmulgee Circuit. ``He's been in no
danger of being executed. His attorney and I have discussed how the
resentencing would be handled. But you know you get involved in
other things and you just never get back to it.''
   Westbrook's attorney, Charles Mathis of Milledgeville, said he
had discussed the case with Briley. ``I don't think I left him in
the lurch,'' Mathis said recently.
   Psychologists say Westbrook has an IQ of 25 to 50 and a mental
capacity of a child 3 to 8 years old.
   Defense attorneys argued that Westbrook had followed another man
in 1977 when the pair kidnapped and killed two women.
   Although Briley admitted that Westbrook was unfairly treated as
a youth _ he served 20 years for stealing $300 worth of property _
the district attorney described the 1977 killings as ``among the
cruelest things I've ever seen. I think he ought to be executed.''
   A defense psychologist testified that people with Westbrook's
mentality ``never take social rules and apply them ... because
their reasoning just isn't there.''
   The first conviction in 1977 was thrown out. The jury in the
second trial in 1985 recommended that Westbrook be given life
without parole.
   Judge Joseph B. Duke of the Ocmulgee Judicial Circuit rejected
the verdict on the grounds that the jury could not consider parole.
The jury then returned a death sentence.
   The state Supreme Court affirmed the convictions, but ruled 18
months ago that the initial recommendation of mercy blocked the
death penalty.
   Briley has tentatively set Westbrook's resentencing for Oct. 13.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
