<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LoudPledge     09-28 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Loud Pledge,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Says Still Will Prosecute for Loud Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials said they hope to prosecute
two supporters of Vice President George Bush who were hosts at a
party where college students allegedly chanted the Pledge of
Allegiance too loudly.
   Mayor Roy Young Jr. said Wednesday the city considers it just
another of many excessive-noise cases it is pursuing. ``This
particular one is getting a whole lot of buildup, but it happens to
be one of 17 that were done that night,'' Young said.
   Though the city wants charges pressed, William Sherman, an
assistant Butler County prosecutor, obtained a two-week delay of
the case Tuesday, telling a judge his office wanted to further
investigate the incident and determine whether it could be
prosecuted.
   Karen Stevens and Kimberly Mart, the two Miami University
students cited, said they were ready to defend themselves against
the misdemeanor charge of exceeding the city's allowable noise
level.
   They scurried to court after distributing campaign buttons at a
rally for Bush, who appeared on the Miami University campus
Tuesday. Bush has made the Pledge of Allegiance a major campaign
theme.
   Ms. Stevens, 21, and Ms. Mart, 22, said police harassed them
even though the women said they had taken precautions to hold down
the noise.
   The police went to the party at least twice. The women said they
came the first time because they were invited to come and take a
noise reading to make sure the sound wasn't excessive.
   The second time the police came, they cited the two women after
a guest, standing on a trench holding iced beer kegs, jokingly led
other partygoers in the chant of the Pledge of Allegiance as the
policemen measured the noise level.
   ``It was a calm party,'' Ms. Mart said. ``We really feel like we
were picked on.'' There were no complaints from neighbors, the
women said.
   Oxford's ordinance restricts acceptable noise levels to 70
decibels most times and 55 decibels at night. Police said the noise
level at the women's party reached 85 decibels.
</TEXT>
