<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CampaignAbroad     09-28 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush and Dukakis _ The View from Abroad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of recent commentary in newspapers abroad on
the presidential race between Democrat Michael Dukakis and
Republican George Bush and their debate Sunday in Winston-Salem,
N.C.:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Guardian (liberal): `` ... not once, in the long night of
Winston-Salem, could either man truly break free. Not once could
they say that the USA faces an extraordinarily tough four years,
whoever wins. Or that taxes must rise. Or that American
productivity is increasingly lamentable by world standards. Or that
responding to Mikhail Gorbachev will need imagination rather than
rhetoric. Not once were they really honest, really themselves. They
remain afraid to lose, and the days are running short for the
courage to win.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Daily Telegraph (conservative), London: ``Misgivings about
(Dukakis') capacity in international affairs are widespread. The
British people have had no opportunity to assess him because he has
never visited London, Paris or Bonn. So little interest in our
concerns is bound to be unnerving. ... He is currently trying to
cultivate an image of greater toughness. But it will take more than
a snapshot (of Dukakis) in a tank to dispel the impression of a man
with a strong disinclination to using force, and who appears to
believe that international affairs can be regulated by moral
imperatives and consensus management.
   ``As he demonstrated in the television contest, Mr. Bush is both
less articulate and less managerial-minded than his opponent. But
from a European point of view, he has more substantial advantages.
He knows us and our problems, and has seen enough of the world not
to expect too much of it. .. Europe has no vote, but is entitled to
a view. On present performance, better Bush.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Enrico Franceschini, writing from Washington in La Repubblica
(liberal) of Rome: ``The debate shows that Dukakis is not an
incompetent, crazy or dangerous man, but a prepared leader who is
sure of himself.
   ``Newspaper editorials in the United States warn that there is
the need to change leadership after eight years of Republican
`Reaganism,' but this need is being pushed aside by a fear of
Dukakis' liberal ideology.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Japan Times (English-language, independent): ``Vice President
George Bush has repeatedly charged ... Gov. Michael Dukakis with
ducking the ``ideological issue,'' while Mr. Reagan constantly
invokes the dreaded `L word'' (liberal) to fend off the Democrats'
drive for the political middle ground.
   ``We suspect that the Republicans have got it wrong, because at
least to our eyes it is precisely the GOP's `liberalism' that has
kept the Republicans in power for eight years and may keep Mr. Bush
in the White House for the next eight. ...
   ``The word liberal of course relates to freedom and the economic
liberal is one who believes in free trade and the market principle.
Protectionists, on the other hand, tend to be nationalists keen to
protect weak and infant industries _ and much else besides _ from
dangerous foreign competition. In the current U.S. election
campaign, it is the Democrats who are the economic nationalists and
the Republicans the economic liberals.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Asahi Shimbun (liberal-leaning): ``We were disappointed that
the debate gave only limited time to questions on world trade and
America's Asian policy.
   ``Customarily, a TV debate is not an occasion for candidates to
announce their new policies, and what they say depends, of course,
on the questions they are asked. But the impression we got of the
Bush-Dukakis debate is that the position of the United States in
the world seems to be changing. ...
   ``We hope the next debate will take up Japan-U.S. relations and
issues related to America's position in Asia.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDONESIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Jakarta Post (English-language, independent): ``In the final
analysis, we suppose, one can only hope that the American voters
will elect a leader into the White House that they consider would
be the best to advance the interests of their country but at the
same time take the interests of the rest of the world into
consideration.
   ``We can only hope that the American voters will chose a
president that not only has the best interests of the U.S. at
heart, but that has the vision and political courage to take a
wider view.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
