<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiverTransplants     09-28 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liver Transplants,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Puts Pieces Of One Liver Into Two Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors transplanted segments of one liver into
two young children, the second time the surgery has been performed
in the United States, a hospital said Wednesday.
   The 16-month-old girl and 4{-month-old boy, both from Chicago,
were in critical but stable condition, customary after a
transplant, said Mary Fetsch, a spokeswoman for Wyler Children's
Hospital.
   A surgical team led by Christoph Broelsch began the operations
at 11:15 a.m. Tuesday and ended at 1 a.m. Wednesday, Ms. Fetsch
said.
   The liver was that of a 16-month-old Oregon boy, she said.
   The girl suffered from biliary atresia, or clogged bile ducts.
The boy's liver was scarred by an unknown cause, she said. The
children's parents asked that the hospital not release names.
   In July, Broelsch was the nation's first doctor to take segments
of one liver and transplant them into two people. Jaclyn Manrose of
Crystal Lake, who was 7 months old at the time, is in good health
at home, Ms. Fetsch said.
   The other youngster, 12-week-old Joseph Kovach of Geneva, died
of heart failure 36 hours after surgery.
</TEXT>
