<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CondoCollapse     09-28 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condo Collapse,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Say They Knew Building Was Unsafe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third body was found Wednesday buried
in the rubble of a six-story condominium that collapsed and slid
down a steep hillside. Residents said the building had been unsafe
for months.
   The complex, built on six cement pillars, collapsed shortly
before 9 a.m. Tuesday in a fashionable suburb of Monterrey, killing
a man and his baby son and a woman.
   A 19-month-old girl and two women were missing.
   Luis Carlos Trevino Berchelman, assistant attorney general in
this northern Nuevo Leon state capital, said rescue crews found the
woman's body Wednesday but couldn't retrieve it because it was
under heavy concrete slabs.
   State authorities at the scene speculate that heavy rain from
Hurricane Gilbert, which ripped through the area Sept. 17,
contributed to the structure's collapse.
   ``One of the neighbors told us that six months ago they told the
architect that the building was breaking loose and it was
leaning,'' said Francisco Javier Nakashima, state judicial police
investigator.
   Asked if Gilbert's torrential rains contributed to the collapse,
Nakashima said, ``It had to have something to do with it, so all
this accelerated.''
   Residents and their relatives say the building already was
unsafe.
   ``We knew this was going to happen,'' resident Marcela Garza
told the daily Monterrey newspaper El Norte.
   ``The whole building had cracks and the frames were crooked,''
said Ms. Garza, who was away from the condominium when it fell.
   Patrick Fiehn, uncle of the 19-month-old girl trapped inside,
said in an interview that the building's support pillars had been
twisting for several months. He said an engineer hired to examine
the building just three days before the disaster told residents it
was safe.
   State and local authorities at the scene said they would not
investigate the cause of the collapse until all the victims were
found.
   Rescue teams working around the clock since the disaster dug by
hand and carried out buckets of broken concrete that had been the
building's walls and floors.
   ``We were advised to do the work by hand. The goal is to
preserve the life of those that may be inside,'' Trevino Berchelman
said.
   He said three teams of dogs that had been brought in to sniff
through the rubble, including an American group from Dallas, all
pinpointed about the same locations where the victims may be
trapped.
   But he said the heavy concrete slabs prevented rescue workers
from reaching those locations.
   Three people were rescued shortly after the structure collapsed
and did not suffer major injuries.
   A fourth survivor, Maria Eugenia Gonzalez de Rodriguez, was
dragged from the wreckage four hours after the building fell. She
was listed in stable condition Wednesday at Monterrey's Muguerza
Hospital, said Rebecca Gonzalez, a nurse on the intermediate care
ward.
   The 3-year-old building had 21 residents and one supervisor, but
only 10 people were inside the building when it fell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Analysis     09-28 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Analysis,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Choice Of Rakowski Gives Pause To Opposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Story also ran for Wednesday PMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In choosing a man unpopular with
Solidarity to be prime minister, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski has
signaled that authorities are not about to roll over and play dead
in talks with the opposition.
   But naming propaganda chief Mieczyslaw Rakowski to head the
government may not be as harmful to chances for achieving national
reconciliation as it initially appeared.
   The selection of Rakowski at a time when authorities have set
aside their longstanding opposition to direct talks with leaders of
the banned free trade union movement raised some eyebrows in this
capital city.
   After all, Rakowski and Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa have had
a long and bitter relationship. According to acquaintances, both
thoroughly dislike each other.
   Rakowski, then deputy prime minister, was the government's point
man in dealing with Solidarity during its 15-month legal period,
which ended in December 1981 with the imposition of martial law.
   Solidarity activists accuse the government of bad faith during
the period, while Communist authorities say Solidarity leaders were
unable to control their rank-and-file, bringing the country to the
edge of anarchy.
   The bitter feelings were not helped after martial law, when
Rakowski continued to defend the decision to crack down on
Solidarity. He went so far as to challenge Walesa on his home turf,
the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, in a dramatic televised verbal
encounter.
   Taking all this into account, promoting Rakowski will give pause
to Solidarity activists who believed that round-table talks
beginning in mid-October would quickly lead to reinstatement of the
union.
   Some people allied with the authorities have complained that the
opposition has been too quick to assume that the government's
agreement to hold talks means Solidarity already has won.
   By agreeing on the talks, authorities succeeded in ending a
Poland's most serious strike wave in seven years.
   Walesa has said publicly that recognition of Solidarity is
``very near'' and another activist told Western reporters that
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak had already conceded a
place for Solidarity in Poland's future.
   Such statements are signs of ``wishful thinking,'' on the part
of the opposition, said party journalist Daniel Passent, who added
that he doubts authorities are ready to recognize Solidarity.
   But naming Rakowski to the prime minister's post does not
automatically doom round-table talks, several political figures
said.
   ``It doesn't matter,'' said Walesa. ``It's a new situation.''
   ``Maybe he will change his opinion about Solidarity,'' said
independent parliament deputy Ryszard Bender.
   In addition, the round-table talks will be conducted by someone
other than Rakowski, who will have his hands full assembling a new
governing team and coping with Poland's disintegrating economy.
   In the three preparatory talks so far, Kiszczak has taken the
lead for the government, and participants said he has shown a good
rapport with Walesa.
   In addition, there are signs that Rakowski, who until the rise
of Solidarity was considered a leading liberal within the communist
party, would like to be seen again as a reformer who will bring
greater diversity to Polish government.
   He told the parliament after his election that he wanted to
bring people who backed reform into the government. Later,
government spokesman Jerzy Urban said members of the ``constructive
opposition'' might be invited to join the authorities.
   Recently, also, Rakowski has tempered his criticism of Walesa,
saying the Solidarity leader may have matured in recent years.
   Finally, there remained the possibility that Rakowski's tenure
in office could be brief.
   Some party observers had said before his appointment that the
next government could be transitional, pending whatever agreement
on the future government in Poland is reached by the talks with
Solidarity. And Urban said Rakowski was expected to stay until
parliamentary elections sometime next year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   John Daniszewski is an Associated Press
correspondent based in Warsaw.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
