<DOCNO> AP880928-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Weinberger-Probe     09-28 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weinberger-Probe,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger Says Greed Led to Pentagon Bribery Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The current Pentagon bribery investigation
arises from ``plain criminal greed'' that is ``a sad aspect of
life,'' former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger said Wednesday.
   ``I don't believe there's anything special about the Navy, or
the Defense Department, or this situation,'' the architect of
President Reagan's defense build-up told the House Armed Services
Committee.
   Before resigning last year, Weinberger oversaw a doubling of the
Pentagon budget under Reagan and a large increase in the Pentagon's
purchase of a vast array of weapons and other items.
   The Justice Department is investigating whether private
consultants, many of them former Pentagon employees, paid bribes to
Defense Department officials for inside information about
contracts, chiefly within the Navy. Such information could be the
difference in winning multimillion-dollar contracts.
   No charges have been filed.
   Weinberger said he didn't know any of the inside details of the
investigation and was not aware it was under way until there were
news reports in June about the serving of subpoenas.
   ``That's the first I heard of it,'' he told the panel. ``Every
once in a while before that, oh, you'd come across an isolated case
here and there, but there was nothing systematic, nothing of this
scale until I read about the investigation.''
   Weinberger steadfastly defended his tenure at the Pentagon and
said he and other top Defense Department officials had worked hard
to root out corruption and fraud.
   But Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the panel, asked
Weinberger ``Why did this happen? Is it the system? Why now?''
   ``I don't know,'' Weinberger said. ``As to why ... I suspect the
simple answer is plain criminal greed. ... It goes back to biblical
times. That's a sad aspect of life.''
   ``This so-called insider trading of information is just greed,''
he continued. ``I don't know of anything in the system ... that
requires or breeds dishonesty, but dishonesty is a sad fact of
daily existence.''
   He did endorse restrictions on the use of consultants.
   ``A lot of these (consulting) services are unnecessary,'' he
said. ``I have moral problems with these.''
   Several legislators have proposed new restrictions on the
Pentagon's use of consultants, but Weinberger declined to endorse
any specific proposals.
   He did say ``the best way'' to restrict consultants ``is to have
very strict rules and regulations with respect to reimbursement of
contractors'' if the companies hire consultants.
   The companies should be required to show that the consultants
are necessary to fulfilling the contract before the consultant fees
are reimbursed by the Pentagon, Weinberger suggested.
   Weinberger called for ``firm oversight'' by both the Pentagon
and Congress. But again, as he has in the past, he criticized
Congress for being involved too deeply in details of weapons
systems and contracts.
   He also said he had ordered sharp increases in the number of
auditors during Reagan's first term, a time when defense budgets
were rising steadily.
   ``We got a lot of criticism for over-auditing, but it seems to
me it's better than under-auditing,'' he said.
   It was the Pentagon, rather than its critics, which uncovered
many of the ``horror stories'' such as $600 toilet seat covers,
Weinberger said.
   ``All of those were uncovered by our own auditors,'' he said.
``And it needs to be remembered that we didn't pay them. We caught
them.''
</TEXT>
