<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Bomb     09-28 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Bomb,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Hurts Man Outside Government Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion on Wednesday
seriously injured a man outside government offices in the
mixed-race township of Bonteheuwel, and police said the victim was
placed under guard.
   Police said it was possible the man was carrying the bomb when
it exploded.
   The man suffered serious arm and leg injuries and was found
lying outside the building after the 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT) blast,
which shattered windows and tore off roof tiles on the building
housing municipal offices, police said.
   Residents of Strand, about 25 miles southeast of Cape Town, said
they heard a second explosion outside municipal offices in that
city shortly after the blast in Bonteheuwel.
   There have been more than 50 bombings in South Africa this year
and police have blamed most of them on the outlawed African
National Congress. But government opponents say that right-wing
vigilantes or secret units of the security forces could be
responsible for bombings of anti-apartheid organization offices.
   South Africa is racially segregated under apartheid, a system
under which the 5 million whites control the country and the 26
million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
   State-of-emergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest, and a broad range of statements
the government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations
has not been comprehensive.
</TEXT>
