<HEAD>Jazz Drummer J.C. Heard Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz drummer J.C. Heard, who performed
with many of the world's best-known jazz musicians, has died. He
was 71.
   Bonnie Niebel, a spokeswoman for William Beaumont Hospital, said
Heard died there Tuesday night. She said she did not know the cause.
   Heard had been scheduled to appear Wednesday night in concert
with his friend, trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie. Heard's agent, Jim
Fleming of Ann Arbor, said attempts were being made to see that the
concert Wednesday night and one Thursday go on.
   Heard performs on two current albums, ``Some of This, Some of
That'' and oen on which he accompanied pianist Mark ``Mr. B'' Braun.
   ``He was the consummate professional,'' Ron Brooks, a bass
player and owner of The Bird of Paradise in Ann Arbor, where Heard
frequently played, said Wednesday. ``He was a great model for young
musicians.''
   Brooks said Heard's wife was visiting friends in Europe when
Heard was stricken. The Heards had been living in Southfield.
   Funeral arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
