<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-NewZealand     09-28 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-New Zealand,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lange Says He Can't Visit White House, But `Hoods' Can</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister David Lange of New Zealand said
Wednesday that strained relations between his government and the
United States have kept him from visiting the White House even
though ``all sorts of hoods'' go there.
   Lange, in the United States for a speech to the U.N. General
Assembly, told ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' the New Zealand
government was firm in its refusal to allow U.S. nuclear-armed
ships to visit ports in his country.
   The ban led the United States to end its alliance with New
Zealand.
   ``If that means you take your Army and Air Force and Navy away,
that's bad; we regret it,'' Lange said. ``But the price of being
defeated by a nuclear devastation is something we're not prepared
to pay.''
   He was asked what that meant for relations between the two
countries.
   ``It means that I don't sort of get taken to the White House,''
Lange said. ``I've been to Disneyland four times, New York about
three times in the last four years, and I've never been to the
White House.
   ``And all sorts of hoods have been to the White House in that
time,'' he said, without elaborating.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater declined to comment when
asked about the remark.
   ``But it's an easy, practical relationship,'' Lange said. ``We
get along well with the United States. We look at the world through
your news cameras.''
</TEXT>
