<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EducationAccountability     09-28 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Education Accountability,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Offers Help To State Accountability Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Education Department on Wednesday issued a
report designed to aid governors, state legislators and educational
committees on how best to measure performance of America's public
schools.
   ``There's not much point in trying to improve schools unless you
can measure whether the efforts are working,'' Chester E. Finn,
Jr., assistant secretary of the Office of Educational Research and
Improvement (OERI) said in a statement.
   ``We're long past the days when good intentions and lots of
activity were acceptable signs of movement. Now policy-makers want
_ and the public deserves _ clear evidence of actual
accomplishment,'' Finn continued.
   The 66-page report, entitled ``Creating Responsible and
Responsive Accountability Systems: Report of the OERI State
Accountability Study Group,'' is based on an in-depth examination
of 10 states' systems and a survey of 50 states and the District of
Columbia.
   The study group, composed of 27 members from 10 states and five
national organizations, was convened last year to examine the trend
in state monitoring of the results of education practices.
   The report details review systems in 50 states and the District
of Columbia and is intended to help states produce information that
is ``reliable, fair and useful for improving schools.''
   ``I think states, without exception, have the constitutional
responsibility for education,'' Finn told a press conference. ``And
I believe that states have a responsibility that goes with that to
know how their schools are doing.
   ``They need to know that even if their localities don't want to
know that.'' he added.
   ``The State has an obligation to see that the public is
informed, the governor is informed, the legislature is informed and
the taxpayer is informed,'' said Finn adding that local communities
should not have the option of concealing such information from the
public.
   ``I think it is also desirable to have this information
available on the district level so that the residents of district A
can see if their kids and their tax dollars are being well
served,'' Finn noted.
   In California, the report noted that the state education
department sends a yearly report card to every school, complete
with an acheivement ranking.
   In South Carolina, districts displaying student achievement
gains may receive monetary awards and bonuses for gains in student
and teacher attendance. Failing school districts may be subject to
withholding of funds or state intervention, the report said.
   The document also attempted to address educators' concerns that
some evaluation techniques may make unfair comparisons, encourage
over testing or narrow their focus by using only standardized tests
results.
   The report's recommendations include using a variety of
indicators to measure performance; make performance data public;
consider programs, rewards and incentives to encourage high
performance, and offer assistance to low performing districts
before considering state intervention.
</TEXT>
