<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eliana-AIDS     09-28 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eliana-AIDS,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Case Of Classroom Enclosure Now in Hands of Appellate Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl with AIDS should be separated from
classmates, but a judge went too far in ordering that she sit in a
glass booth, an attorney for the 7-year-old told a federal appeals
panel Wednesday.
   Eliana Martinez could sit out of reach from classmates at a
kidney-shaped table, said Steve Hanlon, the lawyer hired by the
girl's adoptive mother, Rosa Martinez. He said such a plan would
fulfill guidelines issued by the federal Centers for Disease
Control.
   Ms. Martines contends it would be detrimental to her daughter's
development to sit in a ``glass cage.'' But the 11th U.S. Court of
Appeals judges expressed concerns at the hearing about whether the
alternative was to expose the other children in the special
education classroom to the incurable disease.
   The three-judge panel gave no indication when it would rule.
   ``It's a tough, tough case,'' Tom Gonzalez, an attorney for the
Hillsborough County School Board, said. He said no case had
previously arisen in U.S. courts of a retarded, incontinent child
with AIDS.
   The CDC has concluded children exposed to AIDS do not generally
pose a risk to their classmates, but some unconvinced parents are
still raising objections.
   In South Roxana, Ill., school officials are bracing for protests
Thursday as 8-year-old Jason Robertson entrs second grade. Jason's
family left the St. Louis suburb of Granite City last month, saying
they'd been harassed for their efforts to enroll him in regular
classes there.
   In August, a federal judge in Tampa ruled Eliana could go to
school, but she had to stay inside a glass or Plexiglas enclosure
until she was toilet trained and stopped sucking her fingers.
   The school board wanted the child to be taught at home but
agreed to the partition and built it.
   ``We believe great harm would occur to that child if she went
into that enclosure,'' Hanlon told the appellate panel.
   Citing medical testimony from the trial, he said the risk of
transmitting the fatal disease to other children was a ``remote,
theoretical potential.'' That testimony referred to exposure to the
AIDS virus through tears, saliva and urine.
   Appeals Judge Robert S. Vance noted that the trial judge's order
mentioned that Eliana had a condition of mouth sores and cracked
lips called oral thrush, but didn't say what risk it poses.
   ``I see a significant risk, which I can't erase from my mind,''
said Vance. He said handicapped children are known to bite each
other, which he said could spread AIDS if the infected child had a
trace of blood in the mouth.
   To put a child in such a situation ``may be sentencing those
children to death. That evidence a judge is not going to treat
lightly,'' he said.
   Hanlon said Eliana's doctors found no evidence of blood in the
mouth, but if bleeding developed, Eliana would be held out of class.
   Doctors believe Eliana was infected by blood transfusions
following her premature birth in Puerto Rico. Mrs. Martinez, a
licensed practical nurse, adopted her as an infant after hearing a
radio appeal for a homeless child.
   Mrs. Martinez attended the hearing and afterward was joined by
Eliana on the courthouse steps.
   ``Eliana will not go into that glass enclosure,'' Mrs. Martinez
said. ``She would not be happy there. She's not going; that's it. I
want her in a regular classroom with trainable, mentally
handicapped children just like her. I think the school board has
stalled enough.''
</TEXT>
