<2ND_LINE>AM-ABC-Poll,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Poll Trial Heat Unchanged by Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll Wednesday put the presidential race at
precisely the same place it was before Sunday's debate _ a
statistical dead heat, with 50 percent for George Bush and 46
percent for Michael Dukakis.
   The national ABC News survey, conducted Monday and Tuesday among
674 likely voters, mirrored the 50-46 result of an ABC poll
conducted last week. The new poll had a margin of error of plus or
minus 5 points.
   An overnight poll by ABC immediately after the debate found
respondents divided on who won, and none of four such polls
measured any significant movement in support as a result of the
event. An ABC poll done Monday found increasing numbers calling the
debate a tie.
   ABC said its polls have found the race ``basically a tie'' since
the Republican National Convention last month, when Bush made up a
lead Dukakis had taken from the Democratic convention in July.
