<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AngolaTalks 2ndLd-Writethru   09-28 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0723,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Hampered By Cuban Troop Withdrawal Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with talks extended. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs, President Mobutu ... editing to trim</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. mediator said South Africa,
Angola and Cuba extended on Wednesday talks on ending Angola's
civil war. Officials said a timetable for withdrawal of 50,000
Cuban troops remained a key issue.
   The talks, which were to end Wednesday, will continue and U.S.
mediators ``are confident that the remaining questions will be
approached in a positive spirit which will result in a final
accord,'' U.S. envoy Chester Crocker said.
   Crocker, assistant U.S. secretary of state for African affairs,
said in a statement, ``The parties involved in the Brazzaville
talks continue to show a constructive attitude at the negotiating
table.''
   He met separately with the South African and Angolan-Cuban
delegations.
   President Mobutu Seso Seko of Zaire meanwhile sought to arrange
an African summit to negotiate an end to the 13-year-old conflict,
said government sources in Kinshasa, Zaire's capital. The sources
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Speaking on the third day of U.S.-mediated peace talks between
South Africa and an Angolan-Cuban delegation, South Africa's chief
negotiator, Neil Van Heerden said, ``It is still difficult to say
whether there will be an accord signed in Brazzaville.''
   Van Heerden, director-general of foreign affairs department,
told reporters, ``There is still a gulf between us and the
Angolans.''
   Cuban spokesman Alcibiades Hidalgo said Cuban forces ``could
only leave after fulfilling all its obligations.''
   Hidalgo added, ``If South African continues to link the
withdrawal of Cuban troops to independence for Namibia, and
requires their pullout within 12 months, this could constitute an
obstacle to the conclusion of an accord.''
   South Africa has withdrawn its forces from Angola and insists
that Angola send home an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops. Angola
initially said it would need four years for the Cuban withdrawal,
while South Africa said the troops should be out in one year. The
Brazzaville talks were aimed at reaching a compromise.
   Van Heerden said South Africa recognized it was ``difficult to
demand the immediate withdrawal of 50,000 Cubans,'' particularly
because of Angola's internal security problems. The Marxist
government there has been battling the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola, which has been supported by South
Africa, the United States and other countries.
   African diplomats have said they hope the Brazzaville talks will
lead to a formal agreement signed at the United Nations.
   The latest round of talks began Monday. The main issue has been
the length of time Cuban troops will remain in Angola once South
Africa begins its implementation of a U.N. independence plan for
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   South Africa regards the Cuban presence in Angola as a threat to
South-West Africa, Angola's southern neighbor, as well as a menace
to its own security.
</TEXT>
