<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Viewing     09-28 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Viewing,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What the TV Viewer Can Expect to See During Discovery Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television can't make you feel the
ground shake when the space shuttle starts flying and can't make
you feel the awe as this 16-story-tall structure rises from the
ground. But you'll see it better and longer than the people who are
on the spot.
   If the weather is clear, a person in Launch Control can see the
shuttle clear the tower and do its majestic 120-degree turn, and
follow it until it becomes a pinpoint of light 4 minutes later.
   But Air Force cameras at a nearby base stay with the shuttle far
longer. The home viewer clearly can see the ship's spent solid fuel
booster rockets fall into the Atlantic Ocean, 150 miles downrange,
two minutes into the flight.
   The Challenger explosion 2{ years ago came 73 seconds after
liftoff when the ship was only 8.9 miles away from its launchpad.
</TEXT>
