<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowan-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rowan's Attorney Says City Wanted To Nab A Celebrity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new to UPDATE with jury recessing without
verdict. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``If convicted ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury deliberating the weapons charges case
against syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan recessed for the night
Wednesday after discussing the matter for three hours without
reaching a verdict.
   District of Columbia Superior Court Judge Arthur L. Burnett Sr.
sent the jury home at 6 p.m., and ordered the 12-member panel to
avoid reading about or listening to broadcast accounts of the trial.
   Rowan, an outspoken opponent of handgun use and possession, has
been charged with using an unregistered pistol and ammunition to
shoot a youth who took an unauthorized dip in his pool.
   If convicted of both misdemeanor offenses, the 63-year-old
columnist could face up to two years in prison and a $2,000 fine.
   ``They came in here to prosecute a celebrity,'' Rowan's
attorney, Raoul Carroll, said at the close of a two-day trial in
D.C. Superior Court. ``They aren't interested in the truth.''
   Carroll also argued that Rowan's son, Carl Jr., had repeatedly
been told by police officials that he did not have to register the
weapon his father later used to wound the teen-age intruder.
   ``He was depending upon the competence and intelligence of those
people that the District of Columbia put there (to advise citizens
on gun registration),'' Carroll argued. ``He was entirely at the
mercy of the District of Columbia.''
   The case centered on whether Rowan and his son were misled by
city police officials about the district's strict handgun
registration policy and the prosecution's contention that Rowan Sr.
was not authorized to handle the weapon.
   The handgun ordinance prohibits any person except security
officers from registering weapons, although exemptions commonly are
made for law enforcement officers.
   Rowan's son was an FBI agent when he tried to register the
weapon. Inspector James R. Lee, head of the city's gun control
unit, testified that Rowan Jr. was not authorized to transfer the
weapon to anyone.
   Rowan testified that he was given the .22-caliber pistol by his
son in 1982, after receiving several death threats from persons
purporting to be members of the Ku Klux Klan.
   The columnist testified that he shot Benjamin Smith, 18, of
suburban Chevy Chase, Md., in the early hours of June 14 because he
thought Smith was trying to break into his home.
   Thomas C. Collier, the city's attorney, argued in closing that
the case before the jury was ``vry simple.''
   ``We are here simply because the handgun is not registered,''
Collier said. ``The death threats, the shooting and the issue of
trespassing have nothing to do with this case.''
   Police officers who investigated the shooting testified that a
door at the rear of Rowan's home showed signs that someone had
tried to break in. One officer also testified that the police
investigation revealed Smith had been shot at close range just
outside Rowan's home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Rebels     09-28 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Rebels,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Admits Loss of Two Towns in South to Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said Wednesday it lost two
strategic towns in southern Sudan in fierce fighting that left
heavy losses.
   Chief of Staff Gen. Fathi Ahmed Ali said his forces in Katre
``have been withdrawn to other areas'' and that some units were
withdrawn from Kiala.
   He said heavy fighting continued around Kiala, but a communique
issued later by the armed forces command said Kiala had been
evacuated and troops withdrawn to another town, Toreit.
   Katre and Kiala are near the Ugandan border.
   Ali spoke to reporters after a meeting with Ahmed Ali
el-Mirghani, chairman of the Sudanese Supreme Council, which has
the same role as a head of state.
   The military communique confirmed a report by the newspaper
Al-Ayam on the fall of the two towns, about 825 miles south of
Khartoum.
   Al-Ayam reported continued fighting around the famine-hit town
of Toreit, about 50 miles northwest of Katre.
   The army did not say when Katre and Kiala were evacuated, but
the rebel Sudan Peoples' Liberation Army claimed its fighters
captured Katre on Sept. 16, Kiala on Sept. 25, and a third small
town, Labalo, around the same time.
   The Sudanese military denied the claim, but on Monday, Mauris
Lawya, governor of the Equatoria region, said troops had evacuated
the towns. He said, however, that the situation was ``still
unclear.''
   On Tuesday, a rebel radio broadcast from Ethiopia said that
Liberation Army troops had captured Kiala, inflicting heavy losses
on government troops.
   The rebels took up arms against the government in 1983,
demanding autonomy and administrative and economic reforms in the
south. They claim to control 90 percent of the southern
countryside, while the government retains authority in most major
cities and towns.
   The military communique Wednesday said the rebels received
unlimited military support from ``quarters hostile to Sudan.'' It
accused ``regional and international quarters'' of involvement in
``this dirty plot.''
   The communique said the rebel forces began attacking Kiala Sept.
17 ``with more than 5,000 troops and arms superior even to those of
some regular armies'' and concentrated their assaults on eastern
Equatoria region.
   ``After the increase of the shelling and the arrival of more
support to the rebels and the great losses of our army and
civilians between killed and injured, the commander has decided to
pull out of Kiala,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
