<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     09-28 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessmen, Politicians Being Watched For Links To Renegades</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The capital's military commander said
Wednesday that prominent businessmen and politicians are under
surveillance for allegedly backing renegade soldiers who want to
topple President Corazon Aquino.
   Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon made the remarks before a
congressional committee one day after the arrest of Lt. Col.
Eduardo Matillano, a leader of last year's bloody attempt to topple
Mrs. Aquino.
   Elsewhere, communist New People's Army guerrillas burned a
passenger bus and killed a town mayor, two paramilitary agents and
a soldier in separate incidents. Soldiers killed two rebels.
   In his testimony, Bizon refused to identify those under
surveillance. He said the military was collecting evidence ``before
we take up action.''
   The business executives and politicians were providing
``financial support and a political component to the movement,'' he
said.
   Matillano, former Philippine Constabulary commander for Nueva
Ecija province, played a major role in the failed coup Aug. 28,
1987, which killed at least 53 people and wounded 300. The attempt
was led by former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan, who escaped
after being captured and remains at large.
   Biazon said Tuesday that Matillano had been recruiting dissident
soldiers for a new coup plot and that unidentified civilians were
involved.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said at a news conference that
Mrs. Aquino ordered the military to pursue its investigation of the
dissidents' alleged civilian backers. Ramos said he did not know
the names of all those under suspicion.
   Biazon said some of the recently arrested followers of deposed
President Ferdinand Marcos provided names of their backers.
   The opposition Union for National Action, led by Vice President
Salvador Laurel, demanded in a statement that Mrs. Aquino release
immediately the names of all those suspected of links to Honasan
and other rebel soldiers.
   It said that otherwise, ``it only shows the administration is
involved in a witch hunt which it probably hopes will be a
convenient smokescreen to the unending tales of corruption, which
characterizes the government today.''
   Two assassins believed to be communist guerrillas on Wednesday
killed Mayor Lavi Manpatilan of Esperanza while he was attending a
wedding in a nearby city about 500 miles southeast of Manila,
police said.
   Manpatilan, who heads a 500-man anti-communist militia force,
was shot six times, they said. The gunmen escaped.
   In Laguna province, military regional spokesman Col. Hernani
Figueroa said four rebels abducted a driver and conductor of the
Batangas Laguna Tayabas Bus Co. after setting the bus afire Monday
in San Pablo, about 50 miles south of Manila. But bus company
officials said they suspected a labor dispute was behind the
incident.
   In Lian town in Batangas province, guerrillas killed two
paramilitary agents and a soldier in a jeep Tuesday, a military
report said.
   The military said soldiers killed two communist rebels in a
15-minute clash Tuesday on the outskirts of San Francisco town in
Agusan del Sur province, about 540 miles south of Manila.
</TEXT>
