<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0702,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Block Kahane Supporters from West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Jerusalem riot, nine
wounded, Kahane getting lost, other details. PICKS up 13th: In
Jerusalem...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT SAHOUR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops Wednesday
barred supporters of American-born legislator Meir Kahane from
holding his anti-Arab party's election convention in the West Bank.
   In Jerusalem, police banned Israeli extremists from touring the
Temple Mount, a sacred site claimed by Moslems and Jews.
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded nine Arabs in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, including a 10-year-old boy shot in the
head while playing on the roof of his house in the city of Nablus,
hospital officials said, speaking anonymously.
   The army confirmed three wounded.
   Kahane, whose Kach Party has called for expulsion of all Arabs
from Israel and the occupied territories, scheduled his convention
for the Arab city of Hebron despite an army order banning the
meeting.
   ``I want the Arabs to realize that in four years, when I am
prime minister, it will be a Jewish city, not an Arab city,''
Kahane said before departing Jerusalem.
   He led two buses and a dozen cars and vans on a three-hour
odyssey seeking a back road to Hebron. At times the caravan
appeared lost and Kahane at one point asked an Arab villager for
directions.
   The caravan, stoned by Arabs in several villages, was finally
stopped by an army patrol seven miles south of Jerusalem.
   The right-wing Likud Bloc also mounted a West Bank tour
Wednesday, taking about 4,000 Israelis to visit Jewish settlements
near Nablus, 30 miles north of Jerusalem.
   Benny Begin, son of former prime minister Menachem Begin and a
candidate for parliament in the Nov. 1 elections, told the crowd
Likud would never trade the West Bank in a peace agreement.
   During the tour, one Israeli passenger was hit in the head by a
rock and taken to a hospital, the army said. Israeli radio
identified her as Shoshana Greidi, 73.
   In east Jerusalem, Arab youths rioted for second day in the
Jabal Mukaber neighborhood to protest the death of a 19-year-old
Palestinian hit in the mouth with a tear gas canister Monday,
police and Israel radio said. Police fired tear gas to disperse the
crowd.
   Earlier Wednesday in Jerusalem, officers turned back about 30
members of the Temple Mount Faithful, a group which demands Jewish
control over the area known in Arabic as Haram El-Sharif, or Noble
Enclosure.
   The raised platform is sacred to Jews as the site of the holy
temple destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70 and to Moslems as the
place where the prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven in the 7th
century.
   The mount, dominated by the golden Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa
mosques, is under Moslem administration.
   A visit by the group last year prompted violent protests by
hundreds of Palestinians, and police feared Moslem protests would
be more severe this year.
   Gershon Solomon, head of the group, called the ban ``painful,
humiliating and anti-Jewish.''
   Also Wednesday, the office of Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
retracted a hard-line comment issued a day earlier.
   Rabin said Tuesday the army was intentionally trying to wound
Palestinian protesters with newly introduced plastic bullets. ``Our
aim is to cause more casualties,'' he said.
   But his spokesman Eitan Haber said Rabin meant to stress that
plastic bullets were being used to avoid lethal injuries caused by
lead bullets.
   In Washington, the State Department said it was disturbed by
Israel's use of plastic bullets.
   ``We can see no justification for a policy admittedly designed
to cause an increase in casualties,'' spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
said.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8, 278 Palestinians have been
killed. Six Israelis also have died.

</TEXT>
