<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0716 09-28 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Would Double Size Of IRS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with more Bush and to give Dukakis reaction to
Bush, INSERT one graf after 12th pvs, Bush said...the Soviets, and
17th graf, ``We do...tax free.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush toured the small towns of
central Illinois in a bus caravan Wednesday, painting Democratic
opponent Michael Dukakis as ``an inexperienced liberal governor''
bent on beefing up the police powers of the Internal Revenue
Service.
   Stressing policy differences with Dukakis, and suggesting more
than once that the Massachusetts governor would make it easier for
the IRS to go after ordinary citizens, Bush declared, ``I am with
the American people.''
   Bush's eight-bus caravan, complete with an entourage of country
music entertainers, wended its way north on U.S. highway 51,
passing farm after farm and stopping at towns like El Paso,
population 2,700, and Minonk, population 2,250.
   Bush's trip was intended to galvanize Republicans and lure away
Democrats in central Illinois to offset the traditionally large
Democratic vote in Chicago and Cook County.
   ``He wants to squeeze another $35 billion bucks out of the
taxpayers' pocket,'' Bush said, claiming the IRS would have to
double its workforce to 200,000 people under Dukakis in order to
carry out his proposal to collect billions of dollars in delinquent
and evaded taxes.
   ``I have confidence in the honesty of the American people,''
Bush said. ``I am not for a program that is going to increase IRS
seizures and give the IRS more power.''
   Bush rode in the first bus, accompanied by his wife, Barbara,
and country music singers Loretta Lynn, Crystal Gayle and Peggy Sue
Wright, who warmed up the crowds with favorites such as ``Coal
Miner's Daughter'' and ``Praise the Lord, I Saw the Light.''
   
   
   Bush told voters he has come under attack for criticizing
Dukakis' veto of a bill that would have required public school
teachers to lead students in reciting the Pledge of Allegiance.
Dukakis acted after an advisory opinion from the state Supreme
Court said the bill was unconstitutional.
   ``The liberals hate it,'' Bush said, referring to his criticism.
``They can't stand it. But I am right and I am with the American
people on this and on voluntary prayer in school and a whole bunch
of things I consider fundamental values.''
   He stressed that he supports the death penalty and Dukakis
opposes it.
   Bush said the United States was able to sign a nuclear-arms
treaty with the Soviet Union last December ``because we
strengthened America and knew how to negotiate with the Soviets.
   ``And I don't think this is any time to turn to an inexperienced
liberal governor of Massachusetts to handle the national security
matters of the United States of America,'' Bush said.
   After six stops and six speeches, Bush was having some trouble
getting his message out. He told a small audience at a Del Monte
corn packing plant that the Reagan administration had achieved
success in dealing with the Soviets because ``strength through
peace works, and we'd better never forget that.''
   With 25 electoral votes, Illinois is one of the big prizes in
the presidential race, and Bush has made five visits here since
mid-summer seeking an edge in a neck-and-neck contest.
   ``Illinois is vital to the election,'' Bush said at a Illinois
State University rally in Normal at the start of the day. ``And
before Nov. 8, I'm going to be back again and again because the
land of Lincoln is going to be absolutely critical in choosing the
next president.''
   At the rally with students, Bush attacked Dukakis' college-loan
proposal, under which funds borrowed for school would be repaid
over a long period by deductions from paychecks.
   ``We do not need to put the IRS on your tail for the rest of
your life as the reward for a college education,'' Bush said,
putting in a pitch for his own plan for a college savings bond
under which interest would accumulate tax free.
   The Dukakis campaign said Bush misstated the programs. It said
Bush claimed the student loans were government loans rather than
bank loans, and it said Dukakis' IRS program only calls for a 6
percent annual growth rate in the number of IRS personnel.
   Before farm audiences, Bush pledged to expand agricultural
markets, resist protectionism and never impose a grain embargo as
President Carter did.
   Other communities on Bush's seven-stop tour were Wenona,
Mendota, and West Brooklyn, which with a population of 200 was the
smallest town on the trip.
</TEXT>
