<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Soviets     09-28 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Soviets,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets and Canadians Smooth Over Spy Ouster Troubles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and Canada have repaired
diplomatic damage resulting from the expulsions of accused spies
last summer and will have their embassies back to full strength
soon, officials said Wednesday.
   Canada expelled or barred the return of 19 Soviet diplomats in
June, saying they had engaged in espionage.
   Moscow retaliated by ejecting or barring the return of 13
Canadian diplomats and by withdrawing Soviet support staff at the
Canadian Embassy in Moscow.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark met Wednesday with his
Soviet counterpart, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, and said afterward that
``relations between Canada and the Soviet Union are sufficiently
important that we should put the events of June behind us.''
   ``So we're doing that,'' Clark concluded.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov confirmed
the understanding during an afternoon news conference.
   ``Maybe it's time to return to the previous situation concerning
the personnel of both embassies, in Moscow and in Ottawa,'' he said.
   Clark said he expects Canada will have the right to rehire all
25 Soviet support staff pulled out of the Canadian Embassy, but it
will not fully exercise that right. The government has decided to
replace some of the Soviet citizens with Russian-speaking Canadians.
   The diplomats were in New York to attend the 43rd U.N. General
Assembly session.
</TEXT>
