<1ST_LINE>u a AM-US-Spain     09-28 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Spain,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Concludes Bases Agreement With Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Spain on Wednesday
concluded an agreement for eight more years of American military
use of Spanish bases.
   The deal was sealed at a meeting between Secretary of State
George P. Shultz and Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco
Fernandez-Ordonez.
   For the first time, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman
said, no U.S. economic or military aid will be provided for use of
the bases.
   Redman said the agreement underscored that a U.S. military
presence in Spain served the ``common interest'' of the two
countries.
   He also said the two sides were able to resolve a nuclear
question that had become entwined in the negotiations.
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzales initially had vowed to
keep Spanish territory and naval ports free of U.S. nuclear
weapons. Worldwide U.S. policy, meanwhile, is to neither confirm
nor deny the presence of such weapons on American warships or
fighter planes.
   Redman said the U.S. policy would be upheld. Presumably, this
means Spainish authorities will not put such questions to American
commanders.
   Earlier in the year, the United States agreed to remove 72 U.S.
F16 jets from Torrejon, a base outside Madrid. The warplanes were
shifted to Italy.
   This apparently satisfied Gonzales' initial demand for a sharp
reduction in the U.S. military presence in Spain.
   Redman said U.S. and Spanish negotiators had worked hard to
resolve all the details of the agreement. ``We're happy on both
sides'' with the outcome, he said.
   Shultz also met with Polish Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski
on recent developments in the East European country. A veteran
politician and foe of the outlawed trade union Solidarity,
Miecyslaw Rakowski, was chosen prime minister on Monday by the
Communist Party Central Committee in Warsaw.
   Redman said Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead would
visit Poland Oct. 12 as part of a growing dialogue with Polish
authorities. ``We are very interested in these developments,''
Redman said.
   The U.S. official said Poland also was ``very interested in
continuing to pursue the dialogue'' with Washington.
</TEXT>
