<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrushFire 1stLd-Writethru a0724 09-28 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0724,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LYTLE CREEK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out in San Gabriel Mountains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with second fire, home destroyed, freeways
closed. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FONTANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Ana winds lashed two wildfires out
of the foothills toward housing tracts Wednesday, destroying a
home, closing schools and freeways and spewing smoke that 15 miles
away blotted out the sun.
   A blaze dubbed the Texas fire erupted at 10:30 a.m. at the mouth
of Duncan Canyon, 50 miles east of Los Angeles, and the wind also
fanned to life the embers of a controlled burn near Glen Helen that
was squelched on Tuesday, authorities said.
   The Texas blaze, pushed down from the Lytle Creek area by gusts
up to 30 mph, burned over 2,500 acres, destroying a home and
beehives, said Mary Chislock, spokeswoman for the California
Department of Forestry.
   One person, a civilian, was treated for smoke inhalation, she
said.
   The other blaze, 250 to 300 acres, was about two miles away near
Glen Helen, where authorities had intentionally been burning away
long-overgrown brush the day before, said CDF spokeswoman LoVae
Pray-Martines.
   The fires posed a threat to homes in the northern Fontana and
Rialto areas. The Verdemont Boys Ranch, a juvenile custody
facility, as well as a high school and some residents in the
northern Rialto area were evacuated.
   About 300 firefighters and eight air tankers battled the blazes.
   Marcia Nave, who lives in one of four large ranch homes in the
hills above Fontana that were threatened by fire, said she loaded
her van with jewelry, photographs and heirloom guns and waited
until the last minute to leave.
   ``We had to drive through flames. I was afraid of catching the
van on fire,'' said Ms. Nave, as tears formed in her eyes. ``I
don't know what has happened to my house.''
   The fires were burning in a semi-rural area near large housing
tracts, but Fontana police directing traffic said the winds had
shifted direction by early afternoon and that the housing
developments appeared to be safe.
   The National Weather Service predicted northeast winds through
Thursday because of the Santa Ana, a condition in which air flows
from high pressure over the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah
toward low pressure off the California coast.
   Smoke obscured the sun in Riverside, 15 miles away, and was
visible high in the sky above Hemet, 50 miles to the southeast, and
Corona, 35 miles to the southwest. Interstate 15, the main link
between Los Angeles and Las Vegas, Nev., was closed in both
directions.
   The 2,100 students at Etiwanda High School in Rancho Cucamonga
were sent home, although the school was not endangered, Associate
Superintendent Bette Harrison said.
</TEXT>
