<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Melody     09-28 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Melody,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lord Melody, Pioneer of Calypso Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY FRASER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Melody, an outstanding
pioneer of calypso music and a former composer and arranger for
singer Harry Belafonte, has died at the age of 63.
   Lord Melody, born Fitzroy Alexander, died Monday evening in the
Port of Spain General Hospital after a yearlong battle with cancer,
a city mortuary official said.
   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified,
said funeral arrangements were incomplete. He said authorities were
awaiting the arrival of three children who live in the United
States. He had no other information on survivors.
   Melody was one of the greatest and earliest professional
exponents of calypso, the lilting, syncopated musical style
indigenous to Trinidad.
   He first appeared on a calypso stage 42 years ago, said local
impressario Holy Betaudier.
   Melody often used his songs to make social commentaries and was
known for his spicy ballads. During the 1960s and 1970s, he
composed and arranged music for Belafonte.
   Out of that relationship came dozens of hits which helped spread
a mode of expression and type of music that had its origins in the
Caribbean slavery experience.
   His greatest attribute was his humor, said calypso judge Tony
Mitchell.
   ``I knew him for more than 30 years, and I think that he was one
of the greatest (composers of calypso music). His range of calypsos
is testimony to his artistry,'' Mitchell said.
   Lord Melody's humor was perhaps most trenchant and cutting
against his own supposed ugliness. In the 1950s, he was known
affectionately as ``The Boo Boo Man.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
