<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Bomb     09-28 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Bomb,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes At Syrian Army Checkpoint; Kills Five, Injures
21</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded Wednesday at a Syrian
army checkpoint just south of Beirut, killing five people and
injuring 21, police said.
   They said a red Volvo packed with explosives exploded on a
coastal highway bridge as Syrian troops manning the Khalde
checkpoint were searching it. The blast killed the driver and four
other people, police said.
   They said five Syrian troops were among the wounded.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast, Lebanon's 13th car
bombing this year. By police count, 107 people have been killed and
398 wounded in the attacks.
   The strategic checkpoint, which links Beirut with the
Druse-controlled central mountains and south Lebanon, was jammed
with traffic.
   Police said Syrian troops immediately cordoned off the area,
closing the Khalde road for an hour.
   They said the Syrians prevented Lebanese policemen from reaching
the blast scene for an investigation. Reporters and photographers
were also barred.
   The car bombing appeared aimed at discrediting Syria's
peacekeeping mission in Lebanon.
   Syria, Lebanon's main power broker, maintains 40,000 troops in
north and east Lebanon and in Moslem west Beirut and its southern
suburbs.
</TEXT>
