<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-China-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-China-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0761,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese, Soviet Ministers Set Moscow Meeting, Talk on Cambodia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Qian Qichen throughout, sted of Quian
Quichen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will
visit the Soviet Union at the end of this year in the first such
working visit since the Moscow-Beijing split of the 1960s, Soviet
and Chinese officials said Wednesday.
   The trip points to a major warming of Chinese-Soviet relations
and is expected to lead eventually to a Soviet-Chinese summit.
   A later return visit by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze to China also was planned, but no time was announced.
   Qian met Shevardnadze at the Chinese Mission on Wednesday for a
discussion of Qian's visit, Cambodia and other issues.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov later told
reporters the two ``talked a lot about Cambodia'' and called the
talks ``constructive.'' He said Soviet-Chinese discussions on
Cambodia would continue on the level of experts and deputy foreign
ministers.
   ``They (Shevardnadze and Qian) agreed that actually it must be
decided by the Cambodians, but other countries may help,'' he added.
   In the past the Soviet Union has stayed out of the negotiating
picture and insisted that China and others discuss the matter with
Vietnam.
   Gerasimov said Qian would also meet Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in Moscow and added that Moscow hopes the ministerial
visit will lead to a summit between Gorbachev and Chinese leaders.
   The two communist powers, once close friends, split in the 1960s
over ideology, leadership of the international Communist movement
and other issues.
   ``Shevardnadze mentioned that almost everybody in the General
Assembly believes the overall world situation has improved with the
improvement in Soviet-American relations,'' Gerasimov said. ``And
maybe now it is time to improve Soviet-Chinese relations.
   ``Both agreed the state of Chinese-Soviet relations also has a
very major influence on the state of the world at large.''
   Chinese Premier Li Peng indicated earlier this month that China
plans eventually to attend a summit. He said all that was needed
was for lower level talks to reach further agreement on Cambodia
and then a summit could be put on the agenda.
   China and the Soviet Union agreed in October 1985 to an exchange
of visits of foreign ministers, but set no date. The plan stalled
over China's insistence that the Soviets withdraw from Afghanistan;
reduce Soviet troop strength in Mongolia, on the border with China;
and persuade the Soviet-backed Vietnamese government to pull its
estimated 140,000 troops from Cambodia.
   Two of these issues are in the process of being resolved: the
Soviets are withdrawing from Afghanistan and Vietnam has vowed to
withdraw its forces from Cambodia by 1990. Both Vietnam and
Cambodia are communist states.
   Chinese and Soviet vice foreign ministers have exchanged visits
repeatedly in the last few years for talks on Chinese-Soviet border
issues. Qian went to Moscow several times in that capacity. He
became foreign minister in April.
   The forthcoming visit of the 60-year-old Qian, a Russian speaker
who has been posted in Moscow, marks such visit in at least 20
years.
   Former Chinese Foreign Minister Huang Hua went to Moscow in 1982
to attend the funeral of Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev, but it was
not a working visit.
   The last Soviet foreign minister to visit China was Andrei
Gromyko, now Soviet president, who went there in 1959. In that
year, then-Soviet leader Nikita Khruschev came to the United
Nations and denounced China.
   In an address before the General Assembly Wednesday, Qian asked
for an international peacekeeping force and committee to monitor an
eventual Vietnamese troop withdrawal from Cambodia and to supervise
free elections.
   He complained that Vietnam is delaying its troop withdrawal and
asked the assembly to adopt still another resolution _ its 10th _
demanding an early pullout.
   Qian emphasized that after a Cambodian solution is reached,
China is ready to join other nations in providing international
guarantees for an independent, neutral and non-aligned Cambodia.
   The Vietnamese invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and soon replaced
the pro-Chinese communist regime with a pro-Hanoi, pro-Moscow
government. During the 1975-79 rule by the Khmer Rouge, it is
estimated that about 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people died
from executions, famine and civil unrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
