<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Bomb     09-28 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Bomb,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Subsidiary Manager Escapes Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorists set off a bomb by remote
control Wednesday night in an apparent attempt to kill the head of
a Texaco subsidiary as he and his wife passed by in a bulletproof
car, police said.
   Two passersby were hurt, but executive John Buttle and his wife
Betty escaped harm, the Bogota radio station RCN said, quoting
witnesses at the scene.
   The bomb appeared to have been strapped to a fire hydrant and
was set off as the Buttles' Mercedes Benz limousine passed by
slowly in rush hour traffic, police said in a news release.
   The Buttles were on their way home when the bomb exploded about
three blocks from their house, police said. The explosion was near
the intersection of the North Highway with 127th street in northern
Bogota.
   House windows shattered up to three blocks away, witnesses told
RCN.
   Buttle has lived in Colombia more than 20 years. He is president
of Texas Petroleum, a Texaco subsidiairy.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing, but
suspicion fell on the National Liberation Army, a guerrilla group
headed by a defrocked Catholic priest. The group has been the most
active of six leftist guerrilla organizations and has targeted
American companies in the last two years.
   Last July the guerrilla group kidnapped Jake Gambini, president
of General Pipe Co., of Houston, at an Occidental Petroleum camp in
Colombia's eastern plains. The group has not made public any
demands for his release.
</TEXT>
