<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-HelicopterCrash     09-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Helicopter Crash,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Dead in War Zone Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Salvadoran military
helicopter crashed Wednesday during evacuation operations in a
northern war zone, killing all five men aboard, the armed forces
press office said.
   It said the U.S.-made Bell UH-1H helicopter crashed while
evacuating troops from the vicinity of San Francisco Morazan in
Chalatenango province, about 46 miles north of San Salvador. It did
not say what caused the crash.
   The pilot of another Salvadoran air force helicopter was wounded
by rebel fire in northern Chalatenango on Sunday, the army press
office said.
   A broadcast on the guerrillas' clandestine Radio Venceremos on
Tuesday said there was heavy fighting in Chalatenango and accused
the Salvadoran army of the ``indiscriminate bombing'' of a small
town in the province. It did not identify the town.
   The broadcast said rebel forces inflicted 22 casualties on
government troops Sept. 21-26. It did not say if there were any
rebel casualties.
   Marxist-led guerrillas have waged a 9-year-old war against the
U.S.-backed government.
   Wednesday's crash was the second this year of an army
helicopter. In January, a UH-1H helicopter crashed near San Jose
Guayabal, about 15 miles north of the capital, killing three men
aboard.
   The press office identified the dead as Lt. Oscar Arturo Monge
Vides, the helicopter pilot; Manuel de Jesus Turcios Garcia, the
co-pilot and a cadet; two artillery soldiers and an army medic.
   Also Wednesday, the armed forces press office reported that
rebel forces attacked a sugar mill in central El Salvador, killing
one soldier and wounding another.
</TEXT>
