<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Face to Face with John Cardinal O'Connor'' is
the title of a new weekly, half-hour television news magazine on
Saturday mornings hosted by the New York archbishop on WNYW-Fox
Channel 5.
   Featuring his travels and discussion with guests of various
religious backgrounds and ``heroes'' of community service, the
commercially sponsored program each time concludes with his
``thoughts for the week.''
   On the premiere broadcast last Saturday, including a discussion
of America's growing illegal alien population, he recalls his
parents' immigration to the United States from Ireland and adds in
closing remarks:
   ``I feel personally distressed that we have closed the gates of
our country to so many hundreds of thousands who came to live here
in freedom, in peace, with dignity, with liberty and justice for
all.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Southern Baptist Foreign Mission Board
says 23 more missionaries in Indonesia have been notified their
resident visas won't be renewed, bringing to 32 the number forced
to leave this year because of visa rejections.
   Those forced out are veteran missionaries, all of them serving
there more than 14 years, and most more than 20. The board says a
remaining 45 missionaries who have been there less than 10 years
presently see no visa problems.
</TEXT>
