   After protests from Baptist and Jewish
groups, seven of nine candidates running for various positions in
Sarasota County have repudiated their signing of a document
advocating that the nation officially confess ``our responsibility
to God and the supremacy of his son, Jesus Christ,'' the American
Jewish Committee reports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly published book, ``The Mormon Murders,''
explores the unusual investigative and legal maneuvering in a
1986-87 case in which document forger Mark Hoffman got off with a
plea-bargaining sentence to only five years to life in prison after
committing two murders.
   Based on months of extensive interviews in the wake of the
strange case in which Mormon Hoffman sold ingeniuously faked
documents that embarassed the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints (Mormon), the book was written by two Harvard-trained
lawyers, Gregory White Smith and Steven Naifeh, and published by
Weidenfeld & Nicolson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, the Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church bells chimed 40 times
at an ecumenical service commemorating the founding assembly of the
World Council of Churches here 40 years ago.
   Its present general secretary, the Rev. Emilio Castro, told
about 1,200 worshipers: ``We are the people of Jesus Christ, who
cannot remain quiet as long as there is injustice in the world and
who cannot rest as long as the church remains divided.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual ecumenical setting, a Roman
Catholic bishop and a Lutheran bishop jointly will lead worship
Sunday for a combined congregation here that includes both
Lutherans and Roman Catholics.
   ``We feel the visit will be an encouragement to us in our
ecumenical mission,'' said the Rev. Dale Jamtgaard, Lutheran
co-pastor of the Mission of the Atonement, one of the country's
rare Protestant-Catholic congregations.
   Scheduled for joint participation in Sunday services were
Lutheran Bishop Paul Swanson of the Oregon synod of th Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America and Roman Catholic Archbishop William
Levada of Portland, Ore.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 30</NOTE>
