<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, ADV 30,0566</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Sept. 30, and thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual ecumenical setting, a Roman
Catholic bishop and a Lutheran bishop will jointly lead worship
here Sunday for a combined congregation of Lutherans and Roman
Catholics.
   ``We feel the visit will be an encouragement to us in our our
ecumenical mission,'' said the Rev. Dale Jamtgaard, Lutheran
co-pastor of the Mission of the Atonement, one of the country's
rare Protestant-Catholic congregations.
   Scheduled to participate in Sunday's services were Lutheran
Bishop Paul Swanson of the Oregon synod of th Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America and Roman Catholic Archbishop William Levada of
Portland, Ore.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, the Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church bells chimed 40 times
at an ecumenical service commemorating the founding assembly of the
World Council of Churches here 40 years ago.
   Its present general secretary, the Rev. Emilio Castro, told
about 1,200 worshipers: ``We are the people of Jesus Christ, who
cannot remain quiet as long as there is injustice in the world and
who cannot rest as long as the church remains divided.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new book, ``The Mormon Murders,'' explores the
unusual investigative and legal maneuvering in a 1986-87 case in
which document forger Mark Hoffman got off with a plea-bargained
sentence of five years to life in prison after committing two
murders.
   Based on months of interviews in the wake of the strange case in
which Mormon Hoffman sold ingeniously faked documents that
embarrassed the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
(Mormon), the book was written by two Harvard-trained lawyers,
Gregory White Smith and Steven Naifeh, and published by Weidenfeld
& Nicolson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After protests from Baptist and Jewish
groups, seven of nine candidates running for various positions in
Sarasota County have repudiated their signing of a document
advocating that the nation officially confess ``our responsibility
to God and the supremacy of his son, Jesus Christ,'' the American
Jewish Committee reports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Southern Baptist Foreign Mission Board
says 23 missionaries in Indonesia have been notified their resident
visas won't be renewed, bringing to 32 the number forced to leave
this year because of visa rejections.
   Those forced out are veteran missionaries, all of them serving
there more than 14 years, and most more than 20. The board says a
remaining 45 missionaries who have been there less than 10 years
presently see no visa problems.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's archbishop is host of a new weekly,
half-hour television news magazine called ``Face to Face with John
Cardinal O'Connor.'' It appears Saturday mornings on WNYW-Fox
Channel 5.
   Featuring his travels and discussion with guests of various
religious backgrounds and ``heroes'' of community service, the
commercially sponsored program concludes with O'Connor's ``thoughts
for the week.''
   On the premiere broadcast last Saturday, which included a
discussion of America's growing illegal alien population, he
recalled his parents' immigration to the United States from Ireland
and said in closing remarks:
   ``I feel personally distressed that we have closed the gates of
our country to so many hundreds of thousands who came to live here
in freedom, in peace, with dignity, with liberty and justice for
all.''
</TEXT>
