<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Philippines-Rights ADV03   09-28 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Rights, ADV 03,0876</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Legacy of Human Rights Abuse in Marcos Years Haunts Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two years after President
Corazon Aquino took office with a vow to protect human rights, her
government has yet to shake off the legacy of repressive rule left
by the exiled Ferdinand E. Marcos.
   Officials say the campaign to end abuses and build confidence
among the public has been hampered by a widespread distrust of
government in the wake of 20 years of Marcos rule.
   ``It's a carry-over mentality,'' said Abelardo Aportadera of the
Human Rights Commission. ``Whenever you have government
investigating, you always hesitate.''
   Reliable figures on human rights violations during Marcos' time
and during Mrs. Aquino's years are virtually impossible to
determine because of differences in definition, poor record-keeping
and varying standards used by both the government and private
groups for confirming allegations.
   But criticism of the Aquino government's human rights record has
come not only from social activists and leftists but also from the
hierarchy of the influential Roman Catholic Church.
   In a stinging commentary in August, the country's bishops
appealed for ``more discipline'' in the military and for the
disbanding of vigilante groups established by the armed forces to
help fight communist guerrillas.
   Amnesty International and the International Commission of
Jurists have also expressed concern over unresolved human rights
violations under the Aquino administration. Both organizations have
cited an increasing number of unsolved killings of human rights
workers.
   In a report this year, another group, the church-backed Task
Force Detainees, claimed the number of human rights violations in
1987 equaled or surpassed those for 1985, Marcos' last full year in
power.
   Augusto Catelo, chief of the Human Rights Commission's records
division, said 2,016 cases have been filed since the commission was
established by Mrs. Aquino in March 1986.
   He said the figure includes cases such as financial claims from
private companies, which have been re-classified as non-human
rights cases but have yet to be stricken from the original list of
civil liberties abuses.
   But human rights groups say the government's figures are too
low. The Task Force claims that in 1987 alone, 7,444 people were
arrested without warrants. It said an additional 602 people were
tortured and that 284 people were killed or wounded in 29
``massacres'' of civilians by vigilantes, the military or armed,
private security forces.
   More than 18,000 families were forced from their homes, the Task
Force said. By comparison, the Task Force said, 7,253 people were
arrested illegally and 236 families were forced from their homes in
1985.
   The Task Force added, however, that the number of those slain by
security forces had declined sharply since Mrs. Aquino took office.
   Aportadera says differences in data-gathering methods were
behind the discrepancy. He also claimed the Task Force and other
human rights groups are quick to label reported abuses as
``violations'' without confirmation.
   ``For them, a mere report with some minimum requirement will
already be a violation of human rights,'' he said. ``In our case,
no. ... (If) there's a report of massacre, help us get the data,
the numbers, and then we put it in our file.
   ``I think it is still not that grave, the situation before and
now. I think now what is positive is we are getting cooperation
from the military and police. They are more receptive now to
integrating human rights values in the armed forces.''
   Despite government efforts to educate soldiers on human rights,
officials say, some still abuse civilians, including those
suspected of links to the New People's Army, the communist
guerrilla organization.
   Major abuses include the killing of 13 protesters at a land
reform march in Manila in January 1987, the massacre of 17
civilians in Lupao the following month and unsolved slayings of
prominent leftists, including Rolando Olalia in 1986 and Leandro
Alejandro in September 1987.
   The government's inability so far to identify or prosecute
suspects in those incidents has tarnished the reputation not only
of the Human Rights Commission but also of the country's entire
legal establishment.
   Mrs. Aquino's order for the commission to investigate human
rights violations by guerrillas as well as by soldiers has
reinforced doubts on whether the agency can serve its purpose.
   Critics of the policy say the rebels commit atrocities but
believe the commission should focus its attention on violations by
the military, police and others charged with protecting the
citizenry.
   ``Personally, human rights violations can only be committed by
government,'' said Aportadera. ``In the context of international
human rights, these atrocities that (communist rebels) commit are
crimes, common crimes falling under the purview of rebellion.''
   So far, the commission has completed the investigation of 218
cases, which were referred to the courts. In a partial review of
the agency's records, however, Aportadera says he has found only
one soldier who has been punished for a maltreatment and torture
case.
   ``The element of distrust is there,'' Aportadera said. ``You
still have some elements within government that continue the
practices of Marcos.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs Oct. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
