<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Acronymania ADV04   09-28 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acronymania, ADV 04,0492</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues AMs, Oct. 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Indonesia: Home of the Rampant Acronym</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KOPKAMTIB was abolished recently by a
KEPPRES, which created BAKORSTANAS to take its place.
   The acronym _ some would call it alphabet soup _ is alive and
kicking in Indonesia. What happened recently, in translation from
Indonesian acronymania, is this:
   The Operational Command for the Restoration of Security and
Order (KOPKAMTIB, or Komando Operasi Pemulihan Keamanan Dan
Ketertiban) was abolished by a presidential decree (KEPPRES, or
keputusan president), which created in its place the Coordinating
Agency for Assisting the Strengthening of National Stability
(BAKORSTANAS, or Badan Koordinasi Bantuan Pemantapan Stabilitas
Nasional).
   Acronyms and abbreviations are a national craze, used to
condense unwieldy phrases but serving in many other cases to
compound confusion.
   For one thing, it is common, if not preferable, to use the first
syllable instead of the first letter of words, as with KEPPRES.
   The main political party is called GOLKAR, which is short for
Golongan Karya and comes out in English as Functional Groups.
   Headline writers delight in the convenience offered by the
thousands of short forms, but to the uninitiated the front pages of
Indonesian newspapers resemble a lexicographer's nightmare.
   Acronyms also are found in telephone books and on the doors of
government offices. Standard dictionaries offer no help.
   Many say the use of acronyms first spread during the
administration (1949-66) of President Sukarno, known familiarly as
Bung Karno, for Brother Sukarno.
   During the Sukarno years, the habit was applied to English
phrases as well as the national tongue, Bahasa Indonesia.
   The term ``neo-colonial imperialism'' was cut to ``necolim.''
   A sports tournament for Third World athletes became known as
Ganefo _ Games of the Newly Emerging Forces.
   Communist China became CINKOM.
   Blame or credit for entrenching linguistic short cuts is usually
pinned on the armed forces, or the abri.
   As early as 1976, Professor Takdir Alisjahbana warned that the
influential military was coining so many acronyms that the standard
of Bahasa Indonesia might deteriorate. He said such usage added
nothing to the stock of new ideas but only increased the burden on
the memory.
   Onemagazine editor cautioned his staff about shortening jaksa
agung (attorney general) to jagung, which means popcorn.
   There are acronyms for most government departments and senior
officials.
   The president's personal assistants are aspri _ short for
``asisten pribadi president.''
   The alphabet soup is sometimes flavored with numbers.
   P3 is what people sometimes call the opposition political group
Partai Persatuan Pembangunan (United Development Party).
   Then there's BP-7 _ Badan Pembinaan Pendidikan Pelaksanaan
Pedoman Penghayatan Dan Pengamalan Pancasila.
   That's the Board for Guidance on the Means of Teaching
Guidelines for the True Interpretation and Implementation of the
State Ideology.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues AMs Oct. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
