<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Crash-MainStreet ADV02   09-28 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Main Street, ADV 02,0852</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Stock Market Crash Left No Craters on Main Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Monday, the $500 billion crash heard
'round the world, left no craters on Main Street.
   In the first hours and days afterward, there were stories of
people pawning watches and buying gold. Real estate markets ground
to a halt, and some high-fashion clothiers in Manhattan
contemplated fire sales on suspenders.
   But one year later, such doomsday scenarios have given way to
more hopeful appraisals.
   While the crash instilled caution in the hearts and minds of
investors, cut the value of many stock portfolios and eliminated
thousands of jobs on Wall Street, other damage has been limited
across America.
   The figures say the nation's wealth shrank by the equivalent of
$2,000 for every U.S. citizen on Oct. 19. But the reality was less
severe in most places.
   ``It was kind of a non-event as far as we were concerned,'' said
Doug Fairweather, director of corporate media relations for Sears,
Roebuck & Co., the nation's largest retailer.
   Even in New York, the epicenter of the market crash, officials
say the impact on state finances was negligible.
   ``New York is experiencing a revenue shortfall during the
current fiscal year, but really that is a result of changes from
the federal income tax _ not related to the stock market,'' said
Ann Doyle, spokeswoman for the state budget division.
   Charitable giving did not decline, although the rate of increase
in 1987 was 6.65 percent compared to an increase of 9 percent the
year before, said David Tobin of the National Center for Charitable
Statistics.
   Home buying and retail sales slowed in many part of the country,
but other factors _ rising interest rates and indifference to
fashion trends, for instance _ were to blame for the sluggishness.
   The shock of the stock market crash was mostly absorbed because
the loss really didn't amount to $2,000 per person. After all, most
stock is in the hands of the upper crust, not average Americans.
   ``There was an initial shock, but the other shoe never dropped
for consumers or any of the others of us,'' said Sandra Shaber of
the Futures Group, an economic forecasting firm in Washington.
   That's not to deny that there was a real crash. Her firm
estimated that household net worth _ home equity and financial
instruments such as stocks and bonds _ fell at an annual rate of
22.2 percent in the last quarter of 1987.
   However, it bounced up 9.7 percent in the first quarter of 1988
and 2.3 percent in the second quarter.
   At the time of the crash, panicky investors fled to gold and
silver, traditional havens in perilous times.
   Dennis Lemke, president of University Avenue Coin and Stamp in
Madison, Wis., said business returned to normal quickly. ``Right
now, precious metals are more in the doldrums than last year.''
   At Investment Management and Research Inc. in Iowa City, Iowa,
Lois James reported last year that the brokerage kept busy as a
number of bargain-hunters jumped into the market.
   These investors, who typically pulled $1,000 to $2,000 out of
bank savings, require a little extra hand-holding, she said last
week.
   ``They haven't seen huge gains, but they haven't seen huge
losses either,'' she said. ``When the market goes down, they get a
little panicky.''
   In Iowa, she added, the crash was not as important to the
economy as depressed farm earnings and this summer's drought.
   In Colorado, where the crash arrived on the heels of falling oil
prices, Mayor Al Sweney of Longmont said he felt the crash's impact
in the annual budget process, which he described as the toughest in
his quarter century in city government.
   ``Without a doubt, I think the stock market affects the market
for new construction, and for investors who might have been here
earlier,'' Sweney said. His city, 30 miles north of Denver, expects
to attract 1,000 new jobs this year, but believes those jobs might
have been filled and working sooner if not for the market.
   The mayor, a retired city administrator, also took a personal
hit from the crash. ``It affected the pension fund that I'm drawing
from,'' he said.
   Jim Birne, director of Career Development and Placement at the
Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania, saw the crash's
impact in the declining numbers of MBAs going to New York.
   Thirty-five percent of Wharton's 1988 class took jobs in New
York, compared to 42 percent in 1987; 17 percent of the class found
work in investment banking, compared to 25 percent a year earlier,
he said.
   ``What the crash did that is good for the students is it taught
them that industries were risky,'' Birne said. ``That was good for
us; it taught people what was going on in their own careers.''
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
