<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-28 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0573</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has taken another step in its effort to
become a leader in world economic policies by outlining a proposal
for easing Latin American debt problems.
   The proposal, detailed Tuesday at the annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, calls for some
Latin debt to be converted into bonds and payment terms on the rest
of the loans to be lengthened ``under appropriate conditions.''
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady received the plan cooly.
The plan is seen by some as a rival to the Reagan administration's
own ``Baker Plan.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has approved an amendment reducing
the number of businesses that would have to offer job-protected
leave to workers with medical problems or parental responsibilities.
   But the ultimate fate of the Family and Medical Leave Act
remained in doubt Tuesday as the Senate debated the merits of
mandating rather than encouraging employers to offer the benefit.
   The bill would require employers of 50 or more people to offer
at least 10 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave to seriously ill
employees or those with newborn, newly adopted or seriously ill
children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has passed legislation providing
$10.8 billion in new spending for transportation, as Congress
continues its rush to finish all 13 appropriations bills by
Saturday's start of the new federal fiscal year.
   The bill was approved Tuesday on a 392-13 vote, several days
after Senate-House negotiators agreed to drop a provision that
President Reagan had vowed would prompt him to veto the entire
measure.
   That language would have required airlines to pay benefits to
employees whose jobs are lost or whose incomes are diminished due
to mergers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only tax bill with a chance of becoming
law this year ran into a pair of obstacles in the Senate: a new
anti-abortion amendment and Democratic fears they would be accused
of writing an election-year tax increase.
   The bill includes relief for farmers from the federal tax on
diesel, renewal of a benefit for employer-financed education
assistance and a ``bill of rights'' for taxpayers involved in
disputes with the Internal Revenue Service.
   The bill's main purpose is to correct errors in the 1986 tax
overhaul, but lawmakers said Tuesday it might not even be debated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Drought of 1988, which withered
crops and is reducing fall harvests, now is leading to warnings of
heightened risks of soil erosion before next spring's plantings.
   Corn and soybean harvests are proceeding at a record pace in
Iowa as farmers try to prevent further damage to crops that
survived the drought, and conservationists said Tuesday they are
concerned that will accelerate the schedule of fall tilling and
other field work.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading investment firm again has regained the
upper hand in the 4-month-old battle for Macmillan Inc., with a
$2.5 billion acquisition agreement that elbows out the ardent
suitor Robert Maxwell.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.'s latest bid, submitted Tuesday,
offers cash and securities valued at $90.05 for each of Macmillan's
outstanding shares.
   Maxwell, a British publisher, also increased his bid, but the
$89-a-share in cash he offered fell short. Maxwell said he was
mulling his options.
</TEXT>
