<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-28 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0538</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electronic Data Systems has sued former chairman
Ross Perot, claiming he is violating an agreement made when he left
EDS not to compete in the same markets as his old company.
   The suit filed Tuesday in Fairfax, Va. seeks an order enforcing
a 1986 agreement in which Perot said he would not compete with EDS
for three years.
   Alleged violations include Perot's proposal earlier this year to
automate the U.S. Postal Service. After protests by EDS and other
companies, the General Services Administration suspended his postal
contract.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp., which saw a 25
percent drop in profits in the first half of 1988, has announced a
major restructuring of its pharmaceutical business that will cost
up to $400 million and force layoffs of 1,600 workers.
   The company said Tuesday it will close its Philadelphia drug
manufacturing operation, which employs about 900 workers. U.S. and
international drug sales and research, which had been the three
main units of the company's drug business, will be consolidated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld a judge's
decision to set aside a jury's verdict that the anti-nausea drug
Bendectin caused birth defects in the daughter of a woman who took
the medication during pregnancy.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here
said Tuesday that lower court judge properly rejected the
scientific testimony of a expert witness who said Bendectin had
caused the deformities to the arms and legs of Carita Richardson of
Washington.
   The ruling was hailed as a significant legal development by
Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc., the company which made the drug
for nearly 20 years before stopping production in 1983 due to
mounting legal costs from lawsuits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s heavily hyped Car Buyer's Bill
of Rights may be expanded to include a 30-day money back guarantee
on new cars and trucks, the No. 3 automaker says.
   The guarantee program is being tested until Nov. 20 in the
Washington, D.C. area, and a 30-day vehicle-exchange program is
being offered in the Denver area.
   Chrysler tried the money-back guarantee nationwide in 1982 as it
was emerging from the brink of bankruptcy. Fewer than 1 percent of
the cars it sold during that period were returned, a spokesman said
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices could continue eroding through the
year's end as world economics encourage quota cheating by members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, some
economists say.
   Economists say Tuesday's price declines, which put some crude
futures near two-year lows, were part of a predictable pattern of
gradually eroding prices through the end of 1988 as world economics
encourage continued overproduction by members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices edged lower in light trading Tuesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks fell 2.84 to 2,082.33.
   The dollar was mostly lower. Gold prices moved higher.
   Bond prices fell in a quiet session.
   Soybean futures advanced, but wheat futures finished slightly
lower.
</TEXT>
