<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WorldBank-IMF Bjt   09-28 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Bank-IMF, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brady Wants Third World Debt Solutions Acceptable To Private
Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Third World's $1.2 trillion debt should be
reduced, but only in ways that private markets find acceptable,
U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady has told world financial
leaders.
   Brady also ruled out strategies that would turn over risky loans
from private banks to creditor banks' governments and their
taxpayers, and touted the use of debt-equity swaps and other
innovative devices for reducing debt.
   ``If we embark on a course that involves the transfer of risk
from the private to the public sector, a true and lasting solution
to the restoration of sustained growth among debtor nations will
have escaped,'' he said.
   Brady, making his first appearance on an international stage as
treasury secretary, spoke at Tuesday's opening formal session of
the annual meeting of the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund. The meeting continues through Thursday.
   Most of the ministers of finance from the 151 member government
are attending the meeting, along with thousands of representatives
of banking and industry.
   Brady left for Washington right after his speech, giving no
public indication whether or not he was criticizing a Japanese
debt-relief proposal that would allow some Latin American debt to
be converted into bonds, with lengthened repayment terms.
   Brady defended the so-called Baker Plan, which calls for
providing new loans to developing countries that enact economic
liberalization policies. The plan was devised by his successor,
former Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III.
   ``The United States regards with skepticism proposals that may
appear to conform to the basic principles of the debt strategy, but
which in practice will produce only an illusion of progress,''
Brady said. ``Indeed, such proposals will make the debt problem
intractable.''
   Without singling out any idea, Brady said such measures could
weaken international institutions and prompt political opposition
in creditor countries.
   The Japanese proposal outlined by Satoshi Sumita, governor of
the Bank of Japan, first was made at the Toronto summit of
industrialized nations.
   It calls for some Latin debt to be converted into bonds and
payment terms on the rest of the loans to be lengthened ``under
appropriate conditions.'' To back up the billions of dollars in
loans, the debtor countries could set up special reserve accounts
to be held in trust by the IMF, Sumita said in outlining the
proposal.
   Sumita said the countries also would have to agree to make
IMF-backed changes in their policies to foster economic growth.
   ``It does not entail any transfer of risk from the commercial
banks to the multi-lateral financial institutions or creditor
governments,'' Sumita said.
   French Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy praised the Japanese
initiative.
   ``Efforts by countries with large surpluses are a good way to
augment growth,'' he said.
   Beregovoy also opposed shifting to governments the risky loans
made by banks.
   Mexican Treasury Secretary Gustavo Petricioli, speaking on
behalf of Latin American nations, urged rich countries with extra
money to set up funds that ``constitute an additional source of
financing to the debtor countries in order to support their growth
or carry out debt-reduction operations.''
   Speaking on behalf of Latin American nations, Perticiolo called
for an International Development Pact to help the heavily indebted
developing countries.
   As part of the pact, he said that debtor countries should follow
economic policies that emphasize growth, that international
agencies and banks should channel more money to the debtors, and
that the industrial nations should spread out payment terms on the
debtors' loans.
   The atmosphere in Berlin has been marked by widespread
demonstrations of left-wing groups. They accuse the bank and fund
of impoverishing the Third World. On Sunday, tens of thousands
marched in a protest parade. Police did not let the demonstrators
come close to the International Congress Center, where the meetings
are being held.
   On Tuesday, a bank's windows were smashed and 100 demonstrators
were arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan Bjt   09-28 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Agrees to $2.5 Billion Kohlberg Bid, Miffs Maxwell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell, miffed that
Macmillan Inc. entered into a $2.5 billion buyout agreement without
telling him, is reviewing his options for continuing his pursuit of
the publishing giant.
   On Tuesday, Macmillan accepted a cash-and-securities buyout
offer valued at $90.05 a share from the investment firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co.
   The agreement also gave Kohlberg an option to buy four of
Macmillan's businesses under ``limited circumstances,'' which were
not spelled out in the announcement. Macmillan said details would
be filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Macmillan had set a Monday afternoon deadline for submission of
``final'' buout offer. That evening, Maxwell said Tuesday, he told
Macmillan he was increasing his offer to $89 a share in cash. The
offer apparently fell short, as did Maxwell's outstanding tender
offer of $86.80 a share.
   Macmillan stock jumped $1.50 a share to close at $88.62{ Tuesday
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   A spokesman in New York for Maxwell Communication Corp. said it
was evaluating the Kohlberg offer but would not comment on whether
Maxwell planned to raise his $89 a share bid.
   Maxwell said he had asked the Macmillan board to inform him if
it received a higher bid so that he could have an opportunity to
quickly top it.
   ``I am shocked that (they) would enter into this hasty,
ill-conceived ... junk-bond financed offer with KKR without even
contacting me,'' he said in a statement.
   Macmillan rebutted that Maxwell was ``given every opportunity to
amend his bid.''
   Earlier this month, Macmillan agreed to a Kohlberg-led buyout
and then backed out when Maxwell bettered the price.
   But analysts speculated Kohlberg's latest bid would end the
auction. Even the most optimistic observers said the company was
worth little more than $90 a share.
   ``It's a bidding war, and it has become more than just an
economic question at these prices,'' said Robert Dunlap Jr., an
analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman & Co. The issue has become ``who
can eke out the highest bid.''
   Part of Maxwell's motivation in pursuing Macmillan lies in his
personal commitment to create one of the world's largest
communications concerns. He already owns major U.S. printing
operations and extensive media holdings in Britain.
   While Maxwell likely could afford to top Kohlberg's bid, ``he
said he was willing to pay a fair price, but not a stupid price''
for the company, said Bert Boksen, an analyst at Raymond, James &
Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Analysts said Kohlberg Kravis probably would break Macmillan
apart and put most of its emphasis on the company's information
services.
   The unit, which accounted for 40 percent _ or $62 million _ of
Macmillan's operating profit in 1987, has grown rapidly in recent
years. Dunlap expects the unit, which publishes directories
including Who's Who and trade magazines, can continue to grow at a
25 percent annual rate.
   If all 27.8 million Macmillan's shares were tendered,
shareholders would receive $82.05 in cash, $3 in notes and warrants
valued at $5 for each share they hold. The proportion of cash would
change if fewer than the company's 27.8 million shares were
tendered.
   Maxwell said he believed members of the financial community
``have valued the Kohlberg bid at less than $89 a share.''
   The Macmillan board approved Kohlberg's initial $85-a-share
proposal in mid-September, but withdrew its backing last week after
Maxwell raised his offer to $86.80 a share from $80.
   Macmillan has been embroiled in a takeover contest since May,
when a group led by wealthy Texan Robert N. Bass proposed a buyout
at $64 a share.
   The Bass group since has dropped out of the bidding, with its
last offer at $75 a share.
   In an attempt to head off a takeover attempt, Macmillan proposed
a financial restructuring it valued at about $64.15 a share, but
the Bass Group challenged the plan in court and won an order
blocking it.
   The restructuring would have split Macmillan into two companies
_ publishing and information services _ and paid a special cash
dividend to shareholders.
   In addition to its book publishing and information services
operations, Macmillan owns the Katherine Gibbs secretarial and
Berlitz language schools.
</TEXT>
