<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Banking-ChildCare     09-28 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banking-Child Care,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>74 Percent of Women Bankers Say Their Companies Offer No Child
Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national group of women bankers is mounting a
campaign to get financial institutions to provide child care for
employees' children, after a survey found almost 75 percent did not
offer any day care services.
   In the poll of 4,620 women financial executives with children
conducted by the National Association of Bank Women, 65 percent of
respondents said the absence of adequate day care has hurt their
careers.
   The survey indicated more than 60 percent of the respondents
spend up to three hours a week on the job dealing with children.
   ``The cost of all the lost time and unproductive time is a real
loss to the industry,'' said association President Emily-May
Richards, founder of the Richards Group, an Atlanta accounting
firm. ``What we want to do is fix this productivity problem, but it
has to be a cost-benefit situation.''
   The survey, released Tuesday at the association's convention in
Boston, indicated:
   _74.3 percent of respondents said their employer offered no form
of child-care assistance; 11.7 percent said firms offered some form
of flexible benefit programs. Just five respondents said the
employer provided on-site day care.
   _65 percent said they could have taken on additional job
responsibilities if they had adequate child care.
   _51 percent said they spend up to one hour a week at work
dealing with children and 10 percent spend one to three hours.
   _39 percent said they have children under age 10.
   _20.5 percent use licensed day care, 17.6 percent leave children
with a non-relative outside the home and 14 percent with a relative.
   Outgoing association President Evon Emerson said that because
the number of women financial executives is increasing, child care
is becoming a more important issue.
   She said women account for 70 percent of the banking and thrift
institution work force and 41 percent of its managers.
   The association estimated the average annual cost of caring for
one preschool child at $7,000.
   ``It's not going to be enough to win those people with just
salaries and job change,'' Emerson said. ``There needs to be
affordable, accessible, quality child care and we need to look at
all areas'' for financing it.
   Emerson said the association is forming a task force to study
and develop methods of public-private child care financing, as well
as lobby for child care legislation.
   The Chicago-based group, which was founded in 1921, consists of
27,000 managers, directors and officers from commercial banks,
savings and loans, credit unions and other financial organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
