<DOCNO> AP880928-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EDS-Perot     09-28 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EDS-Perot,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EDS Sues Former Leader, Says Perot Violating Departure Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM LOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The business Ross Perot has lined up for his new
company violates a no-competition agreement he made when he left
his old company, Electronic Data Systems, according to a suit filed
by EDS.
   The suit filed Tuesday in a Fairfax, Va. circuit court seeks an
order enforcing a Dec. 1, 1986, agreement in which Perot said he
would not compete with EDS for three years, said EDS spokesman Bill
Wright.
   The same agreement precludes Perot from operating a for-profit
company until December 1989.
   ``We are asking the court to ask Perot to honor this contract,''
Wright said.
   Perot founded EDS, a giant computer services firm, in 1962 and
sold it to General Motors Corp. in 1984. In December 1986, after a
highly publicized conflict between Perot and GM, Perot and three
other top EDS executives left the the company when GM agreed to pay
them about $850 million.
   The purpose of the no-competition agreement was to prevent Perot
from using ``proprietary and strategic information about EDS'
markets and services to compete with the company,'' Wright said.
   Perot ``with his public statements and marketing activities is
showing that he has no intentions of honoring that agreement,'' the
suit claims.
   The alleged violations include Perot's proposal earlier this
year to automate the U.S. Postal Service. After protests by EDS and
other companies, the General Services Administration suspended
Perot's postal contract.
   Although he had not seen the suit, Perot said, ``It really looks
silly.''
   ``All they do is spend a lot of money on legal work,'' he said.
   In June, Perot founded Perot Systems Corp. and the company
obtained a controversial no-bid contract to automate the Postal
Service. Perot has challenged the GSA's suspension of the contract.
   The Postal Service contract is just one of Perot's activities
that EDS claims violate the 1986 agreement.
   Wright declined to give other examples of how Perot and his new
company may have broken the agreement, but said, ``We don't think
it will be hard to prove.''
   ``Suffice to say, it's (violations) across a broad range of
markets EDS serves,'' Wright said.
   In July, Perot bid on a Medicaid contract, which expires in
1989. EDS won the lucrative Medicaid contract in 1976, helping the
company establish its reputation nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
