<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChryslerBuyback Bjt   09-28 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Buyback, Bjt,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Back Guarantee, 30-Day Trade Promotions Tested By Chrysler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyers of new Chrysler Corp. cars and trucks in
Washington, D.C. can get a full refund within 30 days of purchase,
and Denver buyers can trade in a car they don't like under
experimental marketing programs.
   Both promotions run until Nov. 20 and will be pumped by Chrysler
Chairman Lee Iacocca in television spots and newspaper
advertisements, the company announced Tuesday.
   They are extensions of the company's heavily-hyped ``Car Buyer's
Bill of Rights'' touted in two-page newspaper ads by Iacocca
earlier this month.
   Dealers in the two cities say they don't know what to expect,
but an industry analyst says she thinks similar promotions will
follow from other U.S. car makers as traditional cash rebates and
percentage rate deals continue to fade.
   ``The initial impact is not as influential as a rebate,'' said
Cynthia Certo, an analyst at Integrated Automotive Resources in
Wayne, Pa. ``It is a very good image-building tactic.
   ``What the automakers are saying is they have improved quality
and they're going to back it up. They're saying, `Here's the
guarantee.' The Europeans have been doing things like this for the
last year and a half.''
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Jakobowski said the company hasn't
decided whether to extend the promotion as it did in 1982, when the
company was recovering from its near-failure.
   ``We went back and looked at what we had done before and decided
this program had some merits,'' he said. ``At this point, it's
strictly a test program.''
   Fewer than 1 percent of cars sold during the nationwide
promotion six years ago were returned, Jakobowski said.
   In Denver, Chrysler is allowing customers to bring back a
Chrysler product for exchange anytime within 30 days after purchase
for exchange on another Chrysler product. The buyer can trade up or
down and pay or be refunded the difference according to the
original contract, excluding any incentives, financing and
insurance costs incurred on the first car.
   ``The area advertising on this starts (today),'' said Alex
Jannicelli, retail sales manager at Colorado Chrysler Plymouth in
Denver. ``It's a brand new thing. We don't know how it will go
over. Talk to me in a week.''
   Reaction in the Washington metropolitan area also has been slow.
   ``I guess not that many people know about it,'' said Rick Warn,
sales manager of Rosenthal Dodge in northern Virginia. His
dealership is one of 47 participating in the money back promotion.
   General Motors Corp.'s Pontiac division sponsored a promotion
offering exchanges within 30 days or 3,000 miles to California
buyers of the Grand Am in the summer months. Fewer than 0.5 percent
returned them for different Pontiacs, spokeswoman Sheila Main said.
   ``Certainly, we're evaluating the program for possible
expansion,'' she said.
   Ford Motor Co. spokesman Dave Krupp said the No. 2 automaker has
no plans for similar offerings.
   ``This is an incentive program. We have incentives in place that
we're happy with, that are proven. We plan to stay with them.''
</TEXT>
