<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Time-Warner     09-28 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Time-Warner,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Reportedly Discussed Merger Last Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.
executives reportedly came close to a $10 billion merger last month
but the deal fell through, according to an unnamed source quoted in
Wednesday's editions of the New York Times.
   The newspaper said the source, who it described as an industry
expert familiar with the talks, said a major reason the merger
talks broke down was the difficulty of reaching agreement on how to
manage the combined operations of the two media companies.
   The deal, aimed at making their companies so big that they would
be almost invulnerable to a takeover, reportedly was discussed in
detail by J. Richard Munro, chairman of Time; Steven J. Ross,
chairman of Warner; N.J. Nicholas Jr., Time's president; and Gerald
M. Levin, Time vice chairman, according to the industry expert.
   The proposed merger never was put to the boards of directors of
each company because Time's board might have rejected it, the
industry expert said.
   Spokespeople for Time and Warner each declined to comment to the
Times on the report.
   Time's stock soared by more than $19 a share last week on the
New York Stock Exchange amid unconfirmed rumors that the media and
entertainment giant was contemplating a buyout or restructuring,
but then fell $10.25 on lack of any development.
   After the stock jumped $9.62{ a share to $116.25 on Sept. 19,
Time issued a statement saying it knew of no reason for the rise in
its stock price.
   ``While it is Time Inc.'s policy not to comment on market
rumors, in view of the uninformed speculation about the company in
the last two trading days, Time Inc. said today that it is not
considering a leveraged buyout or any other transaction that could
account for the rise in its stock price.''
   Time closed Wednesday at $106.25 a share, down 12{ cents. Based
on its roughly 58 million common shares outstanding, the company
has a stock market value of about $6.16 billion.
   Warner closed at $35.50 a share, up 37{ cents in New York Stock
Exchange trading, giving it a market value of about $4.47 nillion
based on its 126 million outstanding shares.
   The industry expert quoted by the Times indicated the merger
talks began two months ago, to consideration a combination of just
the companies' cable television operations, but later expanded.
   Time is a leading magazine and book publisher, owns the Home Box
Office pay-television service and has an 82 percent stake in
American Television and Communications Corp., a cable television
operator with about 3.78 million subscribers.
   Warner owns Warner Cable, the naton's sixth-largest system, with
about 1.4 million subscribers, as well as the Warner Bros. film
studio.
   The combined Time-Warner operations would employ 30,000 people
and have annual sales of more than $8 billion, making it one of the
biggest entertainment industry companies.
</TEXT>
