<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Coffee     09-28 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Coffee,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources Say U.S. Price-Support Proposal Would Help Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sources at International Coffee Organization talks
said a U.S. proposal Tuesday on regulating supplies and prices
would tend to benefit Latin American producers at the expense of
most African countries.
   They said the effect of the U.S. proposals for the coming year
would be to transfer export market share from producers of the
cheaper robusta grade to those selling the sought-after arabica
type.
   The sources at the London talks spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The bulk of robusta production _ about 25 percent of all world
coffee grown _ from Africa, principally the Ivory Coast, Uganda,
Cameroon, Zaire and Madagascar. The biggest producer outside the
region is Indonesia.
   Arabicas are grown throughout Latin America, with Brazil and
Colombia the biggest producers. Kenya, Ethiopia, Tanzania and India
are the only significant non-Latin American producers.
   Under the U.S. proposal on the shape of the ICO's market control
plan for the year beginning Oct. 1, producers would be exempt from
reductions in export quota if the price of their type of coffee
exceeded $1.25 a pound.
   The average price of arabicas is just over $1.30 on world
markets, and robustas averaged slightly more than 90 cents.
   The U.S. plan calls for an initial 1988-89 global export quota
of 58 million bags, which would be cut by 1.5 million bags if the
ICO indicator of the average price of robustas and arabicas was
$1.15 or below any time during the year. One bag equals 60 kilos,
or 132 pounds.
   A further cut of 1.5 million bags would take place not less than
10 days after the first if the indicator remained below $1.15 a
pound.
   The indicator _ currently just above $1.13 _ is likely to be
below $1.15 on Oct. 1, thereby triggering an immediate reduction in
the 1988-89 global quota, industry sources said.
   ``Current prices levels are telling us that the brunt of that
cut would be borne by robustas if the United States has its way,''
said a trader.
   The price of this grade was certain to be below $1.25 and that
of arabicas just as certain to be above, he said.
   Robusta producers would also risk losing out under the U.S.
proposal if any quota increases took place in 1988-89, the sources
said.
   Earlier Tuesday, officials of Brazil and Colombia _ the world's
two biggest coffee producers _ said they were ready to open
negotiations with consumers on a price-support regime following
agreement on a joint position.
   The Brazilian-Colombian proposal calls for an initial global
export quota of 54 million bags for 1988-89. The aim would be to
defend an unchanged price range in the area of $1.20 to $1.40 a
pound.
   The 1987-88 ICO export quota stands at 51.5 million bags.
   According to a copy of the Brazilian-Colombian proposal, the
1988-89 global quota would be increased at fixed trigger prices to
reach 58 million bags _ balance between supply and demand _ at
$1.30 a pound.
   It would let producers of arabica coffee have a greater share of
any quota increase than those growing the cheaper robusta grade.
   All proposals presented Tuesday will be considered by a special
contact group of key ICO countries set up to try to negotiate a
price-support deal for 1988-89 by the scheduled end of the talks on
Sept. 30.
   The United States, the European Economic Community and other ICO
consumers want to increase supplies of mild arabicas in 1988-89,
because of growing demand for this grade and the record premium its
price has established over robustas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
