<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IMF-Africa     09-28 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IMF-Africa,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Leader Says Third World Needs More Say In Debt Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The finance minister for Botswana said Wednesday
that the Third World should have more say in designing
debt-reduction programs.
   P.S. Mmusi, a spokesman for African nations, also questioned
whether the United States and other industrialized countries
actually used the case-by-case approach to Third World debt.
   ``Although a case-by-case approach is allegedly used in the
design of programs, it is common knowledge that much of the work is
done in Washington and that different country programs show a very
close similarity,'' Mmusi said at the annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank.
   Both institutions devote much of their efforts to helping debtor
countries out of financial trouble. The World Bank also finances
projects to help them raise their living standards.
   Mmusi said debtor governments should become more active in
designing the programs which are the condition for aid from the
World Bank and IMF.
   Third World leaders often complain that debt-reduction programs
are too austere, requiring, for example, the elimination of food
subsidies. Rather than a case-by-case approach, many debtor
governments would like to see a general reduction of their debts
and the interest they pay on them.
</TEXT>
