<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SmithKlineRestructuring 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SmithKline Restructuring, 1st Ld-Writethru,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SmithKline Beckman Announces $400 Million Restructuring</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, Wendt said ..., to restore dropped word
``million.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. says a major
restructuring of its pharmaceutical business could save the company
$100 million a year by the end of 1990.
   SmithKline, which makes animal health care products and
pharmaceuticals such as Contac cold medicine, announced Tuesday it
was laying off about 1,600 workers as part of the reorganization to
reverse declining sales.
   Under the restructuring, the company's U.S. and international
drug sales and research will be consolidated and headed by John F.
Chappell, who has been head of the international business since
1985, SmithKline said.
   ``To create jobs in the future, we need to be a lean, low-cost
company today,'' Henry Wendt, SmithKline's chief executive officer
said.
   Wendt said the restructing could result in annual savings for
the company of around $100 million in the next two years.
   He said about half of the job losses stem from the closing of
the company's 40-year-old pharmaceutical manufacturing plant in
Philadelphia. SmithKline employs more than 40,000 workers in the
United States and overseas.
   SmithKline recently announced a 25 percent drop in
second-quarter profits. The realignment will result in a
third-quarter charge of between $375 million and $400 million
against pretax earnings.
   Nevertheless, the company said it expects 1988 earnings to be
$3.75 to $4 a share, up from a 5 percent to 10 percent anticipated
drop in 1987's $4.50-a-share profit, the company said.
   On the New York Stock Exchange SmithKline stock closed at
$46.12{ Tuesday, down $2 a share.
   If the changes are successful in handling pharmaceutical
business more efficiently than in the past, the moves will be
successful, said Richard Stover, an analyst with Alex Brown & Sons
brokers in New York. ``They have been slow in making decisions and
slow in commercializing products.''
   The company said in July it would reorganize its business
following a lackluster first-half performance. The company also
predicted that earnings for the full 1988 fiscal year would be down
by 25 percent in addition to the second-quarter decline.
   ``Our purpose remains unchanged,'' Wendt said. ``We are a
technology-driven company pursuing worldwide leadership positions
in fast-growing segments of the health care and life sciences
markets.
   ``We are positioning Smith Kline & French Laboratories, our
pharmaceutical business, to receive more focused leadership and
attention under a single organization designed to more rapidly
commercialize current products and develop and market future
products on a worldwide scale,'' he said.
   SmithKline earlier had blamed some of its problems on the
disappointing sales of its two top drugs _ Tagamet, an anti-ulcer
drug, and Dyazide, a drug used in the treatment of hypertension.
   But Wendt said at a news conference that Tagamet's recent
disappointing performance was not the cause of the shakeup.
   ``If there were strong Tagamet sales and less competition, we
would still be here today talking about these decisions,'' he said.
   With the cost of developing and introducing a new drug at about
$125 million, the company needs to market new products worldwide
and consolidate research and marketing, he said.
   The company also said it plans to issue 5 million new shares of
Beckman Instruments, a subsidiary of SmithKline Beckman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
