<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Jobs Adv02   09-28 0991</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Jobs, Adv 02,1030</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Shock Waves from Crash Could Erase More Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Battle-scarred Wall Street professionals, their
ranks thinned by last October's crash, could be in for another jolt
and more job losses.
   The shock waves sent out a year ago by the stock panic are still
being felt, as many skittish investors have stayed away from the
market. That has brought a prolonged decline in profits for the
nation's battered brokerage firms, intensifying pressure on them to
let more employees go or leave more vacant jobs unfilled.
   Some 12,000 to 17,000 people in the securities industry _ 7.5
percent to 10 percent of the work force _ lost their jobs as a
result of the Oct. 19 crash, according to some estimates. Few have
found new jobs within the industry, and some experts predict that
the number of unemployed could double before the situation
stabilizes.
   ``We're going to see more layoffs coming,'' said Perrin Long, an
analyst for Lipper Analytical Securities Corp.
   Another 4,000 to 5,000 Wall Streeters could lose their jobs by
the end of the year, he estimates. They would swell the legions of
crash victims: stockbrokers, financial analysts, floor traders,
secretaries, and back-office clerks and computer operators who
process orders for stocks and bonds.
   Much of the impetus for new job cuts could come from the big
brokerage companies' earnings reports for the third quarter, which
are widely expected to be even worse than in the previous
three-month period.
   ``They won't be good,'' said Donald McLellan, an analyst for
Fitch Investors Service Inc., referring to the third-quarter
reports. ``The longer this goes on, the more layoffs there will
be.''
   In the second quarter, results already were mixed. The overall
profit of New York Stock Exchange member firms doing business with
the public increased more than 25 percent from a year earlier, but
160 of the 386 companies lost money, the exchange said in a recent
report.
   Between September 1987 and August of this year, 9,186 former
employees of brokerage firms applied for New York State
unemployment benefits, up sharply from 3,500 applicants in the same
period a year earlier, according to the state's Department of Labor
in Albany.
   The maximum unemployment benefit in the state is $180 a week,
one of the lowest in the country, payable for up to six months.
   Those who lost jobs came from three broad categories of Wall
Street workers: clerical and secretarial, paying less than $40,000
a year; brokers and mid-level management, paying $40,000 to
$100,000; and top-level executives pulling in over $100,000.
   ``What we're seeing is an ongoing restructuring on Wall
Street,'' said Samuel Ehrenhalt, regional commissioner in New York
of the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. ``I don't think we've seen
the end of the process.''
   Mari Terzaghi, a clinical psychologist who specializes in
patients from the financial community, says she still treats many
people suffering from what she calls the ``identity crash''
triggered by Black Monday. When people develop a sense of
themselves in money symbols, then lose them because of investments
or jobs, they feel a sense of annihilation, she explains.
   ``The situation really has not gotten better,'' Ms. Terzaghi
said, noting that Wall Street types continue to come to her because
they're ``unable to re-establish a sense of control, a sense of
their self-identity.''
   At least one patient developed heart problems largely because of
post-crash stress, she said.
   Some of the big brokerage houses are trying to put a good face
on things _and if they're planning more layoffs, they're not saying.
   Merrill Lynch & Co. Inc., which cut around 4,000 people, or 8.5
percent of its work force, in the wake of the crash, has recently
started to expand in some areas, spokesman Fred Yager said.
   The expansion has been accomplished mainly through internal
transfers rather than by hiring new employees, he explained.
   ``We have a very upbeat attitude right now,'' Yager said. ``It's
become less of a crapshoot and more old-fashioned business sense.''
   Merrill Lynch is marking the anniversary of the stock debacle
with a series of investment seminars around the country on Oct. 17.
   The first big victim of the crash was E.F. Hutton Group Inc.,
which was absorbed in a merger last December by another Wall Street
giant, Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. Some 5,000 to 6,000 Hutton
employees were squeezed out by the combination.
   Since then, ``there's been a certain amount of caution or
conservatism in terms of adding people,'' Shearson spokesman
Michael O'Neill said.
   Like the other brokerages, Shearson's retail business has
suffered, but O'Neill noted growth in other areas like merchant
banking, mergers and acquisitions and European operations.
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. laid off 150 to 200 of its 11,000
employees. Kidder Peabody & Co.'s firing of around 1,000, or 13
percent of its staff, was partly due to a corporate reorganization
that preceded the crash, the firm says.
   Some brokerage houses are touchy about the layoff issue and
refuse to discuss specifics.
   ``We're not doing head counts,'' said Peter Costiglio, a
spokesman for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Some displaced Wall Streeters seem to be finding new jobs in the
industry, but not enough to make a real dent.
   Raymond James & Associates, a medium-sized brokerage firm in St.
Petersburg, Fla., was swamped with job applications from
shell-shocked Wall Street denizens after Black Monday.
   Now, though, ``the trickle-down theory is over with,'' said
Lawrence Silver, vice president of marketing services for the firm.
   Others are turning to different industries, finding jobs in
manufacturing companies, service industries and insurance companies
(usually as salesman in the latter). Attorneys, accountants and
financial analysts seem most able to transfer their skills to new
jobs, while brokers are having the hardest time of it.
   ``They're having trouble,'' said Gregory Ferrara, a managing
partner of Forum Personnel Inc.'s lower Manhattan office.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
