<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fewer Would-Be Brokers Taking Exam</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Besides throwing thousands of Wall Street professionals out of
work, last October's market crash seems to have reduced the ranks
of aspiring stockbrokers, too.
   In August, 4,894 people took the qualifying written exam for
brokers given by the National Association of Securities Dealers,
down from 6,774 in August 1987. The number of candidates normally
increases from year to year, the NASD says.
   The six-hour exam is tough: The failure rate is around 40
percent to 50 percent. There are no educational requirements, just
a $50 fee.
   It's given on the third Saturday of every month at 36 locations
around the country, and less frequently in five foreign cities.
   Successful candidates get their fingerprints taken and sent to
the FBI.
   There were about 470,000 NASD-registered brokers as of June 30
of this year, up from 450,000 on June 30, 1987. Not all of the
qualified brokers are actually practicing their craft, however.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
