<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-InvestmentClubs Adv02   09-28 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Investment Clubs, Adv 02,0214</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Crash Dampens Interest In Investment Clubs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market crash not only produced big losses but also
took some of the fun out of investing for those who do it for a
hobby.
   Interest in starting private investment clubs _ do-it-yourself
mutual funds that pool members' money mainly to buy stocks _ has
declined, according to the National Association of Investors Corp.
of Royal Oak, Mich., which helps organize the groups.
   NAIC Executive Director Thomas E. O'Hara said that since the
crash he has received about 10 percent fewer inquiries from
would-be club members. When the market was at its peak, in the
summer of 1987, his office was flooded with requests for startup
material, he said.
   More fledgling clubs also went under after the crash.
   ``We ordinarily lose about 50 percent of the clubs in their
first year. After the crash we were losing about 70 percent,''
O'Hara said.
   The collapse in stock prices drained the value of clubs'
portfolios on average 22 percent, although many clubs have recouped
at least half of those losses, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
