<DOCNO> AP880928-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Companies Adv02   09-28 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Companies, Adv 02,0708</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Corporate Finance Emerges Unscathed From '87 Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Crash of '87 may be part of Wall Street
lore, but it's already a fast-fading memory for the moneymen who
have kept corporate transactions moving.
   Mergers and acquisitions, junk-bond deals and new stock
offerings snapped back with a vengeance in the first quarter of
1988, as if making up for lost time, and have marched at a heady
pace ever since.
   Initial nervousness vanished rapidly as investors began to look
upon decimated stock prices as wonderful bargains.
   ``We essentially had a doubling up; it was the logical deal flow
from the previous quarter,'' said Les Fabuss, a senior vice
president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   From January through late September, more than $128 billion was
spent to gain majority stakes in 2,089 companies, according to IDD
Information Services. That compares with 1,981 such deals, for
$91.7 billion in the year-ago period.
   What has changed is that investment houses and brokerages have
become increasingly dependent upon fees garnered from these deals.
   ``It's become very hard to make money out of sales and trading
operations,'' Fabuss said, as the volume of stocks changing hands
in daily trading has eroded substantially.
   Despite the crash, billion-dollar mergers have been no strangers
to the marketplace, with Campeau Corp.'s $6.6 billion takeover of
Federated Department Stores Inc. topping a lengthy list for the
year.
   In the junk-bond sector, the sale of $1.07 billion of the
high-yield, high-risk bonds by Duracell Holdings Corp. _ in what
was one of the largest speculative issues of 1988 _ went off in
September without a hitch.
   In addition, experts say the junk-bond market has attracted a
greater number of players over the past year, making the market
less dependent upon the singular force of pioneer Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., which has been charged with fraud by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
   Even the crumbling of Revco D.S. Inc.'s leveraged buyout in
July, the first major junk-bond buyout to sink into bankruptcy
court, failed to send shivers through the debt markets. Instead,
experts pointed to the deal's poor execution _ sales and earnings
projections were far too rosy and buyers failed to line up to
purchase assets.
   Immediately after the crash, junk bonds, which are often used to
finance corporate takeovers or restructuring plans, plunged on
average between $30 and $80 per $1,000 face value. But by February,
new junk-bond issues again were being churned out to the tune of
more than $1 billion a month.
   In the equity markets, the number of initial public offerings
has been cut in half this year compared with 1987, but the dollar
value remains quite high. From January through August, IDD figures
show companies raised $17.1 billion in the stock market, compared
with $19.4 billion in the year-ago period.
   Size remains a handicap for some corporate dealmakers, however.
Though they typically are not represented statistically, the number
of young firms seeking to raise $20 million to $30 million in the
equity markets has dropped more than 50 percent since October 1987,
estimated Mark Radtke, a vice president at Venture Economics Inc.,
a consulting firm in Wellseley, Mass.
   In the crush to meet expenses, entrepreneurs are knocking on the
doors of venture capitalists and seeking corporate partners rather
than relying on the public.
   ``This sector has been hit pretty hard,'' Radtke said, noting
that only ``the top tier of companies'' are successfully going
public.
   Indeed, if the big guns have anything left to worry about, it's
that they might miss another good fishing expedition, if the market
tanks again.
   Articulating a common Wall Street sentiment, Fabuss noted that
``everybody's very much aware that were there to be another crash,
it would create tremendous opportunity.''
   Robert Willard, senior vice president and head of mergers and
acquisitions at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., agreed, noting
that a ``certain callousness has been built up that (another crash)
would be an opportunity, rather than something to run from.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
