<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Marginally Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
marginally higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction
to increased export demand for U.S. corn.
   But early gains were limited by selling linked to the advancing
corn and soybean harvest, analysts said.
   ``Traders are hesitant to bid up the market in the face of that
seasonal pressure,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain market analyst
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   In export news, the Agriculture Department announced that the
Soviet Union had purchased an additional 550,000 metric tons of
corn for delivery during the coming year, and Mexico was said to be
seeking 100,000 metric tons of U.S. corn or sorghum.
   The Soviet purchase was expected, Spilka said.
   ``We're just seeing confirmation of old rumors, so the market
doesn't do much with it,'' he said.
   Wheat futures rose but analysts said speculators were losing
hope for new life-of-contract high prices in that market.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.22{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to } cent higher with December at $2.86{ a bushel; oats
were } cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.47{ a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 6 cents higher with November at $8.12 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .08 cent higher with October
at 71 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with September at 80 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to
.37 cent lower with October at 39.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .45 cent to .60 cent lower with February at 49.50
cents a pound.
   Pork bellies fell the 2-cents-a-pound limit for daily trading on
Tuesday. Hog futures also closed lower while cattle prices were
mixed.
</TEXT>
