Machines, up | at 113~; Union Carbide, up | at 23~; General
Electric, up ] at 43\, and Exxon, up [ at 44].
   TW Services, which rejected overtures by the investment firm of
Coniston Partners about a possible eceived such a slap on the wrist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   The Tennessean, Nashville, Tenn., on gun control:
   Look again at that gun control vote in Congress recently.
   At issue was the Brady amendment to the sweeping drug
legislation, which would have required a seven-day waiting period
before the purchase of a handgun.
   The amendment's defeat was a shame _ but it wasn't a surprise,
and it wasn't cheap.
   Common Cause reported ... that from 1983 until last July, the
National Rifle Association has pumped $1,167,908 in political
action committee contributions into the coffers of those members of
Congress who voted against the amendment.
   The vote on the measure was 228-182. Of the 194 House members
who voted on the measure and had received no NRA money, 142 of them
_ 73 percent _ voted against the NRA's position.
   The amendment had the support of every major law enforcement
organization in the country. These groups lost a battle.
   Money talks, and in Congress and state legislatures, money
votes. The NRA money bought the NRA victory, and the people stand
helpless, wondering which PAC represents them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 23
   The Capital Times, Madison, Wis., on high school football player
injuries:
   Deerfield (Wis.) High School officials faced a tough decision
this fall. Their football team _ only three seasons ago a contender
for the state championship _ had fallen on hard times.
   Between decreasing enrollment and early season injuries to upper
classmen, the Deerfield Demons were fielding a team composed mostly
of freshmen and sophomores. That meant more than the potential of
losing games. It meant the potential of serious injuries to young
players.
   ``We've got 14- and 15-year-olds going up against 17- and
18-year-olds,'' coach Pete Christopherson said. ``What's more
important than a young person's health?''
   That is precisely the right question and why Deerfield school
officials were right to shorten their football season, even though
it means forfeiting three games. They are putting the youngsters'
welfare first, and for that, they deserve a lot of credit.
</TEXT>
