<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv28   09-28 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28,0664</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Sept. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Immersed in the Credit Society</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It grows so relentlessly that it leaves you
little time to dwell on the impact it has on your way of life, but
that impact affects you from youth to retirement.
   It is the credit society.
   Not long ago it was felt a student should graduate from college
and enter the adult world bright-eyed and raring to go. Now the
student begins with a load of tuition loans to be repaid.
   Less than 20 years ago you felt sorry for the poor bloke who had
to borrow money on the house. A mortgage was there to be paid off,
and nothing provided more satisfaction than doing so. Borrow on the
house? What a pity!
   A house today is considered a cash cow, the equity to be tapped
for what people consider essential expenditures. That's the
assumption, but you wonder when you see your neighbor borrow for a
trip to the Caribbean.
   You may recall that back in the 1960s it was customary to pay
off the car loan in two or three years. Now you take up to seven
years, which means the car might have to be junked before the loan
is retired.
   Perhaps you were one of those people who swore not to run up any
more credit card or bank card debt, since only 40 percent of the
interest _ not 100 percent, as before _ is deductible from your
income tax. Have you kept your promise?
   Or, as is likely, have you been enticed into using your credit
card by the promotional onslaught from the issuers? It's hard not
to bite, because the ``free'' offers come in the mail and over the
phone _ often at dinnertime.
   Once you applied to the bank for credit, but now the bank
applies to you. Why not? The rates they charge you on installment
loans are better than rates they can get almost anywhere else, even
if the paperwork is onerous.
   Back in 1960, consumer credit amounted to about $65 billion. By
the end of 1987 it wad reached $753 billion.
   That figure has been inflated, of course, by the declining value
of the dollar. But most of it is real growth. In 1978, consumer
installment debt as a portion of disposable personal income was
under 15.5 percent and fell close to 14 percent in 1982 and 1983.
Lately it has been in excess of 18 percent.
   Americans have a tradition of managing their credit
intelligently, but some observers wonder if borrowers will be able
to handle the new flexible rates, those that tend to rise at the
wrong time _ that is, when the economy in general is going the
other way.
   The Credit Union National Association recently called attention
to one of the newer problems in handling loans, especially for
automobiles.
   ``Imagine your surprise, even shock, when you learn your car is
virtually worthless as a trade becuase you owe more on it than the
dealer is willing to give you in trade.
   ``The reason? You probably chose longer-term financing for your
automobile _ five, six, even seven years.''
   Even more shocking are the costs involved in longer-term
financing.
   For example, an $8,000 loan at 14 percent interest for six years
would require a monthly payment of about $165. But interest over
the life of the loan would total almost $3,870, only 40 percent of
which is deductible.
   Credit is great, as you read everyday in newspaper
advertisements, hear on radio and television, and are informed by
lenders who load up your mailbox with offers.
   But it is also an expensive habit, perhaps even an addiction.
Some people are never able to shake it in a lifetime.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed Sept. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880928-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f AM-Argentina-Privatization Adv30   09-28 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Privatization, Adv 30,0794</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs Sept. 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Unions, Peronists Block Government's Plans to Sell Public
Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government wants to sell
shares in the state-run airline and telephone company as other
countries with large budget deficits have privatized ports, banks,
oil companies, car manufacturers, shipping lines and hotels.
   But with the economy in disarray, the ties that bind business to
government are not giving way easily.
   Powerful unions criticize the proposed sale of Aerolineas
Argentinas and ENTel, the phone company, because employees might
lose jobs or wages.
   The opposition Peronist Party, closely aligned with the unions,
complains about being left out of discussions in both deals, and
has erected obstacles to the sales in the Congress.
   ``I don't think either deal will be approved,'' said Peronist
Sen. Carlos Tenev, chairman of the Committee of Analysis and
Surveys that reviews the proposed sale of state companies.
   The opposition portrays the sale of state property in terms of
forfeiting the national patrimony, but the party in power believes
privatization is essential to putting the ailing economy back on
track.
   President Raul Alfonsin proposed the airline and phone company
sales with an eye to reducing the bulging budget deficit and
attracting foreign capital and technology. Plans also are being
drawn up to sell shares in the state shipping line ELMA, and divide
the train company into cargo and long-distance passenger segments,
and offer them for sale.
   The Alfonsin government also has committed itself to sell its
interests in seven petrochemical plants, and is considering an
offer by a U.S. consortium to invest $800 million over five years
to build and operate a natural gas processing plant.
   ``A few years ago, it was impossible to even talk about these
things,'' said Horacio Losoviz, director of state companies. ``I
think the perception has developed that it is absolutely necessary
to change direction, due to the economic crisis.''
   Argentina has major investments in several hundred companies,
and influences many others through import restrictions, export
tariffs, foreign exchange regulations, wage and price controls, tax
and investment laws.
   The exploration and production of oil, natural gas and coal is
controlled by the state, as is the distribution of water,
electricity and telephone lines. The railroad is state-owned as are
the main air and shipping lines, and most every port.
   The armed forces at their own factories make, in addition to
tanks and planes, explosives for construction companies, precision
gear for automobiles, farm equipment, train cars, industrial
solvents, tubes, pipes and specialty steel products.
   An estimated 2 million people work for the state of a total
labor pool of about 12 million.
   ``If Lenin were to come here, he'd feel right at home,'' said
Juan Jose Cresto, an economics professor at the University of
Buenos Aires. ``Everything is in the hands of the state.''
   It remains to be seen how much Alfonsin can accomplish before
national elections next May in which the ruling Radical Civic Union
faces an uphill struggle against the Peronists. Other parts of
Alfonsin's economic program have drawn fire for devaluing the
national currency, implementing voluntary wage and price controls
and lifting some restrictions on imports.
   The goal of the initiatives is to stem inflation, running at an
annual rate of more than 400 percent, and secure new loans to cover
the country's $56 billion foreign debt.
   But even critics of privatization concede that many things the
state operates, it does ineptly and at high cost.
   Argentines wait years to get their own telephones. Many people
register their mail _ and pay higher postage _ in the hope it will
arrive at its destination, unopened, within a reasonable time.
   Ferrocarriles Argentinos, the train company, runs decades-old
trains operated by unions that strike for reasons as minuscule as
the lack of gloves for workmen to link the wagons.
   Aerolineas Argentinas has more than 100 more employees per plane
_ 307 to 205 _ than does Scandinavian Airlines Systems, which has
offered to buy 40 percent of the national carrier for $204 million.
   Public Works Minister Rodolfo Terragno estimates that the 13
biggest state companies, which ran a deficit of $2.9 billion last
year, waste $2 billion a year by paying inflated prices for goods
and services.
   ``For 40 years, Argentina has had an economic system
characterized by the advance of the state over private
activities,'' said Alvaro Alsogaray, a former economy minister and
the presidential candidate of the center-right Union of the
Democratic Center. ``That is the cause of backwardism here.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday AMs Sept. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
