<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-28 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed On Wheat Weakness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade after a late sell-off in
the wheat market crushed a broad rally.
   Prices for future delivery of wheat plunged about 8 cents a
bushel during the session's last 20 minutes, in reaction to a
report that Taiwan had agreed to buy a total of 340,000 metric tons
of wheat from Canada over the next three years, analysts said.
   The news disappointed wheat traders who had been looking for an
increase in foreign demand for U.S. wheat, said Walter Spilka,
grain market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New
York.
   ``The wheat market just broke down late in the session and that
was enough to pull the corn market back down,'' Spilka said. ``The
soybeans, which had rallied pretty well on the day, also began to
pull back.''
   Most of the buying that had fueled the rally earlier in the day
was inspired by technical market factors, he said, adding that the
corn and soybean markets were jittery due to the selling pressure
generated by the advancing harvest.
   At the close, wheat was 4\ cents to 5{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.16 a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to 2} cents higher with December at $2.86 a bushel; oats
were 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with December at $2.45{ a
bushel; soybeans were 4 cents lower to 5{ cents higher with
November at $8.13 a bushel.
</TEXT>
