<DOCNO> AP880928-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WiretapSuits     09-28 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wiretap Suits,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Bell Acknowledges Wiretap Lawsuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati Bell Inc. acknowledged Wednesday
that it faces three lawsuits alleging that company employees
illegally tapped customers' telephones.
   The phone company acknowledged the suits in a report to the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Two fired former Cincinnati Bell employees, Robert Draise and
Leonard Gates, testified before a Cincinnati federal grand jury
earlier this month that they installed monitoring devices on
hundreds of business and private telephone lines as part of their
jobs for more than a decade, starting in 1972.
   They said people whose phones were tapped included business
executives, lawyers, police officials, a Black Muslim group and
U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin, chief judge in the federal southern
district of Ohio.
   Cincinnati Bell has repeatedly denied that it acted improperly
or that it ordered or authorized illegal wiretapping. The company
said it intends to vigorously defend itself.
   Among those who have sued Cincinnati Bell so far is Harold
Mills, a former Cincinnati police vice squad commander who retired
in January 1986.
   Cincinnati Bell said it has not been served with any summons,
but has learned that the lawsuit complaints are similar. Each suit
charges the company with having illegally engaged in wiretap
activities, violated federal and state laws, and wrongfully
intruded into the private lives of the plaintiffs.
   The three lawsuits were filed in U.S. District Court for
southern Ohio. Each suit asks a total of $112 million in damages
from the company, Cincinnati Bell said in its SEC filing.
   Draise and Gates said they told the grand jury that some of the
taps were installed on company orders, while others were ordered by
the Cincinnati police and the FBI. Only a federal judge can
authorize electronic eavesdropping.
   Cincinnati Bell has said Draise resigned as a repairman in 1979
to avoid being fired after he was convicted of a federal
misdemeanor involving a tap on a friend's line. Gates has filed a
federal court lawsuit contesting his 1986 firing as a supervisor.
Cincinnati Bell said he was fired because he was hostile and
insubordinate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
