<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Fiat,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Auto Giant Reports Higher First-Half Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fiat, Italy's largest private-sector
industrial group, said Wednesday that its consolidated pre-tax
profit rose by 21 percent in the first half of 1988 compared to the
first six months of 1987 to 2.2 trillion lire, or $1.5 billion.
   The company said group sales, boosted by the ``favorable
national and international situation,'' grew by 14.3 percent, to
22.68 trillion lire ($16.2 billion) in the six-month period.
   Senior analysts in Milan said Fiat results exceeded expectations.
   Fiat common shares rallied to 9,565 lire on the Milan stock
market Wednesday, from 9,480 lire the previous day, prior to the
company announcement as professional speculation went on a buying
spree to anticipate the satifactory results.
   IFI, the holding company of the Agnelli family which is Fiat's
largest shareholder, rose to 16,500 lire, from Tuesday's 16,240.
   Fiat, which has been investing heavily in automation and for the
takeover of Ferrari, the Italian maker of luxury and sports cars,
reported that its net indebtedness as of June 30 was around 400
billion lire ($285 million), slightly down from 424 billion lire
($302 million) a year earlier.
   Fiat posted consolidated profit of 2.3 trillion lire ($1.6
billion) for the entire 1987.
</TEXT>
