<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-28 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in lackluster trading
Wednesday as the British pound continued to draw most investor
interest.
   Gold prices also were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid of $397.75 for a troy ounce of gold, up 50 cents
from late Tuesday's $397.25.
   There was limited interest in the dollar, which traded within a
narrow range, and investors turned instead to higher-yielding
currencies such as the pound, said James T. McGroarty, a vice
president at Discount Corp.
   McGroarty said the dollar was caught between conflicting forces
_ economic fundamentals that should move it higher and the desire
of the major industrial powers to keep the currency at current
levels.
   On Monday, the central banks of several nations, including the
U.S. Federal Reserve, were reported to have intervened in
foreign-exchange markets, selling dollars to cap the currency's
rise.
   Overseas dealers said the Berlin meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank were not offering any news to
stimulate trading. Most of the top officials at the meeting were
merely calling for exchange-rate stability.
   In London, one pound cost $1.6840 late Wednesday, more costly
for buyers than late Tuesday's $1.6785. The pound also advanced
against the dollar in New York, rising to $1.6905 from late
Tuesday's $1.6780.
   The pound surged more than 2 cents against the dollar over
Tuesday and Wednesday following a better-than-expected British
trade deficit report for August.
   The British government said on Tuesday the deficit stood in
August at 1.813 billion pounds, or around $3.06 billion, the
country's second-worst monthly shortfall but down from July's
record 2.651 billion pounds.
   In Tokyo Wednesday, the dollar closed at 134.20 Japanese yen,
down from 134.58 yen. In London, the dollar traded at 134.20 yen,
and in New York, it slipped to 134.02 yen from 134.63 yen late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York Wednesday, compared with
late Tuesday's quotes, included: 1.8767 West German marks, down
from 1.8780; 1.5897 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 6.3877 French
francs, down from 6.3915; 1,398.87 Italian lire, down from
1,399.42; and 1.2212 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2205.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's prices,
included: 1.8785 West German marks, down from 1.8790; 1.5920 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5910; 6.3980 French francs, up from 6.3945;
2.1182 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1185; 1,401.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,402.95; and 1.2215 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2185.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Bullion closed at $398.20 a troy ounce on New York's Commodity
Exchange, up from $397.30 late Tuesday.
   The closing price of gold in London was a bid of $396.50 a troy
ounce, up from $395.30 late Tuesday, while in Zurich, Switzerland,
gold was quoted at $394.90 bid, down from $395.75 on Tuesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $401.64, up from $401.16.
   Silver was unchanged at $6.166 a troy ounce on the Commodity
Exchange in New York. Silver also was unchanged in late London
trading, where the metal was quoted at a bid of $6.15 a troy ounce.
