<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-28 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0792</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Advances On Tight-Supply Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices broke with the other precious metals
markets Wednesday and surged upward in reaction to forecasts for a
supply shortfall in the coming year.
   On other markets, gold and silver were mostly higher; sugar
futures fell sharply; frozen pork bellies plunged again; livestock,
energy, grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures
advanced.
   A report by leading platinum refiner Johnson Matthey PLC saying
platinum demand could outstrip supply by 450,000 troy ounces in
1989 sparked buying of platinum futures on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, analysts said.
   The British company said supplies of platinum could remain tight
for the next five years.
   Platinum for delivery in October rose $8.80 to $494.40. October
platinum had finished below $490 in the three previous sessions as
the market mimicked the weakness in gold prices.
   The main buyers Wednesday were commercial consumers of platinum,
said Richard Levine, vice president of the precious metals and
foreign exchange group of Elders Futures Inc.
   ``This indicates a lot of consumers of platinum have been
waiting for a decline (in price) to cover their requirements. There
was a lot of forward buying going on,'' he said. ``I think they'll
still be there if the market goes back down.''
   Gold futures rose slightly on New York's Commodity Exchange but
the spot price remained below $400 a troy ounce. Gold, pressured by
slack demand in light of the low inflation rate, settled below $400
one week ago for the first time in 19 months.
   Analyst Bette Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York said slight increases in gold and silver prices this week
indicated the precious metals markets were consolidating and
possibly readying for a rally.
   But Levine noted that spot gold and platinum had not broken
through their respective barriers of $400 and $500 a troy ounce.
   Gold settled 80 cents to $1.20 higher with October at $398.70 a
troy ounce; silver was 0.6 cent lower to 0.8 cent higher with
September at $6.166 a troy ounce.
   Sugar futures prices fell sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange following a powerful rally on Tuesday.
   Erik Dunlaevy, a sugar trader with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New
York, linked the market's recent volatility to players scurrying to
close out their positions on the soon-to-expire October contract.
   Sugar settled .18 cent to .40 cent lower with October at 9.46
cents a pound.
   Frozen pork belly futures plummeted for the second straight day
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as traders sought to align
futures prices more closely with the lower cash market, said Tom
Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights,
Ill.
   Hog futures also retreated, possibly on selling by traders who
were rethinking their bullish projections for the Agriculture
Department's quarterly hogs-and-pigs report, which will be released
Friday.
   The report is a tally of the hog-and-pig herd in the 10 largest
pork-producing states.
   Cattle futures were narrowly mixed. Live cattle settled .30 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with October at 71.20 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .18 cent lower to .37 cent higher with September
at 80.17 cents a pound; hogs were .33 cent to .90 cent lower with
October at 39.02 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .95 cent
to 1.23 cent lower with February at 49.02 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices ended mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, reflecting generally bullish inventory statistics from
the American Petroleum Institute, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents to 11 cents
lower with November at $14.11 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with October at 39.50 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .15 cent lower to .60 cent higher with
October at 46.17 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures ended mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade after a late selloff in the wheat market crushed a broad
rally.
   Most of the buying that had fueled the rally earlier in the day
was technically inspired, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 4\ cents to 7 cents lower with December at $4.16 a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 2{ cents higher with December at
$2.86{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to { cent higher with
December at $2.45{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents lower to 5{
cents higher with November at $8.12{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for December delivery of Standard & Poor's 500
stocks settled 1.05 points higher at 271.55.
</TEXT>
