<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Macmillan     09-28 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Macmillan,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxwell Challenges Macmillan's Lock-Up Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell went to
court Wednesday to challenge Macmillan Inc.'s $2.5 billion merger
ageeement with a major investment firm, charging that the bidding
process had been ``rigged.''
   A day earlier, Macmillan said it agreed to be acquired by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. for $90.05 a share in cash and
securities. The bid was selected above Maxwell's latest offer, also
unveiled Tuesday, of $89 in cash for each of Macmillan's 27.8
million outstanding shares.
   Presenting their arguments to the Delaware Chancery Court,
Maxwell attorneys challenged Macmillan's ``lock-up'' agreement with
Kohlberg, which they said ensured the buyout firm would reap
Macmillan's ``crown jewels'' even in the event the firm did not
acquire the company.
   A hearing was scheduled for Oct. 10.
   Under terms of their merger agreement, Macmillan granted
Kohlberg an option to buy four businesses under certain
circumstances. Those businesses include Macmillan's direct
marketing group; the diretory division, which publishes Who's Who
and other directories; the Berlitz language schools; and Michie
Co., which publishes state legal codes.
   Supporting Maxwell's challenge was the Robert M. Bass Group of
Texas, which controls 9.2 percent of Macmillan and which sparked
the bidding war for the publishing and information services company
four months ago. The Bass group initially offered to acquire
Macmillan for $64 a share but backed out when the price began to
rise steeply.
   ``Bass seeks the right to choose for itself between the
competing offers, and the lock-up denies us of that ability,'' said
Josy Ingersoll, an attorney for Bass in Delaware.
   In filing a motion to intervene in Maxwell's case, Bass charged
that Macmillan directors ``breached their fiduciary duty to Bass
and other shareholders by granting the lock-up,'' Ingersoll said.
   Maxwell initially had filed suit challenging Macmillan's
``poison pill'' plan, which makes an unwanted takeover
prohibitively expensive. That suit was amended to include Maxwell's
request to block the lock-up agreement.
   Maxwell, head of Maxwell Communication Corp., had asked
Macmillan to conduct a fair auction, and ``thus far the auction has
been rigged,'' said Maxwell attorney Dennis Kelleher at the hearing.
   In addition to allegations that Macmillan had tied up its best
businesses, Maxwell has complained that Macmillan failed to honor
his request that he have an opportunity to top any bid the company
received.
   ``I am shocked that (they) would enter into this hasty,
ill-conceived ... junk-bond financed offer with KKR without even
contacting me,'' he said in a statement Tuesday.
   Maxwell said he believed members of the financial community
``have valued the Kohlberg bid at less than $89 a share.''
   In mid-September, the Macmillan board approved Kohlberg's
initial $85-a-share proposal but withdrew its backing last week
after Maxwell raised his offer to $86.80 a share from $80.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
