<2ND_LINE>AM-Manville,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge OKs $82.75 Million In Manville Settlements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York bankruptcy judge on Wednesday approved
an additional $82.75 million in out-of-court settlements reached by
Manville Corp. with 15 insurance carriers in asbestos-related cases.
   The cases involve asbestos-related coverage provided to Manville
from July 1980 to July 1983.
   Manville already had won bankruptcy court approval of more than
$770 million in out-of-court settlements with insurance carriers
for other asbestos-related coverage. The latest settlements bring
the total of such insurance settlements for Manville so far to more
than $850 million.
   Manville has been operating under federal bankruptcy law
protection since August 1982.
   Its reorganization plan requires insurance funding of $615
million to fund the Manville Personal Injury Settlement Trust,
established to compensate people who have or will become ill from
exposure to asbestos.
   Insurance proceeds in excess of the $615 million will go to the
Asbestos Property Damage Trust.
   The company cannot consummate its reorganization plan until one
remaining appeal, currently pending in the U.S. Supreme Court, is
exhausted.
</TEXT>
