<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 1922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AudiSuit     09-28 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Audi Suit,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys Start Again in Battle Over Audis, Sudden Acceleration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Audi of America Inc. and 300,000
Audi 5000 owners were back at the starting gate Wednesday, in court
on a legal fight over allegations of sudden acceleration.
   ``We're back to square zero,'' said Jerold S. Solovy, a Chicago
lawyer representing Audi.
   To settle a class-action lawsuit, Audi had agreed to give a
credit ranging from $300 to $2,000 toward the purchase of a new
Audi, but Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas R. Rakowski rejected the
agreement on Aug. 11, saying people would only benefit if they
bought another car.
   Audi has now declared that rather than negotiate further, it
will defend itself at a full trial that attorneys said may not
start for a few years.
   The Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based consumer group,
contends that 402 people have been injured and five have been
killed in at least 1,650 accidents in which an Audi 5000 surged
after being shifted from park into gear. Audi denies there is
anything wrong with the cars.
   Attorneys representing as many as 300,000 former and current
Audi 5000 owners are seeking compensation from the company, saying
bad publicity over sudden acceleration has reduced the car's resale
value.
   Wednesday's court hearing was mostly a procedural matter in
which Rakowski asked attorneys to draft motions on how many people
should be covered in the new class of plaintiffs.
   Some attorneys will ask Rakowski to include people who say they
were injured or had property damaged by Audi 5000s that suddenly
accelerated.
   ``Personal injury claims are not suited to class-action
treatment,'' Solovy said. ``I predict it will go down in flames.
   ``The class would have been much better served if the settlement
was approved,'' he said.
   The next hearing date was not set but is not expected for months.
   Audi, based in Troy, Mich., defends the Audi 5000.
   ``It's a good car. It's a safe car. Everyone should buy it,''
Solovy said. ``It's a silly case. If the federal government doesn't
think this is an unsafe car, how will plaintiffs prove it?''
   Robert F. Lisco, one of the chief attorneys representing current
and former car owners, does not believe people who claim personal
injury or property damage should be part of the lawsuit.
   ``I think it will cause more problems than it solves,'' Lisco
said.
   The Cook County case involves cars built between 1978 and 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
