<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewCigarette     09-28 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Cigarette,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brown & Williamson to Import Danish Cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. will
apparently become the first major U.S. cigarette company to import
a brand for distribution when it test-markets a Danish product in
Arkansas.
   The ``full-flavored, non-menthol'' cigarette will be sold under
the brand name Prince and will be available in Little Rock, Ark.,
beginning next Monday. The price will be the same as for other
Brown & Williamson brands.
   Prince, made by Scandinavian Tobacco International, is sold in
30 countries.
   Brands sold in the United States by the nation's two largest
cigarette makers _ R.J. Reynolds and Philip Morris _ are made
domestically, company spokesmen said.
   Brown & Williamson decided to introduce the cigarette in the
United States because consumers are looking for new products, said
B&W spokesman Michael Bateman.
   Prince, which also comes in a ``light'' version, is aimed at
smokers who want a name-brand cigarette and is promoted as the
``cigarette that doesn't cut corners on taste.''
   B.A.T Industries PLC of Britain is the parent of both
Scandinavian Tobacco and Brown & Williamson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
