<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Caterpillar-Deere-UAW     09-28 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Caterpillar-Deere-UAW,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Contract Deadlines Loom With Caterpillar and Deere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor negotiators for heavy machinery giants
Caterpillar Inc. and Deere & Co. are trying to replace separate
contracts that expire simultaneously at midnight Friday, and avert
a strike by more than 30,000 United Auto Workers members in seven
states.
   Even as tentative local contract agreements were reached
Wednesday in York, Pa., Memphis and Denver, strike preparations
were under way at Caterpillar sites at 12 cities in Illinois, Iowa,
Colorado, Tennessee and Pennsylvania.
   ``I've got my picket line duty roster made out, my picket duty
captains scheduled for 42 shifts and our picket signs ready,'' said
Paul Mantzke, vice president of UAW Local 145, which represents
Caterpillar workers in Aurora.
   Mantzke said his 2,445 members are opposed overwhelmingly to any
contract extension and are getting restless as the deadline
approaches.
   ``I'd say we're going to be going out,'' he said.
   ``People here are getting ready for a strike,'' said Ed Woker at
Local 751 in Decatur, which represents 1,978 union members. ``It's
the only recourse we have. Negotiations have gone on long enough.
Maybe they need something to knock them off dead-center.''
   The rank and file has authorized a strike if no new agreement is
reached by midnight Friday. A walkout would idle 17,500 union
workers at Caterpillar.
   Caterpillar, the world's biggest maker of earth-moving
equipment, employs nearly 59,000 people worldwide.
   ``At this point, we still believe there's a good chance we can
reach an agreement by Friday,'' said Caterpillar spokesman Mark
Polzin. ``We intend to keep meeting and we are working toward that
end. The two parties continue to come together in good faith.''
   In Moline, union negotiators expressed confidence that a
settlement with Deere was imminent.
   UAW negotiator Jim Hecker said Tuesday he was optimistic an
agreement would be reached by Friday. He said the strike
authorization by Deere's union members was a routine part of the
negotiating process.
   ``We're at the proper point we should be at this stage in the
negotiations,'' Hecker said.
   Deere spokesman Robert Combs declined comment on the status of
talks.
   ``There's not much to say,'' Combs said. ``The two parties are
meeting all week and continue to meet on a regular basis.''
   Negotiations with Deere, the giant of farm tractor and
agricultural implement manufacturing, have been underway steadily
since Aug. 11.
   The Deere talks affect about 13,400 active employees, and 4,000
laid-off workers, at 11 cities in Illinois, Iowa, Minnesota,
Colorado and Georgia. Deere employs about 38,000 people worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
