<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Galanis-Sentencing     09-28 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Galanis-Sentencing,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Shelter Promoter Gets 27 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tax shelter promoter John Peter
Galanis was sentenced Wednesday to 27 years in prison for
masterminding multi-million dollar fraud and racketeering schemes
from coast to coast.
   A federal court jury on July 5 convicted Galanis, 45, formerly
of Greenwich, Conn. and now of Del Mar, Calif., on 44 various
counts of participating in a racketeering enterprise that looted
banks, fleeced investors and defrauded the government of taxes.
   In a prepared statement for the court, Galanis admitted he was
responsible for what happened.
   ``My arrogance did not allow me to fully examine the events
through another's eyes,'' he said. ``I thought of myself as a kind
man, imparting good values, not a racketeer.''
   The government in a lengthy presentence report contended Galanis
``directed a sophisticated criminal enterprise, consisting of a
cohesive group of associated individuals and entities...whose
activities defrauded investors, financial institutions and the
public'' of $150 million in a series of schemes over a period of
years.
   Galanis took most of the money ``to support the extravagant
lifestyle to which he had become accustomed during his decades of
unrelenting criminal activities,'' the report said, and learned no
lesson from a previous conviction of conspiracy to violate
securities laws.
   ``This sentence, which is, in my experience, the heaviest yet
imposed for white collar crime, sends precisely the right message
to wealthy and privileged crooks who cheat to make additional
millions upon millions,'' U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani said after
sentencing.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Brieant sentenced Galanis, who had
faced a maximum penalty of 207 years in prison and $8 million in
fines.
   Brieant last week sentenced Galanis' co-defendant, Anthony
Marchese, 48, of Southport, Conn., to 20 years in prison.
   The judge agreed to allow Galanis to remain free on $20 million
bond, over the government's objections.
   Galanis allegedly masterminded a phony oil- and gas-drilling tax
shelter scheme that netted more than $172 million in fraudulent tax
writeoffs for about 2,500 investors.
   The so-called ``Galanis organization'' also left a Rockland
County bank insolvent, fraudulently took over a Westport, Conn.
bank, forced Utah banking officials to take over another financial
institution in Salt Lake City, and stole $3.9 million from three
California mutual funds.
   The Galanis organization allegedly bribed officials of the
Peoples National Bank of Rockland County in Monsey, N.Y.,
fraudulently took over Heritage Bank in Salt Lake City, seized
control of Columbia Federal Savings Bank in Westport, Conn. through
fraudulent misrepresentations to federal regulators and illegally
took over ISI Mutual Funds in Oakland, Calif. and stole $4 million
in mutual fund assets.
   Peoples National Bank collapsed in 1985 and was taken over by
the First National Bank of Highland Falls while in 1987 Heritage
Bank came under the control of the state of Utah.
   Eleven other people pleaded guilty for their roles in Galanis'
various schemes and nine testified against him, said assistant U.S.
Attorney Vincent Briccetti.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
