<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Hunt-Yemen     09-28 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hunt-Yemen,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Summary Judgment In Favor Of Hunt Oil In North Yemen
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dallas judge summarily ruled in favor of Hunt
Oil Co. Wednesday in a $1 billion suit accusing the company of
scheming to deprive other oil companies of oil and gas concessions
in North Yemen.
   Arabian Shield Development Co. of Dallas and Dorchester Master
Limited Partnership of Houston filed the suit against Hunt Oil,
Chairman Ray L. Hunt and Yemen-Hunt Oil Co. last October.
   Arabian Shield is an energy and mineral company controlled by
Dallas businessman Jack Crichton and some Saudi princes.
   Crichton alleged Hunt and his partners in 1981 acted wrongfully
to deprive the plaintiffs of an exclusive contract to explore and
produce oil and gas in a 140,000-square-mile tract in the Middle
East nation and to win the rights for themselves.
   The Hunts accused Crichton and his partners of filing a baseless
suit to achieve economic rewards they were unable to win through
direct negotiations with the Yemeni government.
   A motion for summary judgment was filed in July by the Hunt firm
and heard in August by 116th District Court Judge Frank Andrews.
   ``We feel the decision by the court to grant our motion for
summary judgment is a total and unqualified vindication,'' Ray Hunt
said in a news release.
   Hunt noted that several weeks after the suit was filed the Yemen
Arab Republic government officially refuted the allegations.
   Ray Hunt is half-brother to Nelson Bunker Hunt, William Herbert
Hunt and Lamar Hunt, but operates a separate energy and real estate
empire. He is not involved in the three Hunt brothers' financial
travails.
   Andrews also ruled the defendants were entitled to recover all
legal costs incurred in the suit.
   Crichton, 47, was a personal friend of Hunt's late father, H.L.
Hunt, and a former board member of the Hunt family foundation.
   Arabian Shield and Dorchester plan to appeal the judgment in 30
days, according to a statement issued by Arabian Shield.
   ``This is only the first round in a fight in which Dorchester
and Arabian Shield intend to pursue until Arabian Shield-Dorchester
have recovered the damages suffered...from the illegal actions of
Hunt Oil Company in securing the oil production sharing agreement
in North Yemen,'' the statement said.
   The Alif Field was developed in North Yemen in 1984 by Hunt Oil.
   The plaintiffs claimed Crichton and several associates first
found evidence of oil reserves in North Yemen in 1955 and signed an
agreement with the governement. But political turmoil, including a
lengthy civil war, prevented development of the tract.
   An updated agreement negotiated in 1981 by Dorchester and
Arabian Shield _ the legal successors to the parties given the 1955
contract _ was awaiting final approval of the North Yemeni
government when it suddenly was canceled, the suit said.
   Hunt Oil, through its Yemen-Hunt Oil Co. subsidiary, then was
awarded a contract for rights to the tract in September 1981, the
suit alleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
