<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Zenith-Brookhurst     09-28 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Zenith-Brookhurst,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Zenith's Motion to Dismiss Brookhurst's Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court judge on Wednesday
dismissed a motion that would have given a group of dissident
shareholders leverage to depose Zenith Electronic Corp.'s board of
directors.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph J. Farnan dismissed the challenge
from Brookhurst Partners because he said federal court did not have
jurisdiction over the subject matter.
   Brookhurst spokesman Tom Franco said the group would sue Zenith
in Delaware state court, ``which we believe to be the correct
forum.''
   Brookhurst is seeking shareholder support to dump seven of
Zenith's 10 directors, trim the board to six members and fill three
of those seats with nominees committed to selling the television
and computer maker.
   Brookhurst had asked the court to strike down a company bylaw
that requires approval from all shareholders _ not just a majority
_ for such a move.
   Zenith, which is incorporated in Delaware but based in Glenview,
Ill., unilaterally agreed Monday to such a change. But Franco said
the company's action was not enough, and Brookhurst still was
seeking access to the company's shareholder lists and financial
records.
   ``There are other claims and we believe that they remain worthy
of the court's consideration,'' Franco said in a telephone
interview Wednesday night. ``We're hopeful that there will be a
prompt resolution of the remaining claims.''
   Franco said the group would file a motion Thursday in Delaware
Chancery Court seeking to exempt Brookhurst's solicitation from
Zenith's ``poison pill'' takeover defense.
   The plan now gives Zenith the right to dilute its holdings if
any one shareholder gains consent for change from 15 percent of the
shares.
   Brookhurst is a limited partnership that owns 6.1 percent of
Zenith stock, which makes the group the company's largest
stockholder.
   Zenith stock rose 50 cents to $20.62{ a share Wednesday in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
